<FIRST>u i AM-Cambodia     02-16 0492</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cambodia,0508</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cambodia Resistance Accuses Government of Intransigence in Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ENG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cambodian guerrilla leaders met
Thursday with senior officials in the Phnom Penh government and
charged the officials with merely engaging in a public relations
exercise in entering peace talks.
   The Cambodian officials and the three factions of the resistance
coalition held a 45-minute session apart from their larger meeting
with other Southeast Asian countries.
   The Cambodian officials ``maintained the same rigid attitude
which is not conducive to a comprehensive settlement of the
Kampuchean (Cambodian) problem,'' the coalition said in a statement.
   ``The plan proposed by the other side is tantamount to asking the
(resistance) to capitulate to a regime installed by foreign
forces,'' the statement said, adding that the government was only
engaging in a public relations exercise.
   The meeting is aimed at ending the war that began after
Soviet-armed Vietnam invaded Cambodia in late 1978. Vietnamese
forces since have battled the guerrillas backed by China and the
Association of Southeast Asian Nations.
   The guerrilla leaders said a solution was possible only on the
basis of a plan proposed by resistance leader Prince Norodom
Sihanouk. Phnom Penh rejected that plan even before the talks began.
   Resistance spokesman Thiounn Prasith read the statement aloud at
a news conference after a 10-minute monologue in which he railed
against Vietnam and the ``illegal'' Cambodian regime it was
``manipulating.''
   He denounced Vietnam for not allowing international supervision
of its troop withdrawal and claimed that about 20,000 Vietnamese
soldiers recently have disguised themselves in Cambodian uniforms.
   Vietnam in January said it will end its 10-year military
incursion in Cambodia by the end of September.
   Phnom Penh's representative, Hor Nam Hong, appeared at the same
news conference, insisting his side fervently desires a settlement.
   The organizer of the talks, Indonesian Foreign Minister Ali
Alatas, said that at the plenary session, the officials discussed
the Vietnamese withdrawal, an end to foreign military aid to the
guerrillas, and a mechanism for supervision and control of any
agreement.
   The session brought together Vietnam, its ally Laos, the Phnom
Penh government, the resistance, and the members of ASEAN: Thailand,
Indonesia, Malaysia, the Philippines, Singapore and Brunei.
   A first round of talks, held in July, achieved no breakthroughs
but resulted in a consensus that Vietnam's withdrawal must be linked
to measures preventing the return to power of the Khmer Rouge, which
killed hundreds of thousands of people in Cambodia before Vietnam
toppled it.
   The communist Khmer Rouge is allied in the guerrilla coalition
with the forces of Sihanouk and Son Sann.
   Sihanouk, widely seen as the central figure in any future
Cambodian government, is boycotting the talks because Phnom Penh
rejected his peace plan.
   The plan included calls for dissolution of the Phnom Penh
government before a general election; introduction of an
international peace-keeping force to guarantee any settlement; and
specifics from Vietnam on its pledge to withdraw its troops from
Cambodia.
</TEXT>
