<FIRST>u w AM-HijackingSuspect     02-16 0144</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hijacking Suspect,140</SECOND>
<HEAD>Trial Delayed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The trial of a Lebanese hijacking suspect that
was to have started Thursday has been postponed because the judge
suffered a mild heart attack.
   U.S. District Judge Barrington D. Parker, scheduled to preside at
the trial of Fawaz Younis, is listed in guarded condition in the
coronary care unit at Howard University Hospital. He was admitted
Wednesday.
   Prospective jurors have been told to telephone the courthouse
next Wednesday to learn when the case will go forward.
   Younis has been awaiting trial since September 1987 when he was
lured aboard an FBI chartered yacht in the Mediterranean.
   Younis is charged with leading the June 1985 hijacking of a
Jordanian airliner that was carrying several American passengers.
The plane was blown up at Beirut international Airport after
passengers and crew members were allowed to leave the aircraft.
</TEXT>
