<FIRST>r i PM-Czechoslovakia-Arms     02-16 0232</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Czechoslovakia-Arms,0237</SECOND>
<HEAD>Military Production at Arms Plant To Be Cut by Half</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government says
Czechoslovakia's largest armarments plant will halve its military
production this year and increase its turnout of heavy equipment for
civilian use.
   The official CTK news agency said Wednesday that the cuts are
linked to recent disarmament initiatives by Czechoslovakia and other
East bloc countries that follow Moscow's lead in announcing cuts in
military manpower and spending.
   While halving its military production, the plant at Martin in
western Slovakia will make more equipment for civilian use, such as
construction and road-building machinery, CTK quoted company
director Jozef Uhrik as saying.
   Czechoslovakia last month announced it would cut defense spending
by 15 percent and trim its armed forces by 12,000 men in the next
two years. The cuts are also to include the scrapping of tanks and
other hardware.
   According to NATO figures, Czechoslovakia has about 145,000
troops.
   In December, Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's said 50,000
Red Army troops would be withdrawn from East Germany, Czechoslovakia
and Hungary by the end of 1990. Poland, East Germany and Hungary
have also announced troop cuts.
   While the Warsaw Pact cuts seem designed to boost new East-West
talks next month in Vienna on reducing conventional arms and forces
across Europe, they also benefit the East's Communist governments by
freeing up funds for sorely needed economic reforms.
</TEXT>
