<DOCNO> AP890216-0011 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-16-89 0037EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-ParaguayanMuckraker Bjt   02-16 0678</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Paraguayan Muckraker, Bjt,0697</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crusading Newspaper Plans Comeback After Coup</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELIZABETH LOVE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ASUNCION, Paraguay (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The owner and editor of the popular and
award-winning newspaper ABC Color began planning its first edition
in nearly five years as soon as he heard Gen. Alfredo Stroessner had
been ousted.
   ``We're going to come out with the same kinds of stories that
prompted them to shut us down before _ corruption, narcotics
trafficking, and the violation of human rights,'' said Aldo
Zuccolillo.
   Warming to the subject, the 59-year-old journalist added, ``We
want to become permanent reminders to Gen. Rodriguez of the promises
he made when he assumed power.''
   Gen. Andres Rodriguez toppled Stroessner on Feb. 3 and almost
immediately gave Zuccolillo permission to resume publishing ABC
Color as he promised to respect freedom of the press and human
rights.
   The newspaper, best known for its investigative stories, was once
the most widely read daily in this South American capital of 900,000
people.
   ``I am certain that Gen. Rodriguez will not ask me nor anyone to
refrain from publishing an article because he doesn't like it, ''
said Zuccolillo, who founded ABC Color in 1967.
   Zuccolillo frequently clashed with Stroessner and his aides,
enduring threats, arrests and, finally, closure of the
80,000-circulation paper by plainclothes police in March 1984. The
stated reason: the paper was provoking class hatred among
Paraguayans.
   In preceding years, seven ABC Color journalists were arrested,
and one expelled. Zuccolillo himself was jailed twice, the first
time for 11 days, the second for a week.
   He says he's sure that won't happen again: ``Now, we'll no longer
have the overnight bags that we kept behind the doors in the
newsroom in case the police came and took us directly to jail.''
   The new issue, to hit the street in about a month, will differ
little from editions in the past that won citations from, among
other, the InterAmerican Press Society. Three years ago, Zuccolillo
was awarded the prestigious Maria Moors Cabot Prize from Columbia
University's journalism school.
   ``We're going to investigate everything. We have the staff and
the sources of information,'' Zuccolillo said. ``Now you're going to
begin to see news sources appear that in other times would hide
because they were scared to death.''
   In the days following the coup, Zuccolillo saw a constant stream
of foreign reporters who tried to get a better handle on Paraguayan
politics from a veteran observer.
   ``I think Gen. Rodriguez has no other option than to fulfill his
promises,'' said Zuccolillo. ``The Paraguayan people are totally fed
up with Stroessner and Streossnerism.''
   Zuccolillo said hard work and skill, not luck, had kept
Stroessner in power for nearly 35 years.
   ``Stroessner had a great Machiavellian political talent to
achieve his objectives,'' Zuccolillo said. ``He was a planner, he
was very intelligent, he had a great power of synthesis and an
extraordinary memory, but he also was immoral, unscrupulous,
bloodthirsty and a corrupter.''
   Zuccolillo, who broke with Paraguayan tradition by forbidding his
journalists to accept government payoffs, plans to trace just how
corrupt his former nemesis was.
   ``The first clues are going to come from outside, from
Switzerland,'' he said. ``I already have a couple of Swiss
journalists who are willing to help me, and I'm going to send a
couple of reporters from here ... when I get some money together.''
   Investigative reports published by ABC Color in the past alleged
that by overcharging gasoline sold by the private oil company
Refineria Paraguaya S.A., Stroessner bilked the country of about
$800 million over five years in the 1970s.
   ``Stroessner might barely have a $10,000 bungalow (in Paraguay),
but he has well over a billion dollars overseas,'' claimed
Zuccolillo. Stroessner was exiled to Brazil, where he is said to own
a home.
   Zuccolillo dismisses the reservations some have that the
Rodriguez government may become the equivalent of ``Stroessnerism
without Stroessner.''
   ``You can't have Stroessnerism without Stroessner if you have a
free press,'' he said. ``A free press is the antidote of the people
against totalitarianism.''
</TEXT>
