<FIRST>u a AM-BethesdaShootings 3rdLd-Writethru a0776 02-16 0635</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bethesda Shootings, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0776,460</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS in first 14 grafs with gunman reported to be former mental
patient; Also CORRECTS spelling of Ludington thruout; picks up 9th graf
pvs, Another employee.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Gunman Kills Three Others, Self in Washington Area</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BETHESDA, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former mental patient described as a
``disgruntled employee'' shot three women co-workers to death and
killed himself at the office of a savings and loan association
Wednesday, police said.
   The gunman was identified as Emanuel Tsegaye, 33, of Silver
Spring, Md., police said.
   A spokesman for the Maryland State Health Department said Tsegaye
had been released about a year ago after five years at the Clifton
T. Perkins Hospital Center in Jessup, Md. Tsegaye was sent to the
mental hospital after he was ruled criminally insane following his
arrest on charges of assaulting a police officer.
   Two victims have also been identified by police as Cynthia
Mitchell, 28, of Landover, Md., and Tanya Walker, 23, of Fort
Washington, Md. The names of the other victims were were not
immediately released.
   Police in this Washington, D.C., suburb said the three people
killed in addition to Tsegaye were all female employees at Chevy
Chase Federal Savings Bank.
   Tsegaye also wounded Edward Johnson, 22, of Silver Spring, Md.,
police said. Johnson, who was shot in the jaw, is in critical
condition at Suburban Hospital following surgery.
   According to Montgomery County police spokesman Officer George
Ludington, Tsegaye got off an elevator at the credit card department
of the S&amp;L at the end of the lunch hour, walked down a hallway and
through a set of double doors, and shot Johnson and one of the women.
   The Ethiopian native then went into a nearby lunchroom and killed
the other two women, Luddington said.
   Tsegaye then turned his .38-caliber revolver on himself,
Ludington said.
   ``It happened very quickly,'' Ludington said. He described the
gunman as a ``disgruntled employee.'' A fellow worker said the man
was a collector in the credit card department.
   ``All of the people that I have talked to about it are very
disturbed, very surprised by it ... because all indications were
that Mr. Tsegaye was doing very well,'' Mike Golden, spokesman for
the state health department, told WUSA-TV.
   The station said Tsegaye had originally been arrested after
approaching a Montgomery County police officer and saying, ``I want
to die, kill me,'' and then reaching for the officer's gun. He was
charged with attempted murder in that case, according to the
television report.
   A Montgomery County police official said late Wednesday they
would not release any details about Tsegaye's background.
   Another employee, Dean Abellano said he was sitting next to
Johnson when Tsegaye came into the office.
   ``First he shot Ed and then I went under my chair,'' he said.
Abellano, who was not injured, said Tsegaye had had an argument with
a co-worker earlier in the day. He said that person was not injured.
   Alex Chapin, of Atlanta, who was on the telephone with an
employee of the S&amp;L when the shootings occurred, said he heard
screaming in the background.
   ``I hear a banging at the door and ... I heard somebody say,
`Don't let him in, don`t let him in,' Chapin said in a telephone
interview. ``And then ... I hear another scream and I hear another
shot. ...
   ``Out of horror, I'm sitting here listening to the phone, 'cause
I don't know if it's a hostage situation going on or what. And I
waited and waited and waited until I heard the police sirens, so I
figure somebody's on the scene at that point. Then I heard somebody
say something, `Why don't they come up here?' and that's when I
heard some more shooting and then the phone went dead,'' he said.
</TEXT>
