<FILEID>AP-NR-02-16-89 0209EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Justice-CivilRights Bjt   02-16 0790</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Justice-Civil Rights, Bjt,780</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Seeks Rights Chief to Reverse Reynolds' Policies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The four top candidates for the Justice
Department's chief civil rights job all would sharply change the
controversial policies that William Bradford Reynolds followed for
the last eight years.
   A leading candidate is Evan Kemp Jr., a disabled-rights advocate
who publicly battled Reynolds over a proposal to reduce
anti-discrimination protection for handicapped people.
   Kemp, a member of the Equal Employment Opportunity Commission, is
being considered for the post of assistant attorney general in
charge of the Justice Department's civil rights division, said
administration sources.
   Confined to a wheelchair, Kemp has been an advocate for
handicapped Americans and once successfully sued the Securities and
Exchange Commission after being told his disability would bar his
promotion to supervisor.
   Also under consideration are Daniel Rinzel, minority chief
counsel to the Senate's permanent investigations subcommittee and
Martin Gerry, former head of the Office of Civil Rights for the
Department of Health, Education and Welfare who has served as
counsel to the Wednesday Group of moderate House Republicans.
   A former career Justice Department employee, Rinzel once headed
the criminal section of the civil rights division and set records
for the number of cases brought. That performance won him a
promotion under Reynolds to deputy assistant attorney general.
   Another candidate is James P. Turner, longtime career deputy
assistant attorney general in the division who early in the civil
rights movement prosecuted white supremacists and other rights
violators in the deep South, sources said.
   ``Everyone on the list would turn it around,'' one of the
candidates, who knows the others, said on condition of anonymity.
   David Runkel, an aide to Attorney General Dick Thornburgh, said
``we're looking for someone whose views reflect Thornburgh's and the
president's views on the importance of the civil rights division.''
   ``We're looking for somebody who can work with civil rights
organizations,'' said Runkel.
   The major civil rights organizations tangled regularly with
Reynolds throughout the Reagan administration.
   Reynolds helped formulate and direct the Reagan administration's
policy of challenging affirmative action hiring quotas. He also
moved to overturn court-ordered busing programs and to restrict
federal guarantees for women's rights and the rights of the mentally
ill and disabled.
   Without committing himself on specific issues, President Bush has
said he wants civil rights policy to be sharply different from that
followed under Ronald Reagan.
   Thornburgh reflected the new administration's stance by meeting
with civil rights leaders, notably Jesse Jackson.
   After meeting with the attorney general last month, Jackson
praised Thornburgh and said, ``The lights have been turned back on
in the Justice Department.''
   Runkel noted Thornburgh's ``interest in the civil rights area
that goes back to the 1960s.''
   ``He knows many of the civil rights leaders first hand,'' Runkel
said. ``He is personally committed to making sure the laws are
enforced.''
   While Thornburgh is still reviewing other applications, Kemp ``is
certainly a leading candidate,'' said one source, who spoke
Wednesday on condition of anonymity.
   Kemp confirmed in a telephone interview that he met with
Thornburgh this week and was told a decision would be made ``in a
couple of weeks.''
   The appointment, which will be made by Bush with Thornburgh's
recommendation, is subject to Senate confirmation.
   Kemp said he had been told earlier by White House counsel C.
Boyden Gray that he was a leading candidate for the position and
nothing that Thornburgh said during their meeting dispelled that
impression.
   ``I just thought it was a good interview,'' Kemp said.
   Without directly criticizing Reynolds, Kemp said the GOP's
failure to attract black voters was due in part to the Reagan
administration's civil rights record.
   ``I think it's very important for the Republican Party to have a
civil rights record they can run on and attract votes from groups
covered by the civil rights laws.''
   ``I've seen estimates as low as 9 percent of the black voters
voted for Bush in 1988,'' Kemp said. ``I don't think that's good for
black people to be taken for granted by the Democratic Party or for
this country.''
   Kemp, who is confined to a wheelchair because of a paralyzing
illness and subsequent injury, headed the Disability Rights Center
when he battled Reynolds in 1982.
   At issue was a proposal by a Reagan administration task force on
deregulation to weaken rules prohibiting companies and institutions
that receive federal funds from discriminating against handicapped
employees.
   ``It was very important to the disability rights movement that we
retain the rules and regulations and Brad was very critical of me,''
Kemp said, recalling the dispute.
   At one point, Kemp demanded Reynolds' resignation from the
Justice Department. The proposal to change 1977 regulations
enforcing the anti-discrimination law was withdrawn by the
administration.
</TEXT>
