<FIRST>r w PM-Congress-Stocks Bjt   02-16 0724</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Congress-Stocks, Bjt,700</SECOND>
<HEAD>Members of Senate Communications Panel Hold Stock in Industry</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Members of a Senate communications panel held
stock in the industry and acted on issues that could have affected
their holdings, a practice that is forbidden in the executive branch
but legal for lawmakers.
   Critics complain about the double standard on
conflict-of-interest rules, but others say it would be impossible to
apply the same standards to the executive and legislative branches.
   The Associated Press selected the communications subcommittee of
the Senate Commerce, Science and Transportation Committee to show
examples of stock holdings and congressional action. Financial
information for the 11 senators came from their disclosure forms for
1987, the most recent year available.
   Sen. Ernest F. Hollings, D-S.C., the committee's chairman and
member of the subcommittee, had larger holdings in
telecommunications than any other senator on the communications
panel.
   On Aug. 21, 1987, he bought about $100,000 worth of stock in
McCaw Cellular Communications Inc., the day the company went public.
In December, Hollings helped postpone the Federal Communications
Commission's plans to hold lotteries for licensing cellular
telephones in rural areas, according to Sen. Brock Adams, D-Wash.
   As committee chairman, Hollings had to approve a Jan. 27, 1988,
communications subcommittee hearing on the FCC's proposed lottery
idea. John E. McCaw Jr., executive vice president of McCaw,
testified in opposition to portions of the FCC's plan.
   Hollings said he didn't know he owned the stock because his
broker bought it for him.
   ``As soon as it was brought to my attention that I owned it, I
told him to get rid of it, which he did,'' Hollings said through a
spokesman. He said he first found out about his holdings in McCaw in
February 1988, but it is unclear whether he made a profit or a loss
on the stock. Some of the stock was sold in November 1987.
   In 1987, Hollings also sold between $100,000 and $250,000 in
stock and $2,000 and $10,000 in options in General Electric Corp.,
which in 1986 purchased the National Broadcasting Co.
   A communications subcommittee member, Sen. Ted Stevens, R-Alaska,
said he had no qualms about his longtime interest in Northern
Television in Anchorage, Alaska, which owns two television stations
and two radio stations in his home state. The holding is worth less
than $5,000.
   ``It's not a substantial holding,'' Stevens said. His votes
include one against a bill extending the fairness doctrine, which
required stations to air opposing views.
   Marla Romash, an aide to Sen. Albert Gore Jr., D-Tenn., said the
senator is sensitive to conflict of interest issues but hasn't felt
the $1,540 in Tandy Corp. stock owned by his wife, Tipper, to be an
issue. Tandy, which manufactures electronic goods including
telephones, is the parent company of Radio Shack.
   Gore voted for legislation to require all telephones to be
equipped with devices so they are compatible with hearing aids.
   Sen. Wendell Ford, D-Ky., dismissed the notion there could be a
conflict between his duties on the panel and the less than $5,000
worth of BellSouth Corp. stock his wife inherited. ``The amount of
stock doesn't amount to a grain of sand on the beach,'' Phil Norman,
Ford's spokesman said.
   One member of the full committee, Sen. Nancy Kassebaum, R-Kan.,
said she avoided voting ``a couple of times'' on issues that dealt
with communications because her family had interests in radio
stations. Mrs. Kassebaum sold WREN Broadcasting Inc., in Topeka,
Kan., for more than $250,000 in January 1987.
   Some other senators have their holdings in blind trusts,
including Sen. Pete Wilson, R-Calif., a member of the communications
subcommittee, as a way of dealing with potential conflicts.
   The basic federal conflict law makes it a crime for executive
branch employees to take government action in which their immediate
families have a financial interest, unless a waiver is obtained. The
top penalty is two years in prison and a $10,000 fine.
   But no law or rule prevents members of Congress from holding
assets that might conflict with their official duties. So lawmakers
can routinely craft or vote on legislation that could affect their
financial interests.
   One argument for not applying the conflict law to them is that
their assets are publicly disclosed so voters can decide for
themselves if senators or representatives are acting for personal
enrichment.
</TEXT>
