<FIRST>r w PM-Burnley     02-16 0586</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Burnley,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>DOT Considering Petition To Overturn Burnley On Eastern</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Transportation Secretary Jim Burnley
says an ethics official let him rule in a case involving Eastern Air
Lines even though he was negotiating at the time for jobs with law
firms linked to the company.
   The issue surfaced Wednesday when the Air Line Pilots Association
asked the department to reject Burnley's decision in December not to
investigate Eastern Air Lines' operations. The union claimed a
conflict of interest.
   The department said it is considering the request from the
pilots' union.
   Burnley on Wednesday called the pilots' accusations ``both
malicious and without foundation.''
   Burnley made his response in a statement released by the
Washington law firm of Shaw, Pittman, Potts &amp; Trowbridge which he is
joining March 1. In the statement, Burnley said he rejected the
pilots' request last year to investigate Eastern only after the
department's chief ethical officer ``assured me in writing that I
was not disqualified from participating in the matter.''
   A Dec. 13 Transportation Department memorandum from ethics
officer Rosalind A. Knapp to Burnley regarding the airline pilots'
request says, ``You are not disqualified from particiapting in this
matter.''
   ``I made each decision based on my best judgment of the merits of
each matter as set out in the record before me,'' Burnley said.
   He said no one at Shaw Pittman or any other firm he was
considering communicated with him about the pilots' petition and no
one at the firms represented ``any of the parties in the
proceedings.''
   Documents show that Burnley last Nov. 22 disqualified himself
from matters involving Shaw Pittman and the firm of Patton, Boggs &amp;
Blow, whose partner Thomas Hale Boggs Jr. sits on Eastern's board.
   The Washington Post on Tuesday quoted Shaw Pittman partner
Stephen Potts as saying the firm gave Burnley a list of cases it was
handling for Eastern and Continental, both owned by Texas Air, but
Potts said the firm was not handling the matter involving the pilots.
   Transportation Department spokesman Hal Paris said the department
would consider the pilots' petition to overturn Burnley's action,
but Paris said he did not know when a decision would be made.
   A department statement said the petition for reconsideration
would be considered ``in the normal course.'' It noted that the law
firm Burnley is joining had requested and was being provided
documents related to the matter.
   The pilots asked the department to reconsider Burnley's refusal
to conduct a ``continuing fitness'' investigation of Eastern to see
that the airline remains financially viable.
   Burnley, in rejecting the original petition, accused the union of
trying to put pressure on Eastern by raising new safety concerns.
   The pilots' petition for reconsideration said that Burnley
overrode normal agency procedures in rejecting the petition himself
rather than letting it be handled by an assistant secretary.
   The filing said Burnley's actions ``strongly suggest a lack of
complete independence or impartiality and an eye cocked towards
subsequent private employment.''
   It accused Burnley of violating the department's ethics rules,
which prohibit officials from engaging in actions that would benefit
or would appear to benefit their own financial interests or those of
prospective employers.
   The original pilots union petition accused Eastern and Texas Air
of threatening Eastern's financial viability by ``downsizing,''
including the planned sale of Eastern's lucrative shuttle operations
to New York real estate tycoon Donald Trump. That sale has received
Transportation Department approval but has not yet been approved by
the Federal Aviation Administration.
</TEXT>
