<FIRST>r w PM-QuayleFamily     02-16 0384</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Quayle Family,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Quayles Move into VP's Residence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Dan Quayle family is now sleeping under the
roof of the official vice presidential residence, but they won't be
fully settled until the mansion is remodeled.
   The remodeling is designed to make the three-story Victorian
house convenient for a family with three children and an arthritic
dog, said Quayle's press secretary, David Beckwith.
   The changes include reconfiguring the children's bedrooms on the
third floor, and adding a bathroom, family room and laundry room on
that floor.
   While Mrs. Quayle says she intends to do the children's laundry
herself, there is a staff of stewards to cook and serve food at the
house on the sprawling grounds of the Naval Observatory in Northwest
Washington.
   Work on the residence has not started yet because private
efforts, spearheaded by friends of the Quayles, are being worked out
to raise money for the refurbishing. Beckwith said he didn't know
how much it would cost.
   But in the week since they moved in, the Quayles have broken in
the new place with a slumber party and video night for the kids.
   Each of the children _ Tucker, 14, Benjamin, 12, and Corinne, 10
_ had a friend stay over last Saturday night.
   Quayle admitted to his press secretary that he had been somewhat
lax in his mission when he accompanied Tucker to the video store,
with instructions to supervise selection of the evening's
entertainment.
   Mrs. Quayle said they should get only two videos.
   ``I guess I didn't do a very good job of supervising because he
got away with four,'' Quayle told Beckwith, adding that he stood in
line for 10 minutes to return them Sunday night.
   On the bill _ ``Moonstruck,'' ``Vice Versa,'' ``Throw Momma From
the Train,'' and ``Planes Trains and Automobiles.''
   Beckwith said that for the Quayles' purposes the house is ``very
spacious. It's just not configured for a family with children at the
moment.''
   Tucker will finish out this year at Langley High School, where he
is in the ninth grade and a member of the basketball team. The
school is near the McLean, Va., house where the family lived when
Quayle was a senator.
   The other two children have switched to private schools in
Washington.
</TEXT>
