<FIRST>r w PM-SovietEconomist     02-16 0461</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet Economist,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Economist Says Health Case Spending Will Increase</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A leading Soviet economist says his government
will fulfill its pledge to nearly double health care spending
despite revelations that the state budget is running a severe
deficit.
   ``We intend to reduce the deficit, but not at the cost of
reducing social investment,'' said Abel Aganbegyan, one of the
foremost proponents of the reforms being pushed by Soviet President
Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   Aganbegyan, secretary of the economics section of the Soviet
Academy of Sciences, said in a speech Wednesday that the Kremlin
will meet a promise by Soviet Health Minister Evgeny Chazov to boost
health care spending. Chazov's plan is to increase that spending
from 100 billion rubles, $166 billion at current exchange rates, to
190 billion rubles, or $314 billion, for the five-year plan
beginning in January 1990.
   State investment in health care fell during the 25 years before
the reforms began in 1985, said Aganbegyan, and the reductions
caused such negative trends as a drop in the average male life
expectancy from 71 to 68 years. Under the Soviet socialist system,
virtually all health care is provided through state institutions.
   Murrary Feshbach, a leading U.S. expert on Soviet health and
economic issues, called the Chazov goal a ``noble one'' that is
needed to reverse deteriorating health conditions in the Soviet
Union.
   Feshbach, a professor at Georgetown University, used statistical
evidence in the 1970s to uncover the declining male life expectancy
and other health problems that are now being discussed more openly
in the Soviet press.
   As part of that openness, Soviet Finance Minister Boris I. Gostev
revealed last October that the government, which had claimed a
balanced budget since World War II, was running a $58 billion
deficit.
   Last month, another economist active in the reform campaign,
Leonid Abalkin, said that the annual deficit was actually about $165
billion, or 11 percent of the gross national output, a figure that
is similar to the U.S. measure of gross national product but
excludes personal services. By contrast, the U.S. federal deficit is
about 4 percent of GNP.
   Aganbegyan estimated the Soviet deficit at $182 billion, and said
that $60 billion was financed through bank loans and the remaining
$122 billion through assets held by Soviet savings institutions.
   Aganbegyan painted a largely optimistic picture of the Soviet
economy in a speech at the Johns Hopkins University School of
Advanced International Studies. He claimed that consumer production
has grown 10 to 15 percent since Gorbachev came to power nearly four
years ago.
   ``Of course, this is a modest beginning,'' he said. Soviet
consumer production accounts for only 30 percent of total
production, compared to 40 percent or more in Western nations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
