<FILEID>AP-NR-02-16-89 0311EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-USDADispute     02-16 0603</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-USDA Dispute,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Yeutter, White House Feuding Over Second Slot</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: This stands for PM-Farm Scene</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The White House and Agriculture Secretary
Clayton Yeutter are bickering over who will be President Bush's No.
2 official at the Agriculture Department, sources say.
   According to the sources, who demanded anonymity as a condition
of speaking, Yeutter wants Jack Parnell, California state
agricultural commissioner, or Sam Hollis, a Memphis, Tenn., cotton
warehouseman, to be his deputy secretary.
   But the sources said Wednesday that former Kentucky governor
Louie Nunn, 68, has recently become a top contender, although no
final decision has been made. They said Nunn, who was governor in
1967-71, is well known in the South and would have substantial
support in Congress.
   ``This makes sense to the politicos,'' one source said. ``After
what the South did to support Bush, it deserves a payoff at USDA.''
   Yeutter said through a spokeswoman that the reports of bickering
over the deputy's job were ``completely false'' and offered no
further comment when queried by The Associated Press.
   A White House official, who declined to be identified, also
denied there was a dispute.
   Nunn, contacted by telephone at his farm in Barren County, Ky.,
said Yeutter interviewed him ``several weeks ago'' for the deputy
secretary's job.
   ``Beyond that, I don't have any information, and any comment
would have to come from Washington,'' he said.
   Nunn was mentioned early as a possible choice for secretary of
agriculture. Bush settled instead on Yeutter, a 58-year-old
Nebraskan, who was Ronald Reagan's U.S. trade representative for 3{
years.
   One source said that Yeutter may have worked an informal deal
with Bush to remain in the cabinet for only two years, on condition
that Yeutter has a deputy trained and ready to step in when it comes
time to leave.
   The possibility of a brief hitch at USDA surfaced when Yeutter's
appointment was announced but was discounted by Bush staff people at
the time.
   According to the source, Bush was willing to accept Yeutter's bid
for an abbreviated tenure at USDA because the president felt
Yeutter's help on trade matters in the coming months and on pending
farm legislation was essential. The current 5-year farm law expires
in 1990.
   Yeutter was reluctant to remain in government after Reagan left
office, was ready to leave town quickly for the private sector and
had been interviewed for several job possibilities until Bush's
appeal that he remain.
   At least until now, Hollis and Parnell have traded places as the
lead contender for the deputy secretary's job, according to one of
the sources.
   One of Hollis' supporters for the job is Sen. Bob Dole, R-Kan.,
who says a major new farm bill should not be high on Yeutter's list
of things to do in the next couple of years.
   Parnell, who has been director of the California department of
food and agriculture since June 1, 1987, has a 4,500-acre ranch and
other business interests.
   California, the leading farm state, was the home of Richard E.
Lyng, Yeutter's predecessor, and has been using clout from a number
of powerful farm and commodity organizations to maintain White House
interest in Parnell.
   Parnell's office in Sacramento said he was away from the capital
and could not be reached. A deputy, Bob Fox, said Parnell was in
Mexico City with the governor to open a new trade office.
   There has been ``lots of speculation'' about Parnell being headed
for Washington but nothing further, Fox said.
   ``The latest we have is that there's no official notification (of
Parnell) and no official decision,'' he said.
</TEXT>
