<DOCNO> AP890216-0032 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-16-89 0330EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-AvalancheDeaths     02-16 0531</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Avalanche Deaths,0545</SECOND>
<HEAD>Survivor Had Given Up Hope Of Rescue Following Out-Of-Bounds Avalanche</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELLEN MILLER HADDOW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GRAND JUNCTION, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An out-of-bounds skier who was
buried in an avalanche that killed two companions said he had given
up hope and placed his ski pass around his neck to be identified
when his body was found.
   ``I'd given up,'' Todd Richards, 23, of Chelmsford, Mass., said
in a telephone interview Wednesday, one day after his rescue near
the Telluride ski area. ``So I prayed a little. I didn't expect
anybody to come looking for me.''
   He spoke from a hospital in Montrose, which lies between Grand
Junction and Telluride on the western slope of the Rockies. He is
recovering from frostbite, hypothermia and bruises sustained in the
avalanche.
   Richards was found by a dozen local skiers who had been coming
down legally nearby and heard his screams for help, authorities said.
   His two companions, Anthony Vaughn Shelly, 25, of Wellington, New
Zealand, and Paul Wolford, 23, of Milwaukee, were killed in the
avalanche.
   Richards said he had resigned himself to dying and had put his
laminated employee ski pass, which he had been using to dig, around
his neck ``so it would be easy to identify me.''
   The three young men were spending the winter in Telluride, where
Richards and Shelly worked for the Telluride Ski Resort Inc. and
Wolford was employed at a local restaurant. Shelly ``was leaving
this weekend to go home,'' Richards said.
   Richards said he and Shelly were friends. He said they met
Wolford on Tuesday morning at Telluride mountain and decided to go
skiing out of bounds toward a narrow, steep, powder-filled chute.
   ``If you go backcountry, you're on your own,'' Richards said.
``We knew that. That's why I didn't expect anybody to come looking
for me.''
   About 11:30 a.m. Tuesday, the party stopped at the top of the
chute. Wolford was putting on a ski that had come off and Richards
took off his gloves to take a picture of the spectacular mountains.
   ``I saw it coming 300 or 400 feet above me,'' Richards said. ``I
turned and yelled at my friend and when I turned back, it was in my
face.
   ``It hit me like a Mack truck. It picked me up right out of my
skis. It took me down about 2,000 vertical feet including over a
cliff that had to be at least 150 feet high. But it was taking me
out as much as down. I'd have to guess 70 mph.''
   San Miguel County Sheriff Bill Masters said it appeared Shelly
and Wolford died of suffocation and multiple broken bones. He added
that Richards may be cited for illegally skiing out of bounds.
   Richards said he expects to be charged for rescue payments but is
``obviously grateful to the people who pulled me out.''
   A ski instructor who tends bar at night, Richards said he isn't
sure he will stay in Telluride.
   ``Part of my job as a ski instructor is to calm people down about
their fears,'' he said. ``I'm not sure I could do that right now. I
might have to go back East.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
