<FIRST>r w PM-S&amp;Ls-GOP     02-16 0496</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-S&amp;Ls-GOP,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Florio Criticizes Alleged Gift of Office Space</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A House subcommittee chairman says the Florida
Republican Party was given 18 months of free use of office space in
a building the government inherited from an insolvent savings and
loan institution.
   Rep. James Florio, D-N.J., requested an investigation Wednesday
and also asked for a formal explanation from M. Danny Wall, chairman
of he Federal Home Loan Bank Board that regulates S&amp;Ls.
   ``At a time when the American taxpayer is being called upon to
provide billions of dollars to bail out savings and loans, it is a
scandal that (officials) treat assets as personal accounts'' for use
by ``friends and cronies,'' Florio said in a letter Tuesday to Wall.
   According to a congressional source, the Republican Party of
Duvall County paid no rent from mid-1987 until it vacated the
Jacksonville building last month for 1,200 square feet of office
space.
   The building is owned by the Federal Asset Disposition
Association, an agency established by the Home Loan Bank Board to
dispose of property the government acquires in closing down or
merging insolvent S&amp;Ls, said the source, speaking on the condition
of anonymity.
   Florio, chairman of the Energy and Commerce subcommittee on
commerce, consumer protection and competitiveness, specifically
asked the General Accounting if the Jacksonville arrangement
violated federal laws prohibiting the government from making
political contributions or giving away federal property.
   Gerald Carmen, FADA's president, was out of town Wednesday night
and unreachable, his wife said. But The Washington Post quoted
Carmen as saying earlier that he had not learned of the Jacksonville
arrangement until December and had ordered the GOP to vacate the
premises within a week.
   The congressional source said the subcommittee has documentation
that FADA officials in Washington had been aware for six months of
the party's rent-free use of the office space.
   Meanwhile, the bank board system through which the government
regulates and insures S&amp;Ls and sells home mortgages has donated a
total of $21,600 to a think tank named in honor of Sen. Jake Garn,
R-Utah, who co-wrote a 1982 law deregulating the industry, the Post
said.
   A report issued by the Garn Institute of Finance, which was
started in 1986 and is affiliated with the University of Utah,
showed a $6,000 contribution from the Federal Savings and Loan
Insurance Corp., the Home Loan Bank Board agency that insures S&amp;L
despositors, the Post said.
   In addition, the report listed contributions totaling $5,100 from
district Federal Home Loan Banks in Cincinnati, Dallas, New York and
Atlanta and $10.6,000 from the Federal Home Loan Mortgage Corp.
(Freddie Mac) the Bank Board agency that buys and sells home
mortgages.
   Wall was quoted by the Post as saying he was unaware of the
contributions to the Garn Institute. But he dismissed their
relevancy, saying, ``What's the point?''
   Before becoming the Bank Board's chairman, Wall was a top aide to
Garn. His wife is the senator's personal secretary.
</TEXT>
