<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Markets     02-16 0265</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0273</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tokyo Stocks Fall, Dollar Rebounds</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Tokyo Stock Exchange's leading index fell today
from its latest record high as cautious investors began selling, and
the U.S. dollar rebounded moderately against the Japanese yen.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average, which climbed 166.59 points
to a record closing of 32,149.48 on Wednesday, gained nearly 200
more points in this morning's trading.
   But a plunge in the afternoon left the index at 32,083.58 at the
close, down 65.0 points, or 0.20 percent, from Wednesday's close.
   A Daiwa Securities dealer said the morning's sharp gain made
investors cautious in the afternoon.
   ``Participants first started selling construction issues, which
prompted the selling trend in the afternoon,'' said the dealer,
speaking on condition of anonymity.
   As the index fell, he said, many investors retreated to the
sidelines to see what the West German central bank council might do
later today. There has been speculation it might raise its official
discount rate, pushing up German interest rates.
   Investors also wanted to wait for U.S. trade figures for
December, due to be released Friday in Washington, the dealer said.
   Trading was heavy, with first section volume estimated at 1.9
billion shares. In addition to construction shares, electrical and
chemical issues lost ground.
   The dollar closed at 126.33 yen, up 0.43 yen from Wednesday's
125.90-yen close. The U.S. currency opened at 126.35 yen and traded
in a range of 126.18-126.53 yen. It had dropped a total of 2.40 yen
on the previous two trading days.
   Trading was inactive as market players awaited the U.S. trade
figures, dealers said.
</TEXT>
