<DOCNO> AP890216-0043 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-16-89 0532EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Mother'sTrunk     02-16 0377</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mother's Trunk,0389</SECOND>
<HEAD>Children Find Baby's Skeleton Inside Mother's Mysterious Steamer
Trunk</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ELKRIDGE, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Martha C. Shields told her children when
they were young never to touch the old steamer trunk in the
basement. Before she died, however, she asked them to take care of
what was inside of it.
   Expecting to find her will when they opened the trunk Wednesday,
her son and daughter were shocked to discover the blanket-wrapped
skeleton of an infant, a Bible, a small chest and the remnants of a
baby's white dress, police said.
   The 67-year-old Elkridge woman may well have taken the secret of
the trunk's contents to her grave when she died Monday, police said.
   A police search of the house turned up no sign of a will or
anything to explain the infant's remains, state police Detective
Michael E. Davey said.
   Mrs. Shields' children, Robert, 29, and Joyce, 31, told
investigators they could remember no family discussions about an
infant brother or sister who may have died at birth or shortly
thereafter. Nor did they recall their mother ever being pregnant
while they were growing up, Davey said.
   Davey said the infant was full-term and may have been stillborn
or died soon after birth, possibly as long as 30 years ago.
   The remains were sent to the state medical examiner's office.
   Both children still live in the house. They declined to comment
to The (Baltimore) Sun on Wednesday.
   Mrs. Shields and her husband, Robert, had lived in Elkridge, a
small town about eight miles south of Baltimore, for about 20 years.
Her husband died of lung cancer while the children were young.
   Neighbors described Mrs. Shields as sometimes belligerent with
children who came on her property but so generous to squirrels that
they would come to her door for food.
   She kept a well-stocked bird feeder and often asked her neighbor
to buy nuts for her to feed the squirrels, said Peg Russell, who
lives next door.
   Neighbors said she spent much of each day listening to a police
scanner and seldom left the house. They said she had been in poor
health for several months before her death.
   ``People who had an opportunity to get to know her really liked
her,'' Ms. Russell said.
</TEXT>
