<FIRST>r a PM-Valentine'sTragedy     02-16 0187</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Valentine's Tragedy,0191</SECOND>
<HEAD>Valentine Day's Spat Blamed In Crash That Killed Four</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A trucker who was pursuing his girlfriend in a
spat over a Valentine's Day card slammed into a car containing two
young couples, killing all four people, authorities said.
   Dariuz Kolos, upset that his girlfriend had sped off in a taxicab
in a fit of anger after receiving his unsigned Valentine, had roared
off after her in his tractor-trailer early Wednesday, police said.
Minutes later, the 22-year-old Chicago man ran a red light and
collided with the couples' car.
   Kolos, who was not hurt, was charged with four counts of reckless
homicide, running a red light and driving too fast for conditions,
said police Lt. Jim Carroll. Kolos was driving with a suspended
license because he had failed to appear in Wyoming to pay speeding
ticket, authorities said.
   Hospital officials identified the victims as Raul Lopez, 19; Juan
M. Cantu, 17; and Dolores Moreno, 18, all of Chicago; and Patricia
Hernandez, 25, of Skokie.
   Friends and relatives said the four were close friends who spent
much of their free time together.
</TEXT>
