<FIRST>r a PM-PreschoolMolest     02-16 0422</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Preschool Molest,0434</SECOND>
<HEAD>Defendant In Alleged Mass Child Molestation Trial Freed On Bail</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Raymond Buckey, one of two remaining
defendants in the McMartin Preschool child molestation trial,
expressed concern about threats and criticized news coverage of his
case after being freed on $1.5 million bail.
   Buckey, 30, refused to talk to a crowd of reporters Wednesday as
he left a downtown jail with his attorney, Danny Davis. They climbed
into a Mercedes-Benz and drove to a Chinese restaurant, where Buckey
was interviewed by television station KABC.
   Buckey, who spent more than five years in jail, said he was
worried about threats against him, his attorneys and his family.
   ``I still realize there are people out there, that as far as I'm
concerned, have gone off the deep end,'' he said.
   He further derided news coverage, saying reporters had flocked to
the trial's prosecution phase but few journalists have been
attending while the defense is presenting its case.
   ``It's discouraging to think that they won't come to hear what we
have to say, but they'll come and make a mob scene at my getting out
on bail,'' he said.
   Buckey said he has been in jail so long that ``I don't remember
emotional feelings that everybody out there takes for granted. I've
been isolated in a nightmare. ...''
   He and his mother, Peggy McMartin Buckey, 61, face 65 child
molestation and conspiracy counts stemming from alleged sexual
attacks at the family-run preschool. She has been free on bail since
1987.
   Superior Court Judge William Pounders on Friday ordered Buckey
freed, although his release was delayed by paperwork involving the
real estate that had been pledged for bail.
   Pounders said he wanted Buckey's long pretrial incarceration to
end as soon as possible, but he also set several conditions for
Buckey.
   The defendant was ordered to have no contact with the alleged
victims in the case, to stay away from the seaside area southwest of
downtown where the school had operated, and to turn over his
passport and remain under 24-hour security protection.
   Buckey also was prohibited from coming in contact with anyone
younger than 14 and from drinking alcohol.
   Family friends, as well as Davis and co-counsel Dean Gits,
arranged for Buckey's bail by pledging title to real estate
properties worth twice the required bail of $1.5 million.
   The case drew national attention when it broke in 1984 with
allegations of nursery school children being raped, sodomized, then
terrorized into silence by satanic rites and animal mutilations by
teachers.
</TEXT>
