<FIRST>r a PM-People-Radner     02-16 0234</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-People-Radner,0241</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gilda Radner In Fair Condition After Surgery</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Comedian Gilda Radner, an original ``Saturday
Night Live'' cast member who successfully battled ovarian cancer,
underwent surgery to correct complications of cancer treatment, a
hospital spokesman said.
   Miss Radner, 42, was listed in fair condition after the surgery
Wednesday at Cedars-Sinai Medical Center, said hospital spokesman
Ron Wise.
   Her comic-actor husband Gene Wilder, 53, was with her in the
hospital, Wise said.
   Wise called the surgery routine and said it corrected
complications stemming from cancer treatment Miss Radner had last
year. He declined to give precise information about the
complications or the treatment.
   ``The surgery definitely wasn't related to any malignancies,''
Wise said. ``Her physicians wanted her to wait until she was feeling
good and was strong enough. She's planning a book tour soon, so she
decided to have it done before the tour.''
   Miss Radner was diagnosed with ovarian cancer in 1986 and
underwent nine months of chemotherapy. She also had radiation
therapy and other cancer treatments including surgery.
   The treatments proved successful and Miss Radner told a Life
magazine interviewer in 1988 that ``cancer is about the most unfunny
thing in the world. But it doesn't mean you have to die.''
   Wise said Miss Radner should be released from the hospital next
week. The actress was expected to launch her book titled ``It's
Always Something'' after her recovery.
</TEXT>
