<FIRST>r a PM-BeatlesBattle     02-16 0346</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Beatles Battle,0356</SECOND>
<HEAD>Attorneys For Beatles, Michael Jackson, File Suit Against NJ Video
Distibutor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By THOMAS MARTELLO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TRENTON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorneys for the Beatles and Michael
Jackson have sued to stop a video distributor from selling
videocassettes featuring the Fab Four.
   The federal lawsuit alleges that Video Wholesalers Inc. of
Neptune illegally distributed and sold several Beatles
videocassettes, including ``The Beatles at Shea Stadium,'' ``The
Beatles in Tokyo,'' ``Beatles Concert in Washington D.C.'' and ``The
Beatles in The Magical Mystery Tour.''
   Jackson owns the copyright to most Beatles songs.
   After the lawsuit was filed Wednesday, attorneys for Video
Wholesalers agreed to halt sale of the videotapes until the matter
is resolved in a hearing March 3 before U.S. District Judge Garrett
E. Brown.
   ``This case is of great importance because it is the first time
that Michael Jackson and the Beatles have come together to police
the valuable Beatles material in which they each have substantial
interests,'' said their attorney, Leonard M. Marks. ``This lawsuit
sends bootleggers and pirates of Beatles materials the clear message
that they will be sued for damages and stopped in their tracks.''
   David Saka, a director for Video Wholesalers, denied that his
company is doing anything illegal.
   ``We have complete rights for what we are doing,'' Saka said.
``We sell prerecorded videocassettes that are made by other people,
and made legally. They have not litigated against the manufacturers.
We've looked into it, and everything is in order.''
   Saka said the sale of the videotapes is not restricted by
copyright laws.
   Lyle Hough, Saka's attorney, said the agreement to temporarily
stop sales of the videotape ``is in no way an admission of guilt.''
   The complaint, filed by Jackson and three Beatles-owned concerns,
Apple Corps Ltd., Apple Films Ltd. and Subafilms, alleges that Video
Wholesalers illegally made and sold the videocassettes without
authorization.
   It charges that the company violated federal copyright laws.
   Attorneys for Jackson and the Beatles are seeking to bar the firm
permanently from selling the videocassettes. They said they also
will ask for financial damages.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890216-0054 </DOCNO>
