<FIRST>r a PM-TampaDisturbance     02-16 0318</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tampa Disturbance,0326</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prosecutors Find No Police Wrongdoing in Drug Suspect's Death</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rock and bottle throwing by bystanders may
have contributed indirectly to a drug suspect's death, a prosecutor
said after eight police officers were cleared of wrongdoing in the
case.
   ``It's only common sense to think that if he received treatment
sooner, the outcome might have been different,'' Assistant State
Attorney John Skye said Wednesday.
   Skye's office announced that an investigation had determined that
the death of Edgar Allen Price, 40, was accidental and that there
was no criminal wrongdoing or negligence on the part of eight
officers involved in a violent scuffle on Feb. 1.
   Authorities said it took all eight officers to subdue the
6-foot-3, 300-pound Price following a drug purchase by undercover
agents in College Hill, a predominantly black housing development.
   The arrest triggered two days of sporadic street violence in the
neighborhood.
   Price, an ex-convict from Houston, was hogtied and placed face
down in the back seat of a police cruiser after rock and bottle
throwing erupted, authorities said. Police drove Price to a school
parking lot a couple of blocks away so paramedics could tend him out
of the path of flying debris.
   The medical examiner's office said the restraint following the
exertion of the struggle was partly responsible for Price's death.
   ``By being placed in a limited space with the head face down into
the back seat ... (and) being handcuffed and restrained, the
necessary conditions for producing an asphyxial death existed,'' Dr.
Charles Diggs, associate Hillsborough medical examiner, said in a
report released Friday.
   Police Chief Austin C. McLane defended his officers, saying they
properly restrained Price with handcuffs and leg ropes. McLane said
he was not surprised that no charges were filed.
   A police department internal review of the officers' actions has
not been completed and is not expected for a couple of weeks.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890216-0056 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-16-89 0613EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-CondomReport     02-16 0579</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Condom Report,0594</SECOND>
<HEAD>Consumer Reports Finds Some Condoms Wanting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Consumer Reports called two popular models of
latex condoms ``grossly defective,'' provoking an angry reply from
the manufacturer which accused the magazine of flawed testing and a
misunderstanding of the product.
   Consumers Union, publisher of Consumer Reports, said Wednesday
its testing of 16,000 condoms showed that six other models were less
reliable than desired. The tests involved filling some condoms with
water and then checking for leaks, and inflating others with air
until they burst.
   All passed government standards in the leakage test. But two
models _ LifeStyles Extra Strength with Nonoxynol-9 and LifeStyles
Nuda Plus _ had a projected failure rate of 10 percent in the
inflation test, poor enough for the magazine to rate them defective.
The government does not use that test.
   Ansell Inc., the Dothan, Ala.-maker of LifeStyles condoms,
objected to the methods used in the Consumer Union study, which was
published in the magazine's March issue.
   ``We're mad,'' said spokesman Lou Capozzi. ``We think it's a bad
study.''
   In a statement, the New York-based company said the magazine
reported on products that were voluntarily recalled, tested too few
samples of each product and otherwise used flawed testing procedures.
   ``Clearly, Consumer Reports does not understand condoms,'' it
said.
   Ansell voluntarily recalled 6 million LifeStyles Extra Strength
with Nonoxynol-9 condoms last year, Consumer Reports noted. It said
most of those it tested were from the recalled lots, and it had no
data on subsequent lots.
   It said there was no recall of the LifeStyles Nuda Plus line.
   Ansell President John Silverman said, ``We are shocked that
Consumer Reports would report negative test results on a product
they knew Ansell had voluntarily recalled six months ago.
   ``Consumer Reports knew their information was out of date, they
knew their research was flawed and they published it anyway. We
fully expect them to withdraw this erroneous report and redo the
study,'' he added.
   Six other models had a projected failure rate of 4 percent in the
inflation test, which the magazine called ``higher than we'd prefer
to see.'' They were Sheik Non-Lubricated Plain End, Ramses Sensitol
Lubricated, Pleaser Ribbed Lubricated (now called Saxon Ribbed
Lubricated), Ramses NuFORM, Mentor and LifeStyles Nuda.
   Samples of 32 other models were ranked in the most-durable
category, the magazine reported. They broke very rarely and thus
were more likely to prevent pregnancy and the spread of disease, it
said.
   The federal Food and Drug Administration tests condoms for water
leakage but does not use the inflation test. While it does not rate
condoms and did not endorse the Consumer Union study, ``basically,
we have no disagreements or problems with the study,'' said FDA
spokesman David Duarte.
   The 32 models in the study's strongest category had a projected
failure rate of 1.5 percent. Top-rated for strength were Gold Circle
Coin and LifeStyles Extra Strength Lubricated. Both were thicker
than others.
   Skin condoms, made from sheep intestine rather than latex, are
stronger than many rubber condoms, Consumer Reports said. However,
it said evidence was not conclusive that skin condoms block passage
of some viruses, and said its medical consultants advised using
latex condoms to prevent disease.
   The magazine included general advice for the use of latex
condoms, warning, for example that oil-based lubricants _ such as
Vaseline and Crisco _ break down the rubber and should not be used.
It recommended water-based lubricants such as K-Y Lubricating Jelly
and Today Personal Lubricant.
</TEXT>
