<FIRST>r a PM-Stabbing     02-16 0321</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Stabbing,0330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Son Charged In Death Of Civil Rights Activist</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The son of a longtime civil rights activist was
charged with murder after he admitted stabbing his father to death,
police said.
   Reginald Perry, 24, walked into the Seventh District police
station Wednesday afternoon, handed over a bloody butcher knife and
told officers he had just killed his father, Ivory Perry, police
said.
   ``He had the knife in his hand and laid it on the counter. He
said, `I just murdered my dad,''' Officer Willie Mae Anderson said.
   Minutes later, police found Ivory Perry, 58, at his home. He had
been stabbed three times in the chest and once in the right side. He
died later at a hospital.
   The younger Perry, said to have a history of mental illness, was
charged Wednesday with first-degree murder and armed criminal
action, police said. He was held in the police headquarters jail
Wednesday night.
   Anderson said Perry had appeared calm and had blood on his
clothing when he surrendered. She said she asked him why he had
killed his father, and he replied: ``I couldn't take it anymore. He
said he didn't care if I committed suicide, so I stabbed him.''
   The elder Perry had been active in civil rights in St. Louis for
many years and often had been involved in protest demonstrations. He
was a Democratic precinct captain for many years and was vying to
become an alderman.
   George Lipsitz, the author of a recent biography about Perry,
called him ``an ordinary person who did extraordinary things.''
   Lipsitz said Perry had paid ``extraordinary penalties'' for his
30 to 35 years of activism, including the dissolution of his
marriage.
   Perry led efforts against substandard housing and utility rate
increases and crusaded for employment and public accommodations for
blacks. He also was instrumental in getting City Hall to pass
legislation providing treatment for the victims of lead-based paint.
</TEXT>
