<FIRST>r a PM-ChicagoMayoral     02-16 0498</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Chicago Mayoral,0514</SECOND>
<HEAD>Field Narrows In Chicago Mayoral Race</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL A. DRISCOLL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A respected alderman withdrew from the Democratic
mayoral primary in a move that could tighten the already narrowing
race between Mayor Eugene Sawyer and State's Attorney Richard M.
Daley.
   ``I would say right now this is a dead heat,'' Sawyer said
shortly after Alderman Lawrence Bloom announced his withdrawal
Wednesday.
   Bloom, a South Side alderman who campaigned on the theme of
racial unity, said it had become clear he lacked the money to
finance a competitive campaign for the Feb. 28 primary. He said he
would campaign for Sawyer.
   Daley said he wasn't surprised by Bloom's withdrawal or his
endorsement of Sawyer, who was elected acting mayor by the City
Council in December 1987 shortly after Harold Washington, the city's
first black mayor, died.
   Daley, the son of the late Mayor Richard J. Daley, said he
expects to get half of the votes that would have gone to Bloom.
   However, polls have indicated that most of Bloom's supporters
considered Sawyer their second choice.
   A Daily Southtown Economist-WBBM-TV poll taken last week showed
Daley supported by 43 percent of those surveyed, Sawyer by 33
percent and Bloom by 11 percent. Twelve percent expressed no
preference.
   The 10 percentage points between Daley and Sawyer marks a
narrowing of Daley's 14-point edge a month earlier.
   The poll, which has a margin of error of 4 percentage points,
shows a virtual dead heat if a rumored write-in campaign on the
Republican ticket for former Alderman Edward Vrdolyak were to
materialize.
   The survey indicates Vrdolyak would draw enough votes away from
Daley to give the state's attorney a 1 percentage point lead over
Sawyer, 39 percent to 38 percent, a lead rendered meaningless by the
poll's margin of error.
   Sawyer spokesman Larry Horist said the mayor can expect to get
the vast majority of the Bloom vote, particularly with Bloom and his
staff joining the Sawyer campaign.
   ``Bloom is a very respected alderman,'' said Horist. ``He's going
to have an influence with both the undecided voters and those who
might be leaning to Daley but who might be soft.''
   Daley's staff contends otherwise.
   Marj Halperin, a spokeswoman for the county prosecutor, said she
doubts Bloom's endorsement will mean much because he has been
sympathetic toward Sawyer all along.
   Nonetheless, she said, Daley sees the race getting tighter in the
remaining week and a half.
   Bloom's withdrawal came a day after financial campaign statements
were filed showing he had raised $228,000, compared with about $3
million for each of the two other major candidates.
   The alderman had said throughout the campaign that he was in the
race to stay, though he hedged by reserving the right to change his
mind.
   The winner of the primary will take on the GOP candidate and
Alderman Timothy Evans, a third-party candidate, in the April 4
general election to complete the last two years of Washington's
second term.
</TEXT>
