<FIRST>r a PM-StudentsBoxed     02-16 0469</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Students Boxed,0483</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pontiac School District Discontinuing `Timeout Boxes'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PONTIAC, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A watchdog group that criticized the use of
``timeout boxes'' to punish unruly special-education students says a
decision to end their use is a step in the right direction but more
needs to be done.
   Michelle Hall-Bolden, a spokeswoman for the Champaign, Ill.-based
Protection and Advocacy Inc., said officials of Pontiac's elementary
school district still plan to use such discipline by isolating
pupils in small rooms.
   ``I'd like to see the school district look at other alternatives
besides timeout,'' she said.
   School Superintendent Wayne Krula said Wednesday that use of the
boxes to contain unruly students for brief periods has been
``regrettably discontinued.''
   ``The booths have played a very important and necessary role''
but they will no longer be used because of ``misinterpretations and
reactions,'' he said.
   The boxes, which were in place at three schools, were constructed
for timeouts because of limited classroom space, school officials
said.
   Without the boxes, the district will have to use small rooms at
Central School and Pontiac Junior High School, Krula said. When
students with behavioral disorders at Washington and Lincoln schools
need to calm down, they will be tranported to schools with timeout
space, he said.
   The boxes, which measure 3 feet by 3 feet and stand about 7 feet
tall, have been used in the district in this central Illinois town
of 11,000 people, for the past two years.
   The practice drew attention last month when a 12-year-old boy
broke out of the wooden box made by a janitor at Washington
Elementary School.
   His parents complained about his confinement to Protection and
Advocacy, which fights for the rights of the mentally ill and
disabled.
   Some parents threatened legal action, and The Daily Leader
newspaper here editorialized against the boxes, saying they should
not be used under any circumstances.
   School district officials have defended the boxes as a
time-honored way in which to handle youngsters without corporal
punishment.
   The State Board of Education sent an official to Pontiac to
review the boxes and a report is expected this week on their
appropriateness as a disciplinary measure.
   John Rapp, the district's special-education supervisor, said last
week the punishment was limited to three pupils, ages 10 to 12, who
were seen as a threat to teachers or other children and were
classified as behavior disorder cases by a psychologist.
   Timeouts are used only for students with behavioral disorders who
have shown ``consistently uncontrollable, aggressive behavior such
as swearing or hitting teachers,'' he said.
   Students were put into the boxes only after a series of other
disciplinary steps brought no results, Rapp said. The box was used
only as a last resort for up to 15 minutes and with a teacher or
teacher's aide present at all times, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
