<FIRST>r a PM-RecordJackpot     02-16 0344</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Record Jackpot,0357</SECOND>
<HEAD>As Lotto Jackpot Winnings Soar, So Do Dreams Of Instant Wealth</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JO ASTRID GLADING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TRENTON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Big dreams fueled big lottery sales
throughout New Jersey as players took their chances on a $17 million
jackpot in today's drawing, the largest in state history.
   ``I'd quit work,'' said one woman buying a ticket at the
Middlesex Food Mart in the northern New Jersey borough of Middlesex.
   ``I'd just relax,'' said another.
   ``I'd squander it all in one day,'' said a third.
   The lure of the record jackpot didn't create lines at most
lottery outlets, but shop owners said business was brisk.
   Lottery spokeswoman Sharon Southard said lottery sales usually
average about $2.5 million to $3 million for each Pick-6 drawing,
and there were only $1.3 million in sales last week when the jackpot
was at $6 million.
   But when the jackpot reached $12 million Monday, there were $9.5
million in lottery tickets sold.
   The estimated jackpot for today is the result of six consecutive
Pick-6 drawings without a top prize winner.
   The jackpot also was fueled by a big change in the odds made last
month when lottery officials increased the choice of numbers from 42
to 46. Previously, the odds of hitting the jackpot were about one in
5.2 million, but with the added numbers the odds of picking all six
numbers are one in 9.3 million.
   ``I guess everybody's dreaming about what they could do with $17
million,'' said Tony Salvo, a Federal Express driver from Trenton
who's been hearing about the lottery at every stop.
   ``I try not to think about it too much because it can consume
you,'' he added.
   But Michael Korolenko, a produce truck driver, has spent plenty
of time thinking about the lottery. Korolenko, 31, said he's been
buying tickets at each store as he makes his rounds.
   Korolenko is hoping the lottery tickets will give him an
opportunity to buy another kind of ticket.
   ``Sure, that's the way out,'' he said. ``The ticket out of New
Jersey.''
</TEXT>
