<FIRST>r a PM-US-Rushdie     02-16 0475</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Rushdie,0491</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Tour Cancelled As Iran Puts Bounty On Author's Head</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Satanic Verses, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The author of ``The Satanic Verses'' canceled a
planned promotional tour of the United States after Iran put a $2.6
million price on his head.
   ``The current climate is not appropriate for a promotional tour
of the U.S.,'' said a statement issued Wednesday by the book's
publisher, Viking Penguin Inc.
   Viking Penguin had scheduled an 11-city U.S. tour for Salman
Rushdie, including readings at four universities. The tour was to
begin Friday to coincide with the official U.S. publication of the
book on Feb. 11. The book has been available in stores in this
country for several weeks.
   But Rushdie, who lives in London, was reported to have gone into
hiding with his wife, American novelist Marianne Wiggins, following
the Iranian threat.
   Police said seven bomb threats have been made in the past two
months to the publisher's Manhattan offices.
   The book, banned in Iran, India, Pakistan, Bangladesh, Egypt and
South Africa, was described as ``a dirty conspiracy'' against Islam
by the Iranian government. Six people died earlier this week in
protests against the book in Pakistan.
   Ayatollah Khomeini called for Rushdie's death and Iran on
Wednesday offered $2.6 million to any Iranian and $1 million to any
foreigner who killed the author, a Moslem born in Bombay, India.
   Paul Slovak, a Viking Penguin spokesman, said recent events in
Pakistan and India, ``combined with our understanding of threats
made against the author and those associated with'' the book's
publication led the publisher to cancel the tour.
   ``We reiterate that no offense was intended in the creation or
publication of this work,'' the publisher's statement publisher said.
   ``It is also our unalterable position that freedom of speech,
freedom to publish and freedom to read must be guaranteed
internationally,'' it added.
   Rushdie received support Tuesday from The Authors Guild, which
issued a statement saying it supports the right of all authors
everywhere to write without fear of constraint from any quarters.
   ``We are appalled by Ayatollah Khomeini's threats against Salman
Rushdie and his publishers,'' the statement said.
   Dawud Assad, president of the Council of Masajid of the United
States, called the book ``garbage'' and said he welcomed the
cancellation of the U.S. book tour.
   But Assad said it was wrong to sentence the author to death.
   ``Islam is a religion of peace and tolerance,'' he said. ``Who
knows what is really in the heart of Salman Rushdie.''
   Muslim leaders in Los Angeles and Detroit reacted similarly.
   ``I'm shocked by (Rushdie's) insensitivity, but I think calls for
his murder are absurd, absolutely absurd,'' said Khaled Abou El Fadl
of the Los Angeles-based Muslim Political Action Committee. ``I am
not even in favor of banning the book. I personally think the whole
thing was blown out of proportion.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
