<FIRST>r a PM-FelledTrees     02-16 0258</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Felled Trees,0263</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Convicted of Cutting Park Trees to Get View of Potomac</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man was convicted of removing nearly 150 trees
on national parkland to improve his view of the Potomac River as the
jury rejected his claim that hired tree-cutters ignored his
instructions.
   The federal jury deliberated less than three hours Wednesday
before finding Isaac Fogel, a Montgomery County water bed
manufacturer, guilty of felony conversion of government property to
his personal use and a misdemeanor charge of illegally removing
trees.
   The tree cutters hacked down scores of oaks, locusts and maples
as well as several rarer ironwood and persimmon trees along the C&amp;O
Canal and Potomac adjacent to Fogel's property in February 1985.
   U.S. District Judge Joseph C. Howard set sentencing for April 17.
Fogel, 45, faces up to 11 years in prison and $350,000 in fines. He
remained free on bond pending sentencing.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney David P. King contended that Fogel had
the trees chopped to improve his view of the Potomac and to increase
the value of his $1.1 million home, which he put up for sale but
never sold.
   Gary M. Ralph, who operates Suburban Tree Service in College
Park, testified that Fogel said he ``wanted all these trees cut down
to the canal'' and that he ``wanted a good view of the river.''
   But Fogel countered that Ralph had suggested removing trees on
the slope that included the park land. He said he insisted that he
only wanted trees cut down to his property line.
