<SECOND>PM-People-Fonda-Hayden, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0503,0440</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jane Fonda and Tom Hayden Separate on Trial Basis</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 4th graf, ``Tom and ...' with previous
Hayden comment.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actress Jane Fonda and her husband, state
Assemblyman Tom Hayden, will separate after 16 years of marriage
that began as a romance between two of the best-known activists of
the anti-Vietnam War movement.
   They have two children, Troy, 15, and Vanessa, 20, who is Fonda's
daughter from a previous marriage to director Roger Vadim. The
couple have lived in a large home in suburban Santa Monica and on a
ranch near Santa Barbara.
   The separation will be on a trial basis, spokesman Stephen Rivers
said Wednesday.
   ``Tom and Jane consider this separation a private matter and will
have no public comment or statement on it,'' Rivers said.
   Friends said the pair's divergent careers placed a strain on the
marriage. Hayden himself has joked: ``If Jane and I have an evening
at home alone together, it is a scheduling mistake by the staff.''
   Fonda, 51, who won best-actress Oscars for the 1971 film
``Klute'' and in 1978 for ``Coming Home,'' and Hayden, 49, a
Democrat representing coastal Santa Monica in the state Assembly,
were married in January 1973.
   In his recently published memoir, ``Reunion,'' Hayden offered
intimate glimpses of his romance with Fonda, who has become
best-known in recent years as an exercise guru whose aerobics video
tapes are best sellers.
   ``I have been a lucky man these past fifteen years. Jane Fonda is
many persons _ actress, rebel, fitness expert _ but I love her most
as the mother of Troy and Vanessa ... Like myself, she loves the
fullness of a family life she never had,'' Hayden wrote.
   Hayden, the radical young co-founder of Students for a Democratic
Society, was one of the Chicago Seven defendants acquitted of
plotting to incite a riot during the 1968 Democratic convention in
Chicago.
   Hayden and four others were convicted of individually trying to
promote a riot and he was sentenced to five years in prison, but an
appeals court overturned the riot conviction in 1972 and most of the
contempt citations were thrown out the next year.
   Fonda went to North Vietnam in 1972 and was widely criticized for
making radio broadcasts urging U.S. airmen to stop bombing and for
taking the seat of an anti-aircraft cannon. Critics called her
``Hanoi Jane'' and a traitor.
   Last summer, she went on the ABC-TV show ``20-20'' and apologized
to Vietnam veterans for the Hanoi visit but stood by her opposition
to the war.
</TEXT>
