<HEAD>Hair Spray Can Explodes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GREEN COVE SPRINGS, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An 11-year-old boy was in
critical condition today with severe burns suffered when a can of
hair spray he had ignited exploded in a fireball, authorities said.
   Shane William Ziegler had first- and second-degree burns on his
face and neck and burns on his arm, chest and legs, said Clay County
sheriff's Lt. Tim Martin.
   Shane, his 10-year-old brother and 14-year-old neighbor, Alan
Workman, used matches to ignite the vapor from two cans of hair
spray in the front yard of the Ziegler home Tuesday night, Martin
said.
   ``He bent down and kind of squatted and I started to walk off,
then I heard it go off,'' Workman said. ``I turned around and all I
could see was a red ball over the yard. It was about a 6-foot flame
from where he was standing.''
   With his shirt and pants on fire, Shane ran into Workman's house
and jumped into a bathtub to extinguish the flames. He was flown to
Shriners Burn Insitute in Cincinnati.
