<SECOND>PM-Lebanon,0330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Christians Trade Gunfire Despite Cease-fire</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RODEINA KENAAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Army troops and Christian militiamen
exchanged intermittent artillery fire today, jeopardizing a
cease-fire in their battle for control of the city's Christian zone.
   A police spokesman said the 22-hour battle between the two
Christian forces, which has killed at least 66 people and wounded
200, also caused ``colossal'' material losses amounting to
``hundreds of millions of dollars.''
   ``Many, many houses, shops and even banks have been gutted,'' he
said.
   Gunners of the Lebanese Forces militia and army units were firing
sporadically at each other's positions today in the impoverished
district of Ein Rummaneh and its surroundings.
   ``If the exchange escalates, it might shatter the cease-fire,''
said the police spokesman, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   The leftist newspaper As-Safir called Wednesday's fighting ``the
Maronites' black day.'' The army of the Christian-controlled
government and the Christian militia are made up mainly of Maronites
Catholics.
   The country is now led by two rival governments, one Christian
and the other Moslem. The fighting, which began Tuesday and tapered
off with a cease-fire Wednesday, further divided the Christian camp
in its nearly 14-year-old civil war against the Moslems.
   An official at the U.S. Embassy denied radio reports that
Ambassador John McCarthy has decided to evacuate Lebanon with his
entire American staff to the east Mediterranean island of Cyprus.
   ``There are no plans for us to leave,'' said the official, who
requested anonymity. He said none of the embassy's estimated 20
American staffers had been injured in the fighting, which sent a few
shells crashing 200 yards from the embassy compound in suburban
Aukar and broke windows there.
   The offices were closed Wednesday and today.
   In Wednesday's fight, the army overran militia strongholds to
control about 75 percent of the Christian enclave, police said. They
also said the army took militia positions in a central mountain
range.
