<FILEID>AP-NR-02-16-89 1037EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r p PM-Duke-Treen     02-16 0453</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Duke-Treen,0463</SECOND>
<HEAD>Republican Party Fights Former Klan Leader's Election</HEAD>
<DATELINE>METAIRIE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush and former President Reagan
have made highly unusual endorsements in a state House race in an
effort to defeat a former Ku Klux Klan leader who is running as a
Republican.
   In radio spots that began running today, Reagan said, ``I can't
help but tell you of the high regard I have for one candidate in the
race for your next representative, John Treen.''
   Treen faces fellow Republican David Duke in Saturday's runoff for
a seat in the state House of Representatives, representing a
district in the New Orleans suburbs. Duke was imperial wizard of the
Knights of the Ku Klux Klan until he left the group in 1980.
   Leslie Goodman, a spokeswoman for the Republican National
Committee, described the endorsements by Bush and Reagan as
unprecedented for a state legislative race. The national party is
helping pay the costs and is also assigning three campaign
professionals to help Treen, she said.
   ``David Duke will embrace any political party he can get to
espouse his politics of hatred, violence and bigotry,'' Goodman said
Wednesday. ``If he's trying to say that being a racist and a bigot
is the same as being a conservative Republican, I beg to differ with
him. His background has nothing to do with mainstream American
values. It's a disgrace.''
   Letters signed by Bush, saying that Treen has a ``strong sense of
compassion for others and an abiding faith in the future of
America,'' are being mailed to voters this week, Goodman said. While
neither Bush nor Reagan mention Duke in their endorsements, the
national party's interest stems solely from Duke's background, she
said.
   Treen, also running as a Republican, finished a distant second to
Duke in the seven-way Jan. 21 primary. Under Louisiana's open
primary system, the top two vote-getters in a primary, regardless of
party, face each other in the runoff if no one candidate gets half
the primary votes.
   Duke said he is amazed that Bush and Reagan are involved in the
local election that involves only about 23,000 registered voters.
   ``The outside interference in this race is absolutely
ridiculous,'' Duke said. ``It's like the establishment is closing
the ranks to prevent an independent from coming through.''
   Treen, who was state campaign chairman for Bush's 1980
unsuccessful presidential bid, said the endorsements show ``that at
the highest levels of government, there is a genuine concern about
someone that harbors such a foreign ideology.''
   Duke claims he no longer agrees with the Klan philosophy. He
heads a group called the National Association for the Advancement of
White People, which he says is not racist but a group seeking human
rights for everybody.
</TEXT>
