<FIRST>r a PM-VoodooContract     02-16 0324</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Voodoo Contract,0331</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Men Indicted for Using Voodoo in Attempt to Murder Circuit Judge</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TUPELO, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two brothers trying to get a voodoo death
curse put on a judge who sentenced one of them to prison paid $100
to an undercover agent for a portrait and what they thought was a
lock of the judge's hair, officials said.
   Leroy Ivy of Oxford and his brother John Henry Ivy of Tupelo were
indicted this month on a charge of conspiracy to murder Lee County
Circuit Judge Thomas Gardner III. The indictment was made public
Monday.
   In July, Gardner had sentenced John Henry Ivy to 40 years in
prison after Ivy pleaded guilty to two robberies of Tupelo liquor
stores. From the state penitentiary in Parchman, he conspired with
his brother to retaliate against the judge, authorities said.
   ``They tried to kill him with voodoo,'' said Lee County Sheriff
Jack Shirley. ``We've talked about it. To me, it was kind of a
joke.''
   Jerry Butler, an investigator with the Mississippi Highway
Patrol, said undercover agents discovered that someone was trying to
obtain a photo of Gardner and a lock of his hair to send to a voodoo
practitioner in Jamaica to have a hex placed on the judge. Agents
supplied a picture of Gardner and a lock of a detective's hair to
Leroy Ivy last October, he said.
   The brother paid $100 for the hair and photo, Shirley said,
adding that it was the payment of money that led to the conspiracy
charge. They had allegedly agreed to pay $1,000 to the voodoo witch
doctor, via a middleman in Louisiana.
   Contacted this week, Gardner declined to comment.
   ``I'd rather not discuss it now _ for obvious reasons,'' he said.
   Voodoo is a West African religious belief that incorporates a
number of gods. It is a national religion in Haiti and is widespread
throughout the Caribbean and in some communities in the South.
</TEXT>
