<FIRST>r w PM-ContinentalBank     02-16 0280</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Continental Bank,280</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fed Rejects Continental Request To Purchase Arizona Bank</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Reserve Board rejected a request by
Continental Bank Corp. in Chicago to purchase a small Arizona bank
because it said Continenal had not fulfilled its duties under a law
designed to prevent red-lining.
   The Fed said it found ``important deficiencies'' in the bank's
performance under the Community Reinvestment Act, which requires
banks to meet local credit needs, including those of low- and
moderate-income neighborhoods.
   Continental's petition to acquire Grand Canyon State Bank in
Scottsdale, Ariz., was rejected on a 4-2 vote Wednesday, with Govs.
H. Robert Heller and John LaWare opposed. Gov. Edward W. Kelley Jr.
did not vote.
   ``The bank made no significant effort to ascertain the credit
needs of its communities or to advertise its products to the
community,'' the 10-page majority decision said. ``Finally, given
Continental's size, as well as the opportunities available in the
Chicago area, (the) bank's participation in community development
and redevelopment efforts was unsatisfactory.''
   The decision also said the bank made ``substantially inaccurate''
statements for a number of years about its compliance with the
Community Reinvestment Act.
   It noted that the bank has since developed a plan that should
``make substantial contribution to correcting the past
deficiencies'' in its compliance with the law.
   But it added: ``The board does not believe that commitments by
themselves can serve as a substitute for the established record of
CRA performance required by the statute.''
   The board also voiced concern about the bank's plan to expand
while still financed in part by and subject to the control of
Federal Deposit Insurance Corp., in the wake of a 1984 federal
bailout.
</TEXT>
