<HEAD>Driver Sues Over Scantily Clad Women By Roadside</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CLEARWATER, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A driver who says he was distracted by
two women wearing tight T-shirts and hot pants wants the county to
repair the damage caused when he slammed into the rear end of
another car.
   Kenneth Larrison, 27, of St. Petersburg submitted a $1,900 bill
to Pinellas County to fix both his car and the car he hit on Dec. 10.
   Larrison says he took his eyes off the road to watch the women in
skimpy T-shirts and shorts standing on a median strip advertising
for a Pinellas Park tire company.
   One woman swiveled a hula hoop while the other held aloft a sign.
   Larrison argues the median strip should be free of any unusual
distractions, and he has written the county that he has seen similar
promotional gimmicks along county roads that endanger ``the property
and lives of other drivers.''
   Backing him up all the way, Larrison's fiancee Kathleen Zielinski
says her beau's eyes weren't really on the other women _ but on the
spectacle they presented by the roadside.
   The county has six months to respond to Larrison's claim for the
car-repair money, County Attorney Susan Churuti said Wednesday.
Larrison will be free to file a lawsuit if he receives no response
in that time.
   But Churuti said she doesn't buy Larrison's reasoning.
   ``Let's face it,'' she said, ``you've got to be in control of
your automobile when you're driving it.''
