<FIRST>r a PM-Writer'sDeath     02-16 0272</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Writer's Death,0278</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Gathering Material for Freight Train Book Found Dead In Freight
Car</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who wanted to write a book about
traveling by freight train was found dead in a freight car,
apparently crushed by a load of lumber, police said.
   Gregory Carpenter, 26, of Eau Claire, Wis., who might have jumped
into a small open space in a freight car for warmth, was found
pinned between lumber and an end of the car by two Soo Line
employees Wednesday morning, said Sgt. Gerry Breyer.
   Carpenter, dressed in several layers of winter clothing, left
home Sunday and may have been dead for two to three days, police
said. The Ramsey County medical examiner's office was investigating
the death.
   Carpenter's possessions included a sleeping bag, a railroad atlas
of the United States, books, traveler's checks, credit cards, a list
of 60 people he planned to visit in a dozen states, and notes
indicating he hoped to write about his experiences, police said.
   ``There seems to be a growth in people who think it's glamorous''
to ride freight trains, said John Bergene, a spokesman for the Soo
Line Railroad in Minneapolis. ``What happened today is the reality.
A freight car is a dangerous environment. People can be trapped in
them, freeze to death.''
   The freight car, owned by British Columbia Railway, had come into
the railroad yard from Duluth early Saturday and was moved again
Tuesday night. It was then moved off the main tracks for repairs.
   Police said it was unclear when Carpenter got on the car and what
caused the lumber to shift.
</TEXT>
