<FIRST>u i PM-Israel     02-16 0510</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel,0526</SECOND>
<HEAD>Teen-Ager Dies of Wounds; Four Palestinians Injured</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALLYN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 4-year-old Palestinian girl died today of head
injuries suffered in a mysterious explosion, and three Palestinians
were wounded by army gunfire during protests in the occupied Gaza
Strip, Arab news reports said.
   A military source confirmed the girl's death. The army said it
was checking the other reported casualties. Since the Palestinian
uprising in the occupied lands began 14 months ago, 380 Palestinians
and 15 Israelis have been killed.
   Two aides to Finance Minister Shimon Peres, the leader of the
left-leaning Labor Party, met Wednesday night with PLO supporter
Faisal Husseini to lay the groundwork for future peace talks.
   It was the second meeting this week between Israeli legislators
and Husseini, one of the most prominent Palestinian figures in the
occupied territories.
   The meetings were criticized by Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir's
right-wing Likud bloc, which accused Labor of violating a coalition
agreement that bars Israel from holding talks with the Palestine
Liberation Organization.
   Likud legislator Reuven Rivlin said on Israel radio the meetings
were tantamount to holding talks with PLO chief Yasser Arafat. The
talks were ``directly with someone who thinks he represents
Arafat,'' Rivlin said.
   Avraham Burg, a parliament member and aide to Peres who attended
Wednesday's meeting, said the talks were needed to break through
psychological barriers between Israelis and Palestinians. ``We
cannot consider every Palestinian to be a terrorist and not speak to
him,'' Burg said on the radio.
   ``They (the talks) are a basis so that one day Israelis will come
and say okay so the next stage is a political dialogue,'' he said.
   The death of 4-year-old Iktimal Abdullah of Tayasir village in
the occupied West Bank came three days after she was injured when a
device she found near her home exploded, Arab reports said. Her
10-year-old brother Naim also was wounded in the blast.
   The army launched an investigation into the blast in Tayasir and
into two other Palestinian deaths linked to explosions of
unidentified devices on the West Bank. The air force also has been
asked to look into the blasts.
   Palestinian activists have charged that Israeli soldiers have
thrown explosive devices out of jeeps to lure unsuspecting children,
but the army has denied the reports. The army's deputy chief of
staff, Maj. Gen. Ehud Barak, says the blasts generally have resulted
from children playing with undetonated shells near firing ranges or
with flares that fell from training jets.
   The two earlier blasts killed a 15-year-old near the village of
Kabatiya on Monday and an 8-year-old in the village of Tamoun on
Feb. 4.
   The army said the Kabatiya incidents occurred after the teen-ager
wandered onto an army training ground.
   An army spokeswoman said the military planned to take measures to
prevent such accidents in the future, but she did not elaborate.
   In the Gaza Strip today, teen-agers staged several stone-throwing
protests, Arab reports said. The reports said three youths, aged 12,
14, and 17, were shot in the legs by soldiers.
</TEXT>
