<FIRST>r a PM-NearCollision     02-16 0350</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Near Collision,0359</SECOND>
<HEAD>Airport Blackout Led To Near Collision Of Jets</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COSTA MESA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two jetliners came within 15 seconds of
colliding after one of the planes was rerouted because of an
electrical blackout at John Wayne Airport, a newspaper reported
today.
   The Federal Aviation Administration was investigating the near
collision Monday night involving a British Airways jumbo jet and an
American Airlines jetliner over Westminster, the Orange County
Register reported.
   Air-traffic controllers in the Los Angeles Terminal Radar
Facility at the time of the incident said the planes flew within 1{
miles horizontally and 200 feet vertically of each other. FAA
regulations mandate that planes be kept at least three miles apart
horizontally and 1,000 feet vertically.
   Controllers, whose identities were withheld because of a pending
investigation, told the newspaper that a controller in Los Angeles
spotted the potential collision just after 7 p.m. and quickly warned
the British Airways jet to turn.
   Controllers said the planes, which were flying at about 300 mph,
would have collided in about 15 seconds.
   ``There is an investigation for a possible (controller)
operational error,'' said Barbara Abels, an FAA spokeswoman in Los
Angeles.
   The planes were at an altitude of 9,000 feet, Ms. Abels said, but
she said she did not know how close the aircraft came. Neither pilot
filed a near collision report with the FAA, she said, adding that
pilots have leeway on whether to file a report
   An electrical short-circuit that blackened the main runway lights
prompted officials to close John Wayne Airport to commercial traffic
for about four hours Monday night.
   The American jet was diverted to Ontario International Airport
because of the blackout, said Jim Brown, an American spokesman in
Dallas.
   American Flight 1262 from San Jose had 66 people on board and was
being guided by controllers at the FAA's radar center at El Toro,
airline and FAA officials said.
   The British Airways Boeing 747, which can carry up to 376 people,
was departing Los Angeles International Airport for London,
according to airline departure schedules. It was being guided by Los
Angeles controllers.
</TEXT>
