<SECOND>PM-Flag Dispute, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0531,0286</SECOND>
<HEAD>Innocent Pleas Entered As Black Leaders Move Case To Jury Level</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf, `Last month ...' to explain that defendants'
appeal sent case to circuit court.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MONTGOMERY, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fourteen black leaders convicted of
trespassing in their bid to remove the Confederate battle flag from
atop the state Capitol dome have asked a judge to dismiss the
charges.
   The defendants, Alabama NAACP President Thomas Reed and 13 black
legislators, pleaded innocent Wednesday in circuit court as they
sought a jury trial on the trespass charges.
   Last month a district judge convicted and fined the 14 defendants
$100 each in the misdemeanor case at the close of a lengthy,
non-jury proceeding. But the 14 defendants filed an appeal which
sent their case to circuit court.
   Circuit Judge Randall Thomas, who is to review various pre-trial
motions, did not immediately set a date for a jury trial.
   Reed, as part of a campaign by the National Association for the
Advancement of Colored People, called for the Confederate flag to be
removed from the Capitol last year. On Feb. 2, 1988, Reed led the
delegation of 14 to a fence surrounding the Capitol, which was
closed for restoration. He was arrested for trespassing when he
grabbed the fence as if he might climb it. The others were arrested
in sequence as they put a hand on the chain-link fence.
   Gov. Guy Hunt, the state's first Republican governor this
century, has said repeatedly he feels the Confederate flag is a
historic symbol and he will not remove it unless instructed to do so
by the Legislature. A measure to remove the flag died in the state
House last year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
