<FIRST>r a PM-McDonald'sCash     02-16 0193</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-McDonald's Cash,0198</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fast Food Customer Gets Big Bucks Instead of Big Mac</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EUCLID, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A customer at a fast-food restaurant got more
than two all-beef patties, special sauce, lettuce, cheese, pickles,
onions on a sesame seed bun from a drive-in window.
   The customer got part of the McDonald's receipts for the day when
an employee inadvertently gave the driver a take-out bag containing
cash instead of food.
   The mistake happened about 8 p.m. Friday when the night manager
placed money from the cash registers in a money bag, then placed
that bag inside a McDonald's bag while she awaited a police escort
to the bank, police Capt. Patrick Newkirk said.
   Managers often conceal money bags in restaurant bags to ward off
robbery attempts, Newkirk said.
   An unsuspecting employee handling a busy window handed the cash
to a customer. Newkirk said the manager said it was a ``sizable
amount of money'' but could not give an exact amount.
   No one has returned the money as of this morning, said police
Sgt. Ken Kaselonis. The restaurant's manager filed an initial police
report, but the company is not seeking a criminal investigation.
</TEXT>
