<FIRST>r i PM-ArabAlliance     02-16 0217</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Arab Alliance,0222</SECOND>
<HEAD>Four Arab Nations Sign Accord to Form Economic Alliance</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leaders of Egypt, Iraq, Jordan and North
Yemen signed an accord today to create an economic alliance designed
to boost Arab unity, an official report said.
   Officials of the four countries say the new alliance is aimed
solely at cementing economic ties _ not at rivaling the Arab League
as a political bloc.
   The Iraqi News Agency said the pact was signed at a summit
meeting hosted by President Saddam Hussein. The meeting was attended
by King Hussein of Jordan; President Hosni Mubarak of Egypt; and
President Ali Abdullah Saleh of North Yemen.
   Recent press reports have speculated the new group, called the
Arab Cooperation Council, is meant to counter the influence of Saudi
Arabia.
   But Saudi King Fahd called the Iraqi president by telephone to
congratulate him and the three other leaders on forming the group,
the agency said.
   The main goal of the Arab Cooperation Council is to achieve
``cooperation, coordination, integration and solidarity'' among the
signatories, the agency said. The group's charter envisages
cooperation in agriculture, industry, culture and social programs.
The charter also calls for working toward an Arab common market, the
report said.
   The new group will have a general secretariat in Amman, Jordan.
</TEXT>
