<FIRST>u i PM-Colombia     02-16 0302</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Colombia,0310</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rebel Leader Claims Insurgents Control One-Fourth Of Colombia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former Catholic priest who is the
leader of Colombia's most active leftist guerrilla group claimed in
a letter published today that insurgent groups control one-fourth of
the Latin American country.
   The letter from Manuel Perez, commander of the National
Liberation Army, to former president Alfonso Lopez Michelsen was
published by a half dozen Colombian dailies.
   Lopez has tried to get Colombian guerrillas and the government to
negotiate a truce with Colombia's six leftist guerrilla groups.
   No one answered the telephone at the Defense Ministry's public
affairs office today when The Associated Press tried to ask the
ministry about the guerrilla claim.
   In the last four years, AP reporters have found towns where
police stations have been abandoned because of guerrilla activity.
   The letter was received Wednesday by Lopez, the same day that
Perez's guerrillas reportedly ambushed two river boats in northern
Colombia.
   Five government soldiers, five sailors and 20 guerrillas were
killed, the commander of the army's 2nd Brigade, Gen. Juan Salcedo
Lora, said in a broadcast interview with the Colombian radio chain
RCN. The reported ambush occurred on the Cauca River, 240 miles
north of the capital of Bogota.
   About 150 guerrillas with automatic weapons caught the two boats
in a crossfire near the village of Guaranda, the general said. The
boats were carrying fuel and other supplies for army garrisons,
Salcedo said.
   Army troops aboard the boats fended off the attack until air
force planes attacked the rebels, Col. Jairo Garcia Camargo, said in
an RCN interview today.
   On Sunday, the National Liberation Army attacked a boat carrying
only civilians on the Magdalena River in central Colombia, the
Defense Ministry said earlier this week. Six passengers were killed
and 15 were wounded, it said.
</TEXT>
