<FIRST>r a PM-CocaineLumber     02-16 0375</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cocaine Lumber,0383</SECOND>
<HEAD>Businessman Gets 27-Year Sentence For Record Cocaine Haul</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAT LEISNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A businessman was sentenced to 27 years in
federal prison today for masterminding the smuggling of a record
7,300 pounds of Colombian cocaine into the United States in
hollowed-out lumber last spring.
   U.S. District Judge George C. Carr rejected tearful pleas by
Michael Tsalickis, 61, to impose a lighter sentence. The judge said
he thought evidence in the trial had been clear.
   Tsalickis, jailed since his arrest last May, faced from 10 years
to life for his conviction in October on two counts of smuggling and
two counts of drug trafficking. During a monthlong trial, the
government claimed he was working with a ruthless Colombian drug
organization known as the Cali Cartel.
   Prosecutors had urged the maximum sentence, telling Carr that
their calculations showed the cocaine haul translated into 57
million doses. But the judge's sentence was within federal
sentencing guidelines, which called for a prison term of 24 to 30
years.
   ``This is the largest seizure in the history of the U.S. in which
there has been an arrest,'' assistant U.S. attorney Walter Furr told
Carr. ``Your sentence must punish, deter others and promote respect
for the law.''
   Tsalickis, who lived in Colombia for 35 years and ran an
import-export business, read from a statement, breaking down and
crying as he did so.
   ``If I did harm society in the eyes of the court, then I am truly
sorry,'' he said. His attorney, Frank Wilkles, said an appeal would
be filed.
   During Tsalickis' trial in Tampa federal court, U.S. prosecutors
told jurors that Tsalickis orchestrated the smuggling operation in
which cocaine was hidden inside bundles of cedar lumber shipped from
Brazil.
   Tsalickis and two Colombian associates, Freddy Perez-Rivera, 28,
and Pedro Narvaez, 35, were arrested May 3. The two Colombians were
convicted of conspiracy to smuggle the cocaine in a separate trial.
   Federal and local drug agents, acting on a tip, had watched the
trio as they organized the unloading of the lumber in St.
Petersburg, separated the lumber containing the cocaine from the
rest of the wood, and had it transported by truck to a Tarpon
Springs warehouse owned by Tsalickis.
</TEXT>
