<FILEID>AP-NR-02-16-89 1220EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-UN-Namibia     02-16 0532</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-UN-Namibia,0547</SECOND>
<HEAD>Security Council Authorizes Namibia Independence Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Security Council today authorized an
independence plan and U.N. peacekeeping force for Namibia, setting
in motion the end of 74 years of South African rule over the
continent's last colony.
   The 15 council members unanimously adopted a resolution
implementing an independence plan for Namibia.
   April 1 was set as the date to begin the one-year plan for
Namibia's transition to an independent, black majority-ruled nation.
   Today's resolution also approved a report by Secretary-General
Javier Perez de Cuellar on implementing the plan, which calls for
sending 4,650 U.N. peacekeepers, 500 police and 1,000 civilian
election monitors to Namibia.
   The U.N.'s Namibian independence mission will be called the U.N.
Transition Assistance Group. Perez de Cuellar has estimated the
project will cost $416 million in its first year.
   The General Assembly is expected to authorize funds for a 70-man
team of U.N. military observers who will monitor the withdrawal of
50,000 Cuban troops from Angola as neighboring Namibia becomes
independent.
   The stage was set for the Cuban pullout and the Namibian
independence process in December, when South Africa, Cuba and Angola
signed accords at U.N. Headquarters pledging their cooperation with
a southwest African pace plan.
   Cuba has stationed troops in Angola at that country's request
since 1975, to defend Angola's Marxist government from attacks by
South African troops and the U.S.-backed rebels of UNITA, the
National Union for the Total Liberation of Angola. South Africa has
ruled Namibia, also known as South-West Africa, since it captured
the territory from Germany during World War I.
   The U.N.'s predecessor, the League of Nations, gave South Africa
a mandate to govern Namibia in 1920, but since World War II the
World Court, General Assembly and Security Council all have ruled
that Pretoria's mandate is void.
   South Africa refused to relinquish control of Namibia without the
withdrawal of the Cuban troops, saying their presence just over
Namibia's northern border could intimidate voters during the
independence.
   Under the southwest Africa peace accords, half of the 50,000
Cuban soldiers will have withdrawn by Nov. 1, when Namibia is
scheduled to begin a week of elections for a constituent assembly.
That constituent assembly will draft a constitution and organize a
black majority-ruled government in Namibia, with independence
envisaged in April 1990.
   All Cuban troops are to be out of Angola by July 1991.
   Beginning April 1, the South African military is to reduce its
forces in Namibia to 1,500 troops confined to barracks under U.N.
supervision, and cut back the size of Namibia's police force.
   U.N. peacekeepers will also monitor camps in which the guerrillas
of the South-West Africa People's Organization, SWAPO, will stay.
   SWAPO, a Marxist-influenced independence movement led by Sam
Nujoma, is expected to win a majority of the seats in Namibia's
constituent assembly, but if it fails to hold two-thirds of the
seats it will have to form a coalition with some of the other
parties in Namibia.
   A coalition would probably result in a multiparty state,
observers say, but if SWAPO wins two-thirds of the seats in the
contituent assembly it will probably declare a one-party state.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890216-0095 </DOCNO>
