<FILEID>AP-NR-02-16-89 1222EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-HirohitoFuneral     02-16 0491</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hirohito Funeral,0509</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hirohito State Funeral Ranked as Biggest Ever</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY THORSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Emperor Hirohito's state funeral may be the biggest
in modern times, a Foreign Ministry official said Thursday.
   Japan expects representatives of 154 countries to attend the Feb.
24 rites, led by President Bush and including 54 other heads of
state and many more royals, vice presidents, prime ministers and
foreign ministers, according to a senior official, who spoke on
condition he not be identified.
   The funeral is budgeted at $74 million, including $25.4 million
to be spent on the funeral site, where there will be a sanctuary and
two huge tents to shelter 10,000 dignitaries, $19 million for
security and $21 million to build a mausoleum.
   The Japanese press called it the most expensive state funeral in
history.
   Soon after Hirohito died of cancer at the age of 87 on Jan. 7,
the government notified all 165 countries with which Japan has
relations that they were welcome to send delegations to the funeral.
   Bush quickly accepted, but some countries debated vigorously
whether to send high-level representatives because of Hirohito's
role as leader in World War II.
   The Netherlands, for instance, is sending its foreign minister
but not a member of the royal family because of bitter memories of
Japan's harsh treatment of the Dutch East Indies.
   The overall high level of the delegates is gratifying to Japan,
the Foreign Ministry official said. ``The number of guests and their
high rank is beyond our expectations,'' he said.
   The number of official foreign mourners is expected to be at
least 600, he said, acknowledging difficult problems with protocol
and logistics.
   Some ambassadors complained they will have to group up and arrive
at the funeral in buses. He said Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita's
Cabinet still was wrestling with the protocol issue of how to seat
the guests.
   By tradition, those with longer tenure should have more prominent
seats. That would leave Bush, in office less than a month, in the
back of the crowd.
   ``We are studying all the precedents of past funerals, and I hope
our government will come to a fast conclusion,'' he said.
   Asked how Bush would be treated, he laughed nervously and said:
``The matter is not so simple.'' He did not comment further.
   The 154 countries to be represented include 145 that are actually
sending delegates from abroad, he said. Nine are to be represented
by ambassadors accredited to Tokyo.
   Other recent state funerals:
   _ The 1963 funeral of President John F. Kennedy drew
representatives from more than 100 countries.
   _ The 1980 funeral for Yugoslav President Josip Tito drew 127
foreign delegations.
   _ The 1981 funeral of Egyptian President Anwar Sadat drew
representatives from more than 80 countries; the United States sent
former Presidents Jimmy Carter, Gerald R. Ford and Richard M. Nixon.
   _ The 1984 funeral of Soviet leader Yuri Andropov drew more than
100 foreign delegations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890216-0097 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-16-89 1230EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-China-Amnesty     02-16 0728</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Amnesty,0749</SECOND>
<HEAD>Intellectuals Call For Amnesty Of Political Prisoners</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dozens of China's most famous writers and thinkers
called for an amnesty for political prisoners in an open letter sent
Thursday to the government and ruling Communist Party.
   ``An amnesty ... would be beneficial to the atmosphere of reform
and in accordance with the increasing respect for human rights which
is a pervasive trend in the world today,'' said the letter, copies
of which were given to journalists by several of the signers.
   It was addressed to the standing committee of the National
People's Congress, China's legislature, and the party Central
Committee.
   The 33 signers ranged from Bing Xin, 87, one of China's most
famous pre-Communist woman writers, to 26-year-old author Lao Mu,
who helped draft and distribute the letter.
   ``I think it is the first time since (1949) that intellectuals of
all generations, writers from the 1930s and current writers, all
have joined in such an action,'' said Bei Dao, a 40-year-old poet
and short story writer who got the idea to draft the letter.
   ``I think intellectuals are waking up,'' he said. ``I don't have
any special interest in politics. Like most writers, I'm interested
in my work. But I have a conscience.''
   There are no reliable figures for the number of political
prisoners in China. The London-based human rights group Amnesty
International estimates there are thousands of prisoners of
conscience, including political dissidents, clergy and members of
minority groups such as Tibetans opposed to Chinese rule.
   China acknowledges jailing ``counterrevolutionaries'' but has
never given a number.
   China's most famous dissident, astrophysicist Fang Lizhi, made a
similar call for an amnesty in a letter to Chinese leader Deng
Xiaoping last month. The new letter expressed ``deep concern'' for
Fang's proposal.
   Like Fang, the petitioners singled out Wei Jingsheng, one of the
leaders of a brief political thaw called the Democracy Wall
Movement. Wei was arrested in 1979 and sentenced to 15 years in
prison after calling for democracy as a ``fifth modernization'' to
go along with Deng's program of updating industry, agriculture,
science and national defense.
   ``We hear Wei has gone mad in prison,'' said Bei. ``We have no
proof, there's no way to contact him.''
   Several dozen other Democracy Wall activists also were arrested
and many remain jailed.
   ``Of course we hope the government will respond and give amnesty
to Wei and the others,'' Bei said. ``But realistically _ I don't
know. For such a large group of prominent intellectuals to express
their view, I think it must have influence ... eventually.''
   Su Shaozhi, a leading Marxist theorist who was dismissed in 1987
as director of China's Marxism-Leninism Institute because of his
liberalism, said the government probably ``won't pay attention.''
   But Su said he didn't think anyone would be punished because of
the letter. ``The signers are very famous. They will have to think
how to treat us,'' he said.
   The letter comes during a period of unusual outspokenness by
Chinese intellectuals, who know well the government's pattern of
allowing brief periods of free discussion and then cracking down.
   Small groups of liberal intellectuals have begun meeting to
discuss such dangerous topics as democracy and multiparty rule.
   Ren Wanding, another Democracy Wall activist who was jailed from
1979-83, has declared 1989 a memorial year for his jailed colleagues
and issued a series of essays calling attention to human rights
abuses.
   The letter suggested the political amnesty be given to mark two
other anniversaries this year: the 40th anniversary of China's
communist revolution and the 70th anniversary of the May Fourth
Movement of 1919, which began as a student protest against foreign
occupation of parts of China and turned into a movement for
liberalism and democratic reform.
   Chen Jun, a former student who signed the letter, and Bei both
stressed that the letter signers have many different political views.
   ``But this is just one point on which we all agree,'' Chen said
of the amnesty. He said he hoped to continue collecting signatures,
even though the original letter has been mailed.
   Other signers included Li Zehou, a philosopher who was a delegate
to the 7th National People's Congress that met last year; Wang
Ruoshui, former deputy editor of the party newspaper, the People's
Daily; playwright Wu Zuguang; and novelist Zhang Jie, whose works
have been widely translated.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890216-0098 </DOCNO>
