<FIRST>r a PM-Governor'sAunt     02-16 0235</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Governor's Aunt,0242</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Arrest Man in Death of Governor's Aunt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOSEPH B. FRAZIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARTERSVILLE, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A teen-ager was arrested today in the
slaying of Gov. Joe Frank Harris' 74-year-old aunt, police said.
   William C. Scott, 18, of Cassville was arrested about 8:45 a.m.
today as he drove along U.S. 41 in Cartersville, Georgia Bureau of
Investigation Director Robbie Hamrick said. Scott was charged with
murder, aggravated sodomy and burglary.
   Allie Morrow Roper, a retired florist, was found dead at her
Cartersville home Sunday after friends missed her at church.
Authorities said she was strangled late Saturday, probably by an
intruder.
   Harris served as a pallbearer at his aunt's funeral Tuesday.
   Hamrick said police identified Scott as a suspect Wednesday
through fingerprint evidence processed by the bureau's new automatic
fingerprint identification system, which greatly speeds up the
process of matching fingerprints found at a crime scene with
fingerprints on file.
   ``It's a new system not fully operational yet,'' Hamrick said at
a news conference. ``This is one of the first hits we've made on
this system.''
   Police said they did not know whether Scott knew Mrs. Roper, and
they did not have information about his background. No bond was set
immediately, and no court date was scheduled.
   Police sought Scott for about 16 hours before his arrest, Hamrick
said, adding that he did not resist arrest when stopped.
</TEXT>
