<FIRST>r a AM-Marcos     02-16 0255</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Marcos,0263</SECOND>
<HEAD>Marcos Reportedly Has Benign Kidney Tumor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Philippine President Ferdinand Marcos has
undergone surgery that determined that a tumor on a transplanted
kidney is benign, the Honolulu Advertiser reported Thursday.
   Surgeons on Tuesday removed tissue from the tumor during an
operation lasting more than an hour, the newspaper said. The
newspaper quoted unidentified sources close to Marcos as saying that
pathologists examined the tissue and determined that it was benign.
   The tumor was revealed during a CAT scan Friday.
   Marcos spokesman Gemmo Trinidad confirmed the examination had
been performed, but said he did not know the results. Eugene
Tiwanak, assistant administrator of St. Francis Medical Center, said
he was unaware of the surgery or the CAT scan.
   Marcos remained in guarded condition in the hospital's intensive
care unit Thursday. He is breathing with the aid of a respirator, a
hospital spokesman said.
   Marcos was admitted to the hospital Jan. 15 for treatment of
pneumonia and bronchial asthma.
   Marcos and his wife, Imelda, were indicted last October on U.S.
racketeering charges accusing them of plundering the Philippine
economy of more than $100 million and stashing most of the money in
the United States.
   A federal judge in New York is to decide after a hearing next
month if Marcos is healthy enough to be arraigned. Mrs. Marcos was
arraigned last year in New York.
   The Marcoses have lived in exile in Honolulu since February 1986,
when a civilian-military revolt ended their 20-year rule and
catapulted President Corazon Aquino to power.
</TEXT>
