<FILEID>AP-NR-02-16-89 1441EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-TaxpayersAbroad     02-16 0400</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Taxpayers Abroad,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>IRS to Help Americans Abroad Prepare Their Tax Returns</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Internal Revenue Service announced Thursday
that it is sending workers to 143 cities in 80 countries to help
Americans abroad prepare their 1988 tax returns.
   At the same time, the IRS said it is intensifying efforts to
reduce the number of U.S. citizens living abroad who don't even
bother to file a return. The agency estimates 3 million live in
foreign countries, including retirees and dependents with no income,
but only 900,000 filed returns last year.
   ``We feel there is a big tax gap there,'' Donald Houck, assistant
commissioner for international operations, told reporters.
   Later this year, Houck said, the IRS expects to have in operation
a computer program that will match the names of Americans applying
for passports against the master list of those filing returns. Those
who receive passports but don't file will have to explain why.
   The IRS provided mail, telephone or on-the-spot assistance to
about one-third of those Americans abroad who filed returns last
year. An estimated 5,000 volunteers trained by the IRS helped 30,000
U.S. taxpayers stationed at foreign military installations.
   Houck said that because of budgetary restraints, the IRS had to
postpone opening a toll-free telephone assistance line for Americans
abroad. The line will be opened, starting in Canada and Europe, in
1991, he said.
   Many Americans working in a foreign country may avoid tax on up
to $70,000 earned each year, if they spend enough time abroad, but
they still are required to file a return. Houck cautioned that the
exclusion is not available to employees of the U.S. government or to
members of the military.
   Independent contractors who supply services to the U.S.
government may be eligible for the exclusion if they meet certain
requirements. But the exclusion is not available to workers who are
paid from non-appropriated funds, such as employees of service clubs
or military post exchanges.
   The IRS estimates there are as many as 40,000 such employees. The
agency has assessed additional taxes averaging $4,000 against more
than 600 who erroneously claimed the foreign-earnings exclusion.
Houck said these audits have the potential for $30 million in
deficiencies.
   Schedules for the visit of IRS employees to foreign countries are
posted in U.S. embassies and consulates and, for military personnel,
with the office of the judge advocate general.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
