<FIRST>r w AM-UnsungAmericans     02-16 0468</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Unsung Americans,470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Program to Encourage Volunteers to Help Young People</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARTON REPPERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Media and volunteer service organizations
announced on Thursday a national campaign to encourage more
Americans to volunteer to help young people.
   The campaign, called ``Unsung Americans,'' will use television
and radio public service messages in conjunction with a referral
service to direct citizens to local volunteer agencies.
   ``There is every indication that the time is ripe for this kind
of an effort, given the emphasis on volunteerism in this country,''
said James E. Duffy, president of communications for Capital
Cities@ABC Inc.
   He pointed to President Bush's call for increased volunteerism in
connection with his ``thousand points of light'' theme.
   The Unsung Americans campaign will build upon experience gained
from ABC's partnership with the Public Broadcasting Service in
Project Literacy U.S., or PLUS, an effort launched in December 1985
to raise awareness of the problem of illiteracy in this country.
   ``Studies have shown a strong correlation, a real link, between
the lack of basic skills among young people and the major problems
that they face today _ teen pregnancy, dropping out of school,
substance abuse, unemployment and delinquency,'' Duffy told a news
conference.
   He noted that ``raising basic skills is a key entry point to
creating solutions to these problems. It is not a panacea, but it is
an important and a fundamental approach.''
   Other organizations joining with ABC and PBS in the Unsung
Americans campaign include:
   _VOLUNTEER, a national volunteer group based in suburban
Arlington, Va., that aims to stimulate and strengthen volunteer
citizen involvement.
   _Education Commission of the States, based in Denver, an
interstate compact that helps state leaders improve the quality of
education.
   _National Collaboration for Youth, based in Washington, made up
of 15 national youth-serving organizations that banded together to
help improve conditions affecting young people.
   _Contact Center Inc., located in Lincoln, Neb., which operates a
national telephone referral service for dealing with various social
problems.
   The Unsung Americans public service messages on TV and radio will
utilize a toll-free number, 1-800-228-8813. Viewers and listeners
calling the number for information will be referred by the Contact
Center to volunteer organizations in their own communities.
   Former Michigan Gov. George Romney, chairman of VOLUNTEER, said
the Unsung Americans effort was timely because ``volunteering is the
most effective and least costly way of solving problems. There is no
substitute for the caring volunteer who is capable and willing to
help another individual, with a problem, to help themselves.''
   He added that ``experience has shown that the most effective way
of saving a teen-ager headed down the wrong road _ toward crime or
drug abuse _ is to introduce in their life a caring adult role
model. It is not just an answer, it is the only answer.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
