<DOCNO> AP890216-0129 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-16-89 1449EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-SriLanka     02-16 0476</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sri Lanka,0488</SECOND>
<HEAD>Governing Party Wins Majority in Parliament</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAJU GOPALAKRISHNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Ranasinghe Premadasa's United
National Party won a decisive majority in Parliament after an
election campaign in which more than 1,000 people were killed,
according to results announced Thursday.
   ``The people have exercised their vote in the face of great
adversity. The people have totally rejected the path of violence,''
the president said shortly after the results of Wednesday's vote
were announced.
   Despite death threats and assassinations by Sinhalese extremists
and Tamil separatists trying to halt the elections, about 63 percent
of Sri Lanka's 9.3 million eligible voters cast ballots.
   ``This is the spirit that will restore democracy,'' Premadasa
said in a nationally televised speech. ``The time for national
reconstruction has begun. The agenda is clear: We must restore law
and order.''
   His party won 125 seats in the 225-member Parliament. The chief
opposition group, former Prime Minister Sirimavo Bandaranaike's Sri
Lanka Freedom Party, captured 67 seats, Tamils won 23 seats, and the
rest went to small parties and independents.
   Premadasa, who won presidential elections two months ago, failed
to secure the two-thirds majority needed to amend the constitution
and key laws. That could hamstring legislation needed to implement
his ambitious anti-poverty program, which he considers vital for
ending sectarian violence that has killed at least 10,000 people in
the past six years.
   Premadasa, Mrs. Bandaranaike and the majority of their followers
are Sinhalese, the largest ethnic group on this Indian Ocean island.
   Comprising 75 percent of the country's 16 million people, the
Sinhalese dominate the government, military and economic
infrastructure. Tamils, a minority of 18 percent, claim they are
discriminated against, and the most radical members of their
community have been waging a separatist war since 1983.
   The Tamil winners included 13 members of the Eeelam Revolutionary
Organization of Students, a former underground militia that was
involved in the guerrilla war.
   Soldiers and police enforced a strict curfew imposed Thursday
morning after Sinhalese extremists shot and killed five Sri Lankan
soldiers and wounded four policemen in attacks on army and police
posts in southern and central Sri Lanka.
   Police blamed the attacks on the People's Liberation Front,
composed of militant Sinhalese who believe the government has made
too many concessions to Tamils.
   The police blamed 47 of the 56 election-day killings on the
front. They said security forces killed seven Sinhalese extremists
who tried to attack polling places, and they blamed the other two
deaths on Tamil guerrillas.
   Premadasa's party, which held 139 of the old Parliament's 168
seats, scored most of its heaviest victories in its ethnic
constituency, the Sinhalese heartland. It captured only one seat in
Northern province, which is almost totally Tamil. It won five seats
in Eastern province, where the population is about evenly divided
among Sinhalese, Tamils and Moslems.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
