<FIRST>r a AM-CupcakesBanned     02-16 0320</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cupcakes Banned,0328</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mother Claims Cupcakes Rejected Because of AIDS Fear</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RIVERSIDE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who baked 106 Valentine's Day
cupcakes for her sons' classmates said school officials turned away
the treats because they feared the spread of AIDS, but officials
denied her claim.
   Edwina Hatzenbuehler said she was first told by the kindergarten
teacher of her son Mark's class at Monroe Elementary School that the
cupcakes had to be declined for ``health reasons.''
   She said Principal Corrine Law later told her the school had a
policy against distribution of homemade food, possibly because it
could have been made in a ``dirty house'' and threatened spread of
diseases such as AIDS.
   ``Everybody in that school knows me,'' Hatzenbuehler said
Wednesday. ``It really just hurt my feelings. I told her you can't
spread AIDS by cupcakes.''
   Law denied mentioning AIDS or ``dirty'' houses when explaining
the policy to Hatzenbuehler, but said the policy resulted from
general concerns about health.
   Store-bought food is allowed because preparation is supervised by
health agencies, Law said.
   There is no scientific evidence that the AIDS virus can be
transmitted through food, said Faith Davis, a senior communicable
disease specialist for the AIDS unit of the Riverside County Health
Department. It is spread most often through sexual contact, needles
or syringes shared by drug abusers, infected blood or blood
products, and from pregnant women to their offspring.
   Law said the school's policy, adopted last September, was a
decision by the school staff and Parent-Teacher Association. Besides
health considerations, parents showing up with homemade goodies were
disrupting instruction, Law said.
   Distribution of store-bought treats has been put under the
coordination of room mothers, the principal said. Hatzenbuehler is
not a room mother.
   ``We try very hard not to offend any parent, but we have to ...
act on what is best for the children,'' said Joan Shurtliff,
assistant superintendent for the Riverside Unified School District.
</TEXT>
