<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Legionnaires     02-16 0185</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Legionnaires,0192</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Contract Legionnaires' Disease in Hospital</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BIRMINGHAM, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two patients contracted Legionnaires'
disease while being treated in a hospital for other illnesses, a
hospital spokeswoman said Thursday.
   All water supplies at the Queen Elizabeth hospital are being
tested and an internal investigation has been ordered, said a
hospital spokeswoman. An independent inquiry also will be launched,
said a regional health official.
   A middle-age man contracted Legionnaires' disease after a liver
transplant and died on Jan. 29 from other causes, the hospital said.
A woman is being treated in the hospital for Legionnaires' disease,
the spokeswoman said.
   No other details on the patients were released.
   ``It is almost certain that they contracted the disease while in
hospital,'' said hospital bacteriologist Dr. Tom Elliott.
   Officials said Wednesday that a second man had died from an
outbreak of Legionnaires' disease in central London. Health
officials said 14 other people were suffering from the disease and
47 others were suspected of having it.
   The pneumonia-like disease is carried by bacteria found in soil
and in the water of air-conditioning ducts, storage tanks and rivers.
