<HEAD>Storm Halts Oil Production at Field off Norway</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STAVANGER, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A three-week storm with winds of up to
115 mph and 43-foot waves has forced a state-owned company to
suspend oil production from a major offshore field, the company said
Thursday.
   The storm has made it impossible for tankers to moor at the
loading buoys at the Statfyord oil field, said Statoil company
spokesman Haakon Lavik.
   Lavik said gas production has also been reduced.
   The field normally produces 700,000 barrels of oil daily. Statoil
said it will supply its European oil and gas customers from other
facilities if necessary.
