<FIRST>u w PM-NorthTrial 4thLd-Writethru a0605 02-16 0783</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-North Trial, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0605,840</SECOND>
<HEAD>Defense Objects to Attorney General's Involvement</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 11 grafs new with Walsh rebuttal; picks up 10th graf pvs,
Meantime. Cuts last 3 grafs to shorten.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oliver North's lawyers said today a plan worked
out between Attorney General Dick Thornburgh and prosecutors would
``impose intolerable burdens'' in the Iran-Contra case, but the
independent counsel prosecuting North denied the assertion.
   North's attorneys, Brendan Sullivan and Barry Simon, filed a
motion seeking rejection of the plan to protect classified material
detailed Wednesday by independent counsel Lawrence Walsh.
   Under that plan, drawn up to reflect a court order issued Tuesday
by U.S. District Judge Gerhard A. Gesell, the independent counsel
said he will, if necessary, seek an affidavit from the attorney
general to prevent the disclosure by North of classified information
that could harm national security.
   The defense motion was filed a few hours after Chief Justice
William H. Rehnquist lifted an order that had delayed the start of
the trial. Thornburgh said he is satisfied with arrangements for
handling state secrets that North wants to make public.
   ``The court's oral ruling and its subsequent written order were
clearly intended to exclude the AG (attorney general) entirely from
the trial process,'' Sullivan and Simon said in their motion.
   They said that each time the court rules admissible an item of
information falling within nine categories specified by the judge's
order, ``the trial will come to a halt'' while Walsh sends word to
Thornburgh.
   North's lawyers said Walsh's plan contemplates that Thornburgh
would be permitted to intervene in the trial through ``bits and
pieces of affidavit,'' an approach that the judge rejected Tuesday.
   Walsh's plan would ``cripple'' North's right to cross-examine
prosecution witnesses and to present his case and ``would impose
intolerable burdens on the court, the witnesses, and the jurors,''
they contended.
   Gesell did not comment on Walsh's plan.
   Walsh said in a response that the ``independent counsel does not
contemplate the trifling `bits and pieces' activity by the attorney
general'' which North anticipates, adding:
   ``The day-to-day conduct of this case will be by the independent
counsel and only the independent counsel.''
   Meantime, he called a closed hearing this afternoon to discuss
disclosures of the Reagan administration's offer of inducements to
third countries to funnel support to the Nicaraguan Contra rebels
during a time when Congress had banned aid to them.
   At the hearing, Gesell was to consider the proposed text of what
the government is willing to admit at North's trial about the quid
pro quo arrangements, which defense lawyers say are at ``the heart
of the case.''
   On Monday, Sullivan asserted that then-President Reagan
personally participated in a plan to offer favors to third countries
willing to support the Contras and that Reagan and other top
administration officials then agreed to cover up the arrangements.
   The government is willing to make limited disclosures about the
matter, but North's lawyers want to delve into it in greater detail
at his trial.
   Rehnquist, in a brief order this morning, lifted a stay he had
granted the government on Sunday. The Justice Department says
adequate safeguards to prevent disclosure of national security
secrets at the trial are in place and there no longer is a need to
hold up the proceedings.
   Thornburgh on Wednesday accepted an order from Gesell barring the
attorney general from filing affidavits continuously during the
trial objecting to individual pieces of classified material that
North wants to introduce in his defense.
   Walsh made it easier for Thornburgh to accept Gesell's order.
Walsh devised a plan saying that he will, if necessary, seek an
affidavit from the attorney general to prevent the disclosure during
the trial of classified information that could harm national
security.
   Walsh's statement added that he ``is prepared to discharge his
responsibility'' under Gesell's order.
   Thornburgh said Walsh's promise ``provides the government with
the substance of what we have been seeking for the past week.''
   As he left work, Thornburgh told reporters he was satisfied
because ``the independent counsel has agreed to be my
representative'' on all secrecy matters in the trial.
   Late Wednesday, Acting Solicitor General William C. Bryson filed
papers asking that the stay issued by Rehnquist be lifted.
   ``In light of the district court's order and the report of the
independent counsel, the attorney general believes that the concerns
that gave rise to the relief from this court have been satisfied,''
the department said in its brief.
   North is accused of shredding evidence and lying to Congress to
cover up the Reagan administration's attempts to help the Nicaraguan
Contra rebels during a period in which Congress had banned direct
U.S. aid.
   py
