<FIRST>r w AM-Cattle-Feedlots     02-16 0264</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cattle-Feedlots,190</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cattle Being Fed for Slaughter at 7.7 Million Head Feb. 1</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cattle being fed for the slaughter market as of
Feb. 1 in the seven major beef states totaled 7.7 million head, down
2 percent from a year ago but 5 percent more than inventories of two
years ago, the Agriculture Department said Thursday.
   The placement of new cattle and calves in fattening pens last
month was reported at 1.71 million head, up 3 percent from a year
ago but 8 percent more than two years ago. Officials said it was the
largest January feedlot placement since 1974.
   Marketings of ``fed'' cattle in January totaled 1.67 million
head, down 5 percent from a year ago and down 7 percent from two
years ago.
   As of Feb. 1, feedlot inventories were smaller than a year
earlier in Arizona, Colorado, Nebraska and Texas. But California,
Iowa and Kansas showed increases. The seven states produce about
three-fourths of the nation's beef.
   State feedlot cattle inventories are listed here for the seven
states. The first number is the number of cattle, in thousands, as
of Feb. 1, and the second number is the percentage of a year
earlier.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Arizona          260   77
California       425  102
Colorado         825   95
Iowa             675  103
Kansas         1,535  110
Nebraska       1,920   96
Texas          2,060   93
  
