<FIRST>r i AM-Baker-Book 1stLd-Writethru a0604 02-16 0341</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Baker-Book, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0604,0349</SECOND>
<HEAD>Baker Calls Rushdie Death Threat `Regrettable'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Satanic Verses, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: LEADS with eight grafs to ADD State Department comment. Pick
up 5th pvs, `Baker made...' ^By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>THE HAGUE, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State James A. Baker
III said Thursday that Iranian death threats against author Salman
Rushdie were ``regrettable.''
   In Washington, the State Department said it was appalled by the
threats of the Iranian government, which says Rushdie's novel ``The
Satanic Verses'' is a blasphemy against Islam.
   While Baker posed for photographs in Luxembourg with Foreign
Minister Jacques Poos, he was asked about the multimillion-dollar
reward offered Wednesday in Iran for the murder of Rushdie, whose
novel has sparked violent protest from Islamic fundamentalists.
   ``I think that is regrettable,'' Baker said. ``The United States
is fundamentally committed to oppose terrorism in all its forms,
particularly state-sponsored terrorism.''
   Baker's predecessor, George Shultz, was identified with a tough
stand on terrorism.
   In Washington, State Department spokesman Charles Redman said,
``We are appalled by the death threats against Salman Rushdie by the
(Iranian leader) Ayatollah Khomeini, as well as a subsequent offer
of a reward for his murder.'' ``Such threats are completely
irresponsible and are incompatible with basic standards of
international conduct,'' he added.
   Redman said he did not see how ``this in any way could improve
the prospects'' for U.S.-Iranian relations.
   Baker made his comments as he held talks with leaders of the
Benelux countries and met with Manfred Woerner, the
secretary-general of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization, as he
neared the end of an eight-day trip to 15 allied capitals.
   Baker began the day in Brussels, meeting Belgian Prime Minister
Wilfried Martens and Foreign Minister Leo Tindemans. He met Woerner
at NATO headquarters.
   In Luxembourg, he was received by Grand Duke Jean and Prime
Minister Jacques Santer along with Poos. In the Netherlands, he had
talks with Foreign Minister Hans Van den Broek before a scheduled
flight back to Brussels.
   Baker's trip ends Friday after a stop in France.
</TEXT>
