<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Burma-Elections     02-16 0202</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Burma-Elections,0209</SECOND>
<HEAD>Burma Announces Multiparty Elections</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Multiparty elections will be held in spring
1990, official radio said Thursday, about five months after a
military coup ended 26 years of one-party rule.
   Military leader Gen. Saw Maung used his forces to suppress
nationwide pro-democracy demonstrations in September, saying Burma
was heading toward anarchy. But he then promised fair, multiparty
elections.
   The 26-year one-party rule by the Burma Socialist Program Party
ended when Saw Maung, the armed forces chief, took power in a coup
on Sept. 18.
   Thursday night's announcement by the Election Commission over
state radio did not give an exact election date.
   But it said an election law would be published on March 1, ``14
months before the actual elections,'' suggesting a date around early
May 1990. It said the election campaign would begin three months
before the general elections.
   The mention of a three-month campaign was seen as an indication
that the existing ban on public assembly would be lifted and the
parties would be allowed to use state radio and television.
   Registration of political parties began last Sept. 29 and is to
close on Feb. 28. So far, 188 parties have registered with the
commission.
</TEXT>
