<FIRST>r i AM-Ramos-Plane     02-16 0246</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ramos-Plane,0253</SECOND>
<HEAD>Philippines Defense Chief Has Trouble Getting Off the Ground</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Secretary Fidel Ramos, whose
plane burned on the tarmac of a remote island in December, was
delayed leaving a U.S.-run naval base Thursday when three of his
aircraft had engine trouble.
   Ramos and his party boarded a Fokker aircraft at Subic Bay naval
base for a flight to another installation when the pilot discovered
a faulty starter engine and circuit breaker, the Philippines News
Agency said.
   Ramos and the others waited about 90 minutes until a Philippine
navy BO-5 helicopter was flown to the base, 50 miles west of Manila.
   The helicopter arrived at Subic and Ramos boarded. When the pilot
revved up the engines, however, the helicopter also developed engine
trouble and the takeoff was scrubbed.
   Officials then telephoned Villamor Air Base in Pasay City to
dispatch a third aircraft _ a Fokker _ to retrieve Ramos, the news
agency said.
   Minutes later, that Fokker also developed engine trouble and had
to return to Villamor. Finally, a UH-1 helicopter was sent to Subic
and managed to take off with Ramos aboard, the agency said.
   On Dec. 19, a Fokker carrying Ramos and 17 others caught fire
moments after landing at Catarman on Samar island. All passengers
escaped without injury but the plane was totally destroyed.
   One of several helicopters sent to Catarman to fetch Ramos' party
developed engine trouble and ditched in the sea. No one was killed.
</TEXT>
