<FIRST>r i AM-LawyerKilling     02-16 0249</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lawyer Killing,0255</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Given Life in Prison for Killing Human Rights Lawyer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man linked to the military was
convicted of assassinating an Amnesty International official, and he
was sentenced to life in prison, a judge said Thursday.
   Allan Climaco was found guilty Wednesday of ``murder with
aggravating circumstances'' after witnesses identified him as the
triggerman in the June 24, 1988, slaying of lawyer Alfonso Surigao.
   Surigao was an official of the Philippine branch of Amnesty
International, the international human rights group. He was also
chairman of the Protestant Lawyers' League, an association of human
rights lawyers who have frequently defended alleged communist rebels.
   The attorney was one of five human rights lawyers slain in the
Philippines last year. Human rights groups say the killings were
engineered by the military, which is trying to put down a 20-year
communist insurgency.
   In a telephone interview, Judge Juanito Bernad said the evidence
against Climaco ``was overwhelming and very strong.'' He said seven
witnesses identified Climaco as the gunman who killed Surigao at his
home in Cebu City, 350 miles southeast of Manila.
   Climaco later surrendered and issued a written confession,
claiming he acted on instructions of Maj. Rico Palcuto, the regional
military security chief. Climaco said he was a former guerrilla of
the communist New People's Army and had turned into a military
informant.
   Three months later, Climaco retracted his statements and pleaded
innocent before the court.
   Palculto was court-martialed last year but later reinstated.
</TEXT>
