<FIRST>u a AM-StanfordMigrants Bjt   02-16 0694</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Stanford Migrants, Bjt,0713</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stanford Denies Responsibility For Migrants Living On University
Land</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVE WILSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STANFORD, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A short walk from Stanford University's
golf course, impoverished migrant farm workers living on university
land are crammed into wretched wooden shacks without heat, toilets
or running water.
   ``There are more illegalities, more exploitation of workers, more
breaches of workers' rights in this one plot of ground right here
than we've seen in a long, long time,'' said Jim Eggleston, attorney
for a university union that the migrants want to represent them.
   But who is legally responsible for the migrants' plight?
   Is it the university, which owns the land? Or is it Webb Ranch,
which has leased 300 acres and pays the migrants for picking berries
and vegetables that sell to restaurants and markets 30 miles north
in San Francisco?
   The migrants have asked the United Stanford Workers, the union
for 1,200 university maintenance workers, to represent them. The
union sent a letter this week to Stanford President Donald Kennedy
and Webb Ranch demanding recognition as the bargaining agent for the
farm workers.
   If Kennedy and Webb don't recognize the union by Friday, the
union plans to file a petition with the state Agriculture Labor
Relations Board that could lead to a vote by the farm workers on
union representation.
   Eggleston contends Stanford, as land owner, is the true employer
of the farm workers under state law and is ``legally responsible for
the shameful activity that's going on here.''
   Stanford attorney Priscilla Wheeler disagreed.
   ``Stanford is not responsible for the employment policies of its
lessees or contractors,'' she said in a statement. ``We would, of
course, be concerned if any lessee violated the law. So far as we
know, Webb Ranch has not done so. If there are issues of
mistreatment, we hope they are brought up with the state.''
   Stanley Webb, manager of the ranch leased by his family since
1922, was not available for comment Thursday, his office said. Other
ranch officials would not comment.
   The migrants' shacks are just a half-mile from the center of what
is considered one of the most beautiful college campuses in the
nation. Tuition and room and board next school year will total
$19,164.
   Up to 90 migrants, including 20 children, live in the encampment.
Among them are Tibuecio Cabrera, 67, and his wife, Cointa Mendoza,
58.
   Cabrera's last monthly pay receipt shows he worked 194 hours and
earned $824.50, or $4.25 an hour. He took home $514.86 after
deductions for Social Security, unemployment tax, a $50 personal
advance, rent of $145.50 and utilities.
   ``I sometimes get angry, but I have to comfort myself,'' Cabrera
said. ``What else can I do?''
   Cabrera and his wife have a small electric heater and some
blankets to keep warm. They have a hot plate, but there is no sink
or water in the room. Clothing hangs from a cord and a bare bulb
dangles from a wire tacked to the wall near several pictures of
Jesus and the pope.
   Like the other workers, Cabrera receives no health care, no
holidays and no vacation. He said he had to use all his savings to
pay for treatment of a stomach ailment.
   The camp has only one portable toilet and three indoor toilets.
There is a communal kitchen and refrigerators are padlocked between
meals.
   Only a few of the migrants speak or read English.
   Webb charges 75 cents for every hour worked for rent, so the more
hours worked the higher the rent. The migrants are charged for the
tools they use.
   The migrants, long afraid to speak out because they were illegal
aliens from Mexico, asked the Stanford union to represent them after
receiving protection under the federal amnesty program for
agricultural workers, Eggleston said Wednesday.
   Other labor groups also are supporting the migrants.
   ``I think this is a step backward in history,'' said Art Pulaski
of the San Mateo County Central Labor Council. ``It's somewhat
reminiscent of the company towns, where the employers control people
not only at work but at home after work ... Stanford University is
acting like a Third World employer here.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
