<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Antarctica     02-16 0131</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Antarctica,0135</SECOND>
<HEAD>European Parliament Calls for Ban on Mining in Antarctica</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STRASBOURG, France (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The European Parliament on Thursday
called for a strict ban on mining in Antarctica and denounced a
proposal to divide the continent's mineral resources among
industrial countries.
   Parliamentarians from the 12-nation European Economic Community
also condemned the Wellington Convention and urged member states not
to ratify it.
   The convention, if ratified, would divide the continent's mineral
resources among the industrial nations.
   The Parliament said if Antarctica's oil and mineral resources are
exploited, it ``could have disastrous effects on its ecosystem and
consequently on the well-being of mankind.''
   The European body said the Antarctic should be set aside as a
nature preserve where all wild animals would be protected and the
natural state would remain intact.
</TEXT>
