<FIRST>r a AM-Mother'sTrunk     02-16 0427</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mother's Trunk,0437</SECOND>
<HEAD>Baby's Skeleton May Have Been Inside Steamer Trunk For More Than
30 Years</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM PAUL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Martha C. Shields told her son and daughter when
they were growing up to stay away from the old brown trunk in the
basement. When she died this week, they found the skeletal remains
of an infant inside.
   State medical examiners Thursday set about determining the age,
sex and cause of death of the infant, who may have been dead 30
years. There is no evidence so far to suggest that any crime was
committed, police said.
   ``Investigators at the scene, assisted by the state crime
laboratory and the medical examiner's office, speculate that the
baby was a full-term baby, and was probably a couple of weeks old,''
said state police spokesman Sgt. Joseph Ireton.
   Mrs. Shields, a 67-year-old widow, died of natural causes Monday
in her home in suburban Elkridge. The skeleton was found in a
steamer trunk Wednesday afternoon by Mrs. Shields' grown daughter
and son, who were going through the woman's effects searching for a
will, said Trooper Mike Davey.
   ``It was a brown steamer trunk, pushed against the wall in the
basement,'' Davey said. ``It had things piled on it and things piled
around it.'' The skeleton was found wrapped in two blankets, he
said, and an old Bible and remnants of a white dress also were found.
   Joyce Shields, 31, and her brother, Robert, 29, told
investigators that when they were young, their mother told them
never to go near the trunk, Davey said.
   But not long before she died, she told them to take care of what
was in the trunk, the officer said, adding, ``It was their
interpretation that it was the will that was in the trunk.''
   Mrs. Shields' children, who declined to comment publicly, told
investigators there had been no family discussion about a child who
died at birth or shortly afterward, Davey said. Nor did they recall
their mother ever being pregnant while they were growing up.
   A search of the home by state police failed to turn up anything
to explain the infant's remains, he said, and a check of state
records found no mention of any child born to Mrs. Shields from 1950
on, other than Joyce and Robert.
   The family had lived in the house in Elkridge for about 20 years.
Before that they lived in Baltimore, Davey said. ``As near as they
(the two children) can recall, when they moved, the trunk went with
them,'' he said.
</TEXT>
