<FIRST>r a AM-SawdustShootout     02-16 0362</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sawdust Shootout,0371</SECOND>
<HEAD>Posse Of Politicians Rides To Rescue Of Wild West Restaurants</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY LOPEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Theme restaurants that sprinkle sawdust on the
floor for a dash of Wild West authenticity won the first round
Thursday in a shootout with the state health department, which calls
the practice unsanitary.
   ``This is regulation gone wild,'' said Rep. Stan Barnes as he
voted for a bill overturning the Department of Health Services
sawdust ban.
   Restaurants with names like the Big Apple and the Satisfied Frog
are pushing a bill to overturn the department and allow sawdust as
long as it is changed daily and sprinkled with a non-toxic fire
retardant. The House Environment Committee approved the measure
Thursday in an 8-4 vote and sent it to the health committee.
   The feud began in earnest a year ago when state and county health
departments cracked the whip on an estimated 25 to 40 restaurants in
the state that sprinkled sawdust on the floor.
   The Bill Johnson's Big Apple chain has used sawdust since 1956
and has served 30 million customers, said Don Kalfas, general
manager of the chain and president of the State Restaurant
Association.
   ``If there were a health hazard, direct or indirect, with
customers during those years and with those numbers, we'd have heard
some feedback,'' he told committee members.
   One of those voting against overturning the ban, Rep. Herb
Guenther, said he enjoyed dining at the Big Apple but ``I don't see
why this issue should be before this body. I'm just not prepared to
usurp the authority given DHS on minor issues.''
   Dr. Steven Englender, who heads the health department's division
of disease prevention services, said sawdust in a dining area is
kicked up by foot traffic and settles on silverware, food and
kitchen tables.
   California and Pennsylvania are the only other states to allows
sawdust, he said, adding that county and local health departments in
Arizona agree that sawdust ``may harbor insects and vermin.''
   As for the requirement that sawdust be changed daily, Englender
said, with inspections averaging two times a year, ``enforcement
obviously would be difficult; compliance would be next to
impossible.''
</TEXT>
