<FIRST>r w AM-Japan-AircraftTechnology     02-16 0468</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Aircraft Technology,470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Delay Japanese Fighter Decision</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARTON REPPERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration has delayed until
mid-March a decision on letting a major U.S. defense contractor work
with Japan to develop and produce a new version of the F-16 fighter,
congressional sources said Thursday.
   Plans to transfer to Japan $7 billion in advanced American
aircraft technology have generated opposition on Capitol Hill to the
deal involving the proposed FSX fighter, which Japan wants to
upgrade its air capabilities by the late 1990s.
   Under the pending agreement, St. Louis-based General Dynamics
would join forces with Japan's Mitsubishi Heavy Industries to
co-develop and co-produce the fighter.
   A congressional source, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
that after considerable jockeying among agencies, the Defense
Department and Commerce Department were asked to study the
strategic, commercial and technological aspects of the project and
do a combined report by March 10.
   The review was ordered at a National Security Council meeting
Tuesday night that had been called on less than 24 hours notice,
according to the source.
   The State Department and the Pentagon, which had taken the lead
in negotiating the FSX agreement, contended that a final decision
should be made this month. The Commerce Department, however, had
sought a delay of 60 to 90 days.
   Other agencies, including the U.S. Trade Representative and the
Labor and Treasury departments, also had been leaning toward
Commerce's position in favor of a thorough review.
   During a White House press briefing Thursday, presidential
spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said only that with regard to the FSX,
``the interagency process is still under way. I would not expect it
to come up in Japan.''
   President Bush will go to Japan next week to attend the funeral
of Emperor Hirohito.
   Proponents of the FSX deal say it is the best that could be
negotiated _ in view of Japanese refusal to buy wholly
American-built planes _ and it fosters beneficial technology
transfer in both directions with Japan while generating income and
jobs for U.S. industry.
   But critics contend the agreement amounts to a technological
giveaway that will enable the Japanese to compete more effectively
against this country in the global aviation market. They argue that
Tokyo should purchase American-made fighters to help offset the $50
billion U.S. trade deficit with Japan.
   On Capitol Hill, a group of 21 senators last week introduced a
resolution declaring they have ``strong reservations'' about the
deal and urging a 60-day delay to allow time for a thorough review.
   General Dynamics, this country's No. 2 defense contractor, has
said that under the deal, it and other U.S. companies will receive
35 percent to 45 percent of the $1.2 billion being spent on
development of the FSX as well as a comparable share of the $5
billion production program.
</TEXT>
