<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     02-16 0461</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0479</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright &amp; Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>THIEF RIVER FALLS, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some moose are spending lots of
time on the town these days.
   With the Thief River frozen over, the animals use it as a highway
to steal into this northwestern Minnesota town where they wander
down residential streets, dine on hedges and apple trees and often
get their pictures taken.
   ``Everybody seems to enjoy them, other than they like to get them
out of their yards,'' said police Officer Tim Miller.
   Usually, they go back home to the woods after police herd them to
the edge of town by slowly driving alongside, maybe yelling, honking
or sounding the siren.
   But these days, three persistent moose just aren't taking hints,
so officers have taken to firing exploding shells to frighten them.
   ``We chase them out and they just come back,'' said Miller, who
has chased off the cow and her calves three times in a week.
   One reason the moose come to town, observers say, is that it's a
lot easier to move around than in the woods, where the snow these
days is moose-belly-deep.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This Hollywood is none too happy with
efforts by Tinseltown on the Pacific Coast to take control of the
city name.
   City commissioners in Florida saw stars _ not the movie variety _
when they learned the name could become the exclusive property of
Hollywood, Calif.
   It seems the Chamber of Commerce of Hollywood, Calif. _ actually
a district of Los Angeles _ filed last month for a trademark on the
name.
   ``We don't believe we should have to get their permission to use
our own city's name,'' Mayor Mara Giulianti said. ``We are a duly
incorporated city, and they aren't even a city.''
   If granted, the trademark would apply throughout the United
States for any commercial use of the name Hollywood, although an
exception would be made for the area within the city limits of
Hollywood, Fla.
   That's not good enough, City Manager Irv Rosenbaum said.
   ``We market tourism nationally,'' he said. ``We're the eighth
largest city in the state. We should be able to use our name
wherever.''
   At least seven other Hollywoods _ in Alabama, Louisiana,
Maryland, Missouri, New Mexico, South Carolina and West Virginia _
would face the same problem, Giulianti said.
   In 1987, the same Chamber of Commerce lost a battle for exclusive
rights to the name when the U.S. Patent and Trademark Office decided
the name did not belong exclusively to Hollywood, Calif.
   The California group changed its application to allow Hollywood,
Fla., to use the name commercially within the city's limits. But the
Californians want control over the name for the rest of the country.
   Hollywood, Fla., plans to fight the trademark application.
</TEXT>
