<FILEID>AP-NR-02-16-89 2002EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Ozone-Containers     02-16 0374</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ozone-Containers,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Makers of Containers Widely Used by Fast-Food Industry Stop Using
CFCs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Makers of foam plastic containers widely used
by fast-food restaurants have stopped using CFCs which contribute to
destruction of the world's ozone layer, a trade group said Thursday.
   It said makers of the food and beverage containers no longer use
fully halogenated chlorofluorocarbons, or CFCs, as an expanding
agent during the manufacturing process.
   When CFCs reach the stratosphere, they break down the ozone layer
that protects the Earth from ultraviolet rays. Increased exposure to
this solar radiation is known to cause skin cancer.
   An international agreement has called for cutting the production
of CFCs by 50 percent by the end of the century and some of the
leading manufacturers have said they intend to phase out production
of CFCs entirely, although no timetable has been set.
   CFCs are most widely used in refrigeration and air-conditionining
systems. Their use as an expanding agent in manufacturing food and
beverage containers always has been small, accounting for less than
3 percent of all CFCs produced.
   But David Dull, whose office at the Environmental Protection
Agency monitors CFC use, said elimination of CFCs from food service
containers is significant because it represents the first time an
entire industry has stopped using the chemicl.
   ``What we're applauding ... is a process, the beginning of a
process,'' Dull said at a news conference held by the Polystyrene
Packaging Council and the Foodservice &amp; Packaging Institute.
   He said the phaseout of CFCs in the making of polystyrene food
containers ``is proof that American industry can develop
inexpensive, technological alternatives to CFCs.''
   Recently, the Polyurethane Foam Association also announced plans
to phase out the use of CFCs in making foam cushioning, he said.
   Joseph Bow, president of the Foodservice &amp; Packaging Institute,
said the makers of the fast-food containers have replaced CFCs in
the production of polystyrene with another chemical that poses a
significantly lesser threat to the ozone layer because it breaks up
at a much lower altitude.
   ``We realize this (replacement) product too has some ozone
depleting potential,'' he said, adding that the industry is
searching for another agent that poses no such threat at all.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
