<FIRST>r w AM-Lufthansa-Airbus     02-16 0252</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lufthansa-Airbus,230</SECOND>
<HEAD>Deal Could be Worth $3 Billion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lufthansa German Airlines has signed a contract
to purchase as many as 30 commerical aircraft from Airbus Industrie
in a deal estimated to be worth as much as $3 billion, Airbus
officials announced Thursday.
   Lufthansa has agreed to purchase 15 Airbus A340 aircraft, which
are to be delivered between September 1992 and March 1994. Lufthansa
will receive both A4340-200s, which seat 222 passengers, and the
larger A340-300s, which have 256-seat cabins.
   According to the contract, signed Wednesday, Lufthansa will
decide later on whether to purchase the additional 15 aircraft.
   Airbus officials said Lufthansa will use the A340s to replace its
fleet of DC10-30 aircraft. The new jets will enable Lufthansa to
offer more non-stop, long-range routes from Germany to the United
States, South America and the Far East, according to Airbus
officials.
   With th Lufthansa order, Airbus now has firm orders, options and
commitments for 110 A340 aircraft.
   Lufthansa's order gives another boost to the commercial jet
industry, which is already enjoying a successful year.
   Earlier this month, American Airlines signed a 142-plane deal
with McDonnell Douglas Corp. The contract was estimated to be worth
as much as $7 billion.
   Last year, $48.5 billion dollars worth of new planes were
ordered, the highest total ever.
   The Lufthansa purchase plan continues a trend predicted by
industry officials, who estimate that the demand to replace aging
aircraft could push annual aircraft sales to $450 billion in 1989
dollars by the year 2005.
</TEXT>
