<DOCNO> AP890216-0170 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-16-89 2014EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Refugees-Detention 390   02-16 0395</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Refugees-Detention, 390</SECOND>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Justice Department is planning to set up a
tent-city detention center where it will hold Central American
refugees while their applications for political asylum are
processed, congressional officials said Thursday.
   Rep. Lamar Smith, R-Texas, said in a statement the tent city on
isolated brushland 15 miles from the U.S.-Mexico border would meet
basic human necessities _ adequate housing, food and sanitary
conditions.
   But Duke Austin, a spokesman for the Immigration and
Naturalization Service, said no course of action has been ``set in
stone'' and the issue is still under review by INS and Attorney
General Dick Thornburgh, who has already said detention is an option.
   Justice Department sources, speaking on condition of anonymity,
said the idea of a tent city is one option under consideration. But
one source indicated it may not be the preferred option saying:
``nobody wants tent cities.''
   More than 2,000 refugees a week are entering the United States
from Central America and most of them do so by crossing the Rio
Grande River near Brownsville, Texas, officials say.
   The plans call for keeping the refugees in tents near the Port
Isabel Service Processing Center where INS is processing their
asylum applications, the congressional officials said.
   But Smith and two congressional aides, who spoke on condition of
anonymity, said the tents would have plywood floors and food would
be provided by contractors. No fences would surround the tents, they
said.
   One congressional aide said the Justice Department policy will
begin after U.S. District Judge Filemon Vela is expected to
reinstate an INS policy that bars asylum-seekers from traveling
beyond the Rio Grande Valley while their applications are pending.
   Vela is supposed to rule in the case Tuesday and Austin said the
INS would discuss its plans for handling the refugees at the court
hearing, but not before.
   Before Vela blocked the INS' no-travel policy Jan. 9, Central
Americans who had crossed the Rio Grande illegally were forced to
live in shanty town conditions _ camped out beneath plastic sheets
in open fields _ or condemned buildings.
   INS officials contend many people seeking asylum are here only to
better themselves economically and use the asylum process and
lengthy appeals to get into the United States. Political asylum is
granted only to those fleeing persecution for political or other
reasons.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
