<FILEID>AP-NR-02-16-89 1808EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Baker     02-16 0525</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Baker,0539</SECOND>
<HEAD>Baker Says Time Not Right for Israeli-Arab Negotiations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III told West
European leaders Thursday the time is not right to push for
negotiations between Israel and the Arabs, a senior U.S. official
said.
   Baker promised, however, to have American diplomats pursue
prospects with the PLO, Israel and Arab states and report the
results in three weeks, the official said.
   ``One has to till the ground carefully; one has to proceed
cautiously and understand that if you push the level of discussion
too high, too soon, and create too much international attention you
might preempt opportunities,'' Baker was quoted as telling the Dutch
foreign minster, Hans van den Broek, at The Hague.
   The U.S. official, briefing reporters on condition of anonymity,
said van den Broek gave Baker a brief account of findings by the
French, Greek and Spanish foreign ministers, whom the 12-nation
European Economic Community appointed to explore Middle East peace
prospects.
   They visited Israel, Egypt, Jordan and Syria earlier this month
and also met with PLO representatives. The U.S. official said they
found areas of potential progress and also obstacles, but he
provided no details.
   Baker's cautious response indicated the Bush administration was
not eager to plunge into the Middle Eastern thicket despite its
contacts with the Palestine Liberation Organization.
   His assurance that the PLO would be sounded out also seemed to
rule out a suspension of the 3-month-old dialogue despite U.S.
irritation over a clash between Palestinian guerrillas and Israeli
forces in southern Lebanon.
   Five guerrillas were slain in what Israel said was an attempted
infiltration of Israel and an act of terrorism. The United States
opened talks with the PLO in December only after its leader, Yasser
Arafat, made a public statement renouncing terrorism.
   The U.S. official said Baker would report results of the U.S.
soundings on the Middle East at the opening of arms control
negotiations between NATO and the Warsaw Pact in Vienna on March 7.
All the Western foreign ministers are expected to attend.
   Baker also met with Manfred Woerner, secretary-general of the
North Atlantic Treaty Organization, as he neared the end of an
eight-day trip to 15 allied countries.
   He is exploring their views on foreign policy and defense before
President Bush decides how to deal with Soviet arms reduction
proposals that have raised hopes of disarmament by West Europeans
and unsettled their leaders.
   U.S. officials said Baker was finding an ``ironic'' situation:
that President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's proposals were largely
inspired by the United States but the West European public was
giving the Soviet leader much of the credit.
   Although Baker gave four news conferences on the first four days
of the trip, he has kept reporters at a distance since and sid
little.
   The secretary of state began the day in Brussels, meeting with
Prime Minister Wilfried Martens and Foreign Minister Leo Tindemans
of Belgium and then with Woerner at NATO headquarters.
   He visited Luxembourg and the Netherlands during the day and
returned to Brussels. Baker will fly back to Washington on Friday
after a visit to France.
</TEXT>
