<FIRST>r i AM-Chile-Pinochet     02-16 0369</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chile-Pinochet,0381</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pinochet Won't Run In December Election</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Military President Augusto Pinochet said
Thursday he will not run in scheduled December presidential
elections, but he urged government supporters to unite to pick ``one
of ours'' as his successor.
   The constitution bars Pinochet from succeeding himself, but
several pro-government politicians have suggested that a formula be
found to allow him to run, such as a constitutional amendment.
   ``I'm not here as a candidate,'' Gen. Pinochet, 72, said at a
luncheon with supporters in Loncoche, a rural community 370 miles
south of Santiago. ``I cannot be a candidate now.''
   The president's remarks, carried by local radio stations, was his
strongest rejection so far of the possibility he might run in the
election, scheduled for Dec. 14.
   Pinochet, who seized power in a violent 1973 coup, was obliged to
call elections after losing an Oct. 5 referendum in which he sought
voters' approval to remain in power until 1997.
   On the third day of an eight-day tour of southern Chile, Pinochet
urged his supporters to restore their unity, which had been badly
disrupted in the wake of the referendum defeat.
   At least two pro-government politicians have announced their
candidacies to succeed Pinochet. A group of independent businessmen
and politicians are actively promoting the nomination of Pinochet's
finance minister, Hernan Buchi. Buchi, 39, so far has refused to
accept the candidacy.
   ``You must work together for a government of ours,'' Pinochet
told his audience. ``It does not make a difference the person who is
nominated, as long he is one of ours. The candidate must be the one
we all pick. That's our man.''
   The opposition also has stated plans to seek a single candidate.
Leaders of a coalition of 17 opposition parties are scheduled to
meet next month to pick from among at least four contenders to the
nomination.
   Patricio Aylwin, a moderate former Senate president, is
considered the frontrunner. Aylwin is president of the centrist
Christian Democratic Party, the largest in the opposition, and was
the chief spokesman for the opposition during the campaign for the
referendum.
   According to the constitution, Pinochet must hand power to the
winner of the December election on March 11, 1990.
</TEXT>
