<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-Herzog     02-16 0404</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Herzog,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush to Meet with Herzog in Tokyo</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush will meet next week with Israeli
President Chaim Herzog in Japan at the funeral of Emperor Hirohito,
American and Israeli sources said Thursday.
   Bush is also expected to meet in Tokyo with Jordan's King Hussein
and Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak, French President Francois
Mitterrand and other world leaders, U.S. officials say.
   The meeting with Herzog is expected to be one of ceremony rather
than substance, since Herzog's role as head of state is largely
cermonial. U.S. officials expect the meetings with the other Mideast
leaders will also be more in the nature of get-acquainted talks than
serious discussions, due to a lack of time.
   Bush will be host to Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir at the
White House in April for talks about the future of the Middle East
peace process, a U.S. official said, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
   In preparation for those talks, Israeli Foreign Minister Moshe
Arens will meet in the second week of March with Secretary of State
James A. Baker III, said the U.S. officials.
   Arens had sought an earlier meeting with Baker while on a
three-day visit to London this week, but was told that Baker's
schedule during his swing through NATO capitals was too hectic to
accommodate him, Israeli sources said, speaking on condition they
not be named.
   The Bush administration has yet to formulate its position toward
future Arab-Israeli peace talks and is still evaluating the latest
developments in the region.
   Among these is the new U.S. opening to the Palestine Liberation
Organization after a 13-year ban on contacts with the group. Bush
and Baker have both expressed caution about the ties to the PLO,
saying it is too soon to tell whether the group is a serious
candidate for peace talks.
   Israel has been urging the new administration to cut off the
talks, saying the group has not changed its anti-Israel agenda
despite a pledge to give up terrorism.
   Both Jordan and Egypt are hoping the new administration will
bring a fresh approach to the 40-year-old Arab-Israeli conflict, but
Baker appears reluctant to rush into the search for a solution which
eluded his predecessor George Shultz.
   U.S. officials say Bush will not make any decisions until after
he meets with the Egyptian, Israeli and Jordanian leaders. Mubarak
is also expected in Washington this spring.
</TEXT>
