<FILEID>AP-NR-02-16-89 2035EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-SavannahRiver     02-16 0400</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Savannah River,390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pipe Break Forces Shutdown At Plutonium Extraction Building</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The operator of the government's
problem-plagued nuclear weapons complex in South Carolina said
Thursday it had discovered a break in an underground pipe that
carries slightly radioactive waste water to a treatment plant.
   E.I. du Pont de Nemours &amp; Co. said it temporarily reduced
operations at the Savannah River Plant chemical separation facility
while it replaced a 10-foot section of the pipe and inspected other
underground pipes of similar construction.
   The company said the waste water that leaked from the broken pipe
was high in acid content with ``minute amounts'' of radioactivity
and posed no danger to workers or the environment.
   Joe Odum, chief supervisor with du Pont's environment and energy
department at Savannah River, said in a telephone interview that
workers first detected a problem early this week when a liquid
accumulation was noticed on the surface. The leaking pipe is eight
inches in diameter and is nine feet underground.
   On Wednesday it was determined that a small section of the pipe
had broken off, Odum said, adding that it was too early to estimate
how long it would take to fix the problem.
   The incident is the latest in a series of technical problems that
have arisen at Savannah River, the site of three U.S. Energy
Department nuclear reactors that produce tritium, a radioactive gas
needed to make most nuclear weapons. All three reactors are shut
down because of safety and technical problems.
   Odum said the pipe leak had no direct affect on the
tritium-producing reactors.
   The chemical separation plant at Savannah River separates
plutonium from used fuel rods from the reactors. The plutonium is
then shipped to the Rocky Flats Plant at Golden, Colo., where it is
shaped into triggers to be used on nuclear warheads.
   Once the plutonium is separated from the high-level radioactive
waste in the used fuel ods, the liquid waste is taken to a tank farm
at Savannah River, where some of the waste is evaporated. The
remaining water, containing what du Pont called minute amounts of
radioactivity, is then piped to an effluent treatment plant for
further purification before it is discharged into streams.
   The pipe that developed the leak was installed at Savannah River
during the 1950s and is made of terra cotta, a thick, hard
pottery-like material widely used in sewer lines at that time.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
