<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Lithuania 1stLd-Writethru   02-16 0748</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Lithuania, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0702,0766</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lithuanian Grass-Roots Movement Calls for `Independence'</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: LEADS with two grafs to CLARIFY that group does not seek full
independence. Pick up 3rd pvs, `The vote...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANN IMSE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Lithuanian political organization that claims
more than 150,000 members agreed to seek an ``independent path'' but
stopped shy of calling for secession from the Soviet Union, one of
its leaders said Thursday.
   The action coincided with the anniversary of Lithuania's original
declaration of independence in 1918. Hundreds of thousands of
Lithuanians turned out for two days of public celebrations, which
were greeted with police dogs and beatings just one year ago.
   The vote late Wednesday night by the national assembly of the
grass-roots group, Sajudis, amounted to the strongest call yet out
of the small Baltic republic for control over its own affairs.
Lithuania has been a part of the Soviet Union since it was annexed
during World War II.
   Small organizations in Lithuania have demanded secession, and
speakers at public rallies have called for removal of the Soviet
``army of occupation.''
   But Sajudis' membership has grown to 150,000-200,000 in a
population of 3.7 million in barely nine months. It is backing
candidates in virtually every electoral district of Lithuania in the
Soviet Union's first multiple-candidate elections for Parliament.
   The vote to strive for an ``independent path'' for Lithuania
passed the Sajudis assembly by a vote of about 204-8, with eight
abstentions, said Alvydas Medalinskas, a spokesman for the group, in
a telephone interview from Vilnius.
   ``It means full political, economic and legal sovereignty,'' he
said. ``But we have many opinions on how to achieve this.''
   The declaration states Sajudis will strive ``to create the
conditions for free and democratic national self-determination,''
according to a text released by a Lithuanian emigre group in New
York. It also said Lithuania should be a neutral state in a European
demilitarized zone.
   Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev rejected any possibility of
Lithuanian secession during a Kremlin meeting with factory workers
Wednesday, but his words were mild.
   ``Those who demand Lithuania secede from the U.S.S.R. are either
people driven by personal or career ambitions, or simply
extremists,'' he told K.M. Ashmonas of the shipyard in Klaipeda,
Lithuania, according to Thursday's newspaper reports.
   ``They do not accept socialism at all, and to expect that they
would protect our value, interests of workers and farmers is
useless. Let us be calm, but let us give them a calm rebuke.
Perestroika has to help us sort out and solve many problems.''
   Lithuanians gathered in cities and towns across the republic for
independence celebrations marked by songs, flowers, a Catholic Mass
at a cathedral and ceremonies at the national cemetery where heroes
of the war of independence are buried.
   A monument to freedom, which had been removed after the Soviet
annexation, was rededicated with a flourish of doves.
   Just one year ago, celebrations of the anniversay ended when
police beat hundreds of demonstrators with rubber truncheons. This
year, the anniversary had government approval.
   Valdas Analauskas, a Lithuanian activist and journalist,
estimated the crowds in Kaunas at 100,000 and in Vilnius at 200,000,
although Medalinskas said celebrants at the Vilnius rally numbered
closer to 80,000.
   The head of the Lithuanian Communist Party even put in a surprise
appearance at the Kaunas rally Thursday morning, Analauskas said in
a telephone interview. Algirdas Brazauskas, the party first
secretary, offered a short speech calling for unity.
   Medalinskas said Sajudis' action was similar to nearby Estonia's
``declaration of sovereignty,'' but noted it was merely the vote of
a grass-roots organization and not a governmental action like the
Estonian constitutional amendments passed in November.
   Estonia's Parliament gave itself the right to overturn Soviet
laws. Moscow promptly declared that unconstitutional but has done
nothing to halt Estonia from selectively exercising its newly
declared authority.
   The revival of Lithuanian nationalism has not been greeted
unanimously in the republic, where 20 percent of the population is
Russian or of other natinality. On Sunday, thousands of mostly
Russian residents of Lithuania gathered in central Vilnius to
demonstrate against a new law defining Lithuanian as a state
language.
   The crowd was estimated at 20,000 to 30,000 by Medalinskas and
100,000 by the Communist Party newspaper Pravda.
   The New York-based Lithuanian Information Center said eight
Americans involved in emigre groups were denied visas to attend the
celebrations. The center quoted government sources as saying
Lithuanian party leader Brazauskas approved the visas but they were
rejected in Moscow.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
