<BYLINE>By MARY SEDOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli troops shot and killed a Palestinian in
a stone-throwing clash in the West Bank Thursday and wounded eight
others, Arab doctors said. A 4-year-old Arab girl died of head
injuries suffered in a mysterious explosion.
   In the West Bank city of Nablus, doctors at Ittihad Hospital said
25-year-old Issam El Bulbul died of a chest wound suffered in a
stone-throwing clash with soldiers. The army had no immediate
comment.
   Arab reports said troops opened fire while pursuing Palestinians
who hurled rocks at an army patrol in Nablus' Old City.
   The death raised to 381 the number of Palestinians killed in the
14-month rebellion against Israeli rule. Fifteen Israelis also have
died.
   Palestinian doctors at east Jerusalem's Mukassad Hospital said
Iktimal Abdullah of Tayasir village in the West Bank died of
injuries suffered three days ago when a device she found near her
home exploded. Her 10-year-old brother Naim was wounded.
   A military source confirmed the death.
   The army started an investigation Wednesday into that blast and
into other unexplained explosions in the West Bank that killed two
other Palestinians and wounded eight.
   The air force also has been asked to look into the explosions
after Palestinians reported seeing helicopters in the area of one
incident.
   In other cases, Palestinians accused Israeli soldiers in jeeps of
throwing out explosive devices that lured unsuspecting children. The
army denied it.
   The army deputy chief of staff, Maj. Gen. Ehud Barak, has said
previous explosions resulted from children playing with undetonated
shells near firing ranges or flares that fell from training jets.
   The West Bank and Gaza Strip were captured by Israel from Jordan
and Egypt in the 1967 Middle East war.
   Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin on Thursday raised the possibility
of talks involving Palestinians from the occupied territories and
Jordan.
   He said on Israel Television's Arabic-language program that
Palestinian negotiators should be chosen in free elections and
indicated he would be flexible about conditions, such as army
withdrawal from voting areas on election days and guarantees that no
one would interfere with the balloting.
   ``There may be different proposals, (Palestinian) committees, no
army on election day in the areas where elections are held. There
may be different ways to guarantee really free elections,'' Rabin
said.
   He said talks would be on a ``political process that would not
immediately reach a permanent solution. We can't resolve that
problem at once.''
   Controversy flared over a new dialogue developing between
prominent Palestinians, headed by PLO supporter Faisal Husseini, and
liberal Israeli politicians and academics.
   Labor Party leader Shimon Peres endorsed the new dialogue and
hinted on armed forces radio that he may take part.
   ``I support meetings with the representatives of Palestinians
from the territories who are not themselves involved in terrorism,''
Peres said.
   Right-wing politicians harshly criticized the talks.
   Yossi Ahimeir, spokesman for Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir, said
the meetings ``will not come to anything. These people are not in
charge of making policy for the state.''
   In Tel Aviv, District Court Judge Arye Segalson sentenced Khalid
Al Kadayem, 19, an Israeli Arab, to three years in prison for
stoning an Israeli passenger train in Lod six months ago, army radio
reported. No one was injured.
   Arab doctors in the Gaza Strip said six Palestinians were wounded
Thursday in protests by teen-agers hurling stones in the Jabaliya,
Shati and Rafah refugee camps and in the Sheikh Radwan neighborhood
of Gaza City. They included a 12-year-old boy shot in the leg and a
14-year-old shot in the abdomen.
   The doctors also said they treated a 21-year-old Nablus Arab shot
in the foot and a teen-ager from Jenin who was wounded in the leg.
