<SECOND>AM-South Africa, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0566,0825</SECOND>
<HEAD>Many Detainees Expected to be Freed After Partial Halt of Fast</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS two grafs after 11th, `Never before...' to UPDATE with
police ordering church goers to disperse. Pick up 12th pvs, `Kathleen Satchwell...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Mandela, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 170 black detainees at a
prison outside Johannesburg halted a 24-day hunger strike Thursday
and proclaimed victory, and anti-apartheid leaders said many
detainees would be freed.
   In Port Elizabeth, however, civil rights workers said 105
detainees at St. Albans prison continued their fast.
   The hunger strikers at Johannesburg's Diepkloof Prison, some of
whom had not eaten since Jan. 23, ended their fast at 7 a.m. ``An
important victory has been won,'' they said in a statement.
   Anglican Archbishop Desmond Tutu, after meeting in Cape Town with
Law and Order Minister Adriaan Vlok, said the government had pledged
to free within two weeks a ``substantial number'' of the estimated
1,000 detainees held without charge nationwide.
   Tutu and other activist clergymen emerged from the meeting to
urge a suspension of the hunger strike. Tutu said a decision on
whether to resume the protest would depend on how many detainees are
freed.
   ``The burden is now on the shoulders of Mr. Vlok,'' Tutu said.
``Our goal is to get all the detainees released and then we will
carry on to change the total structure of apartheid.''
   Vlok issued no statement, but his office described the talks as
``a victory for negotiation.'' The state radio said Vlok gave
permission to the Rev. Frank Chikane, general-secretary of the South
African Council of Churches, to visit the hunger strikers and
discuss the developments.
   The church leaders said Vlok promised to give urgent personal
attention to the cases of individual detainees and told the
delegation the death of any hunger striker would be ``too ghastly to
contemplate.''
   ``A very significant move has happened,'' said Tutu. ``It has
given hope to our people that non-violent action can in fact
sometimes achieve goals they have set for themselves.''
   Tutu later received a standing ovation from about 1,500 people at
a church service in support of the detainees.
   ``Never before has minister Vlok and the government been shaking
in their boots like they are today,'' said activist Cheryl Carolus,
who was at the service.
   As people left the service at the Methodist Metropolitan Church
in Cape Town, they found a police water cannon truck, several vans,
constables armed with shotguns, and a colonel warning them with a
loudspeaker that they had two minutes to disperse or police would
take action.
   An angry Tutu spoke with the police colonel, saying, ``I'm going
to see Mr. Vlok and tell him that your attitude is very
unreasonable.''
   Kathleen Satchwell, a lawyer representing several hunger
strikers, said in Johannesbrug that the government indicated a
majority of the roughly 1,000 people detained nationwide would be
freed soon.
   She said it was not clear how many of those released would be
among the estimated 300 detainees at several prisons participating
in the hunger strike.
   Oliver Tambo, president of the African National Congress
guerrilla movement, said in Harare, Zimbabwe, that the latest
developments proved the strike was ``a jolly good idea.''
   The Diepkloof detainees said their decision was based on concern
for the health of some hunger strikers and on Vlok's pledge to
review their cases.
   ``There have been broken promises in the past. We hope that this
is not the case now,'' their statement said. ``We have succeeded in
our principal objection ... to highlight the desperate plight of
detainees.''
   Ms. Satchwell said there was no specific assurance from the
government about who would be freed. But she said officials had told
her releases would begin immediately.
   Another lawyer, Azhar Cachalia, said detainees who had been
fasting since the start of the strike would need several weeks to
regain enough strength to go free.
   He said the government had given no indication it was considering
ending its policy of detention without trial but was seeking a way
to free a substantial number of detainees without losing face.
   An estimated 30,000 people, most of them black activists, have
been detained for varying periods since a national state of
emergency was declared in 1986.
   Among the clergymen who met with Vlok was the Rev. Allan Boesak,
who had fasted since Monday. He said he was suspending his fast for
two weeks because of the prospect of widespread releases.
   The detainees had threatened to starve themselves to death unless
they were freed or put on trial. More than 20 had been hospitalized,
and fears for their health were growing.
   Vlok had said the government cannot be ``blackmailed'' by a
hunger strike, but he met with civil rights lawyers, clergy and
relatives of the strikers to discuss the crisis.
</TEXT>
