<FIRST>r i AM-Korea     02-16 0210</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Korea,0216</SECOND>
<HEAD>North Agrees to Accept Western Capital For Resort Project</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   North Korea has agreed to let Western
companies join in developing a resort area around scenic Mount
Kumgang in the north, South Korean business tycoon Chung Ju-yung
says.
   Chung, founder of South Korea's largest business conglomerate
Hyundai, told reporters on Wednesday that he proposed Western
participation during his recent visit to Pyongyang, the northern
capital, and the communist side consented.
   Chung said that during his Jan. 23-Feb. 1 visit, he and the north
exchanged documents agreeing to jointly undertake the resort project
if the two governments agree. He did not say how much the project
would cost.
   Chung said he plans to form a consortium with U.S., Japanese,
British, West German and other Western companies to build hotels and
other facilities. He said South Korean firms also may join.
   North Korea, with a low international credit rating, has so far
failed to attract meaningful foreign investment in joint ventures in
the north.
   Chung said he hopes to combine the north's steel, cement and
labor with the south's capital and technology in developing the
Kumgang project.
   He plans to return to the north with engineers in April to
discuss details and for feasibilty studies.
