<FIRST>r i AM-France-Scandal     02-16 0496</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-France-Scandal,0509</SECOND>
<HEAD>Close Friend Of Mitterrand Charged In Stock Scandal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHARLES CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A close friend of President Francois Mitterrand and
four other people were charged Thursday in an insider trading
scandal, judicial sources said.
   Roger-Patrice Pelat confirmed he was charged with receiving
insider information that allowed him to buy shares of the U.S.
company Triangle Industries Inc. shortly before the state-owned
aluminum maker Pechiney SA offered a higher price in a successful
takeover.
   ``I am a bit surprised, but it seems that this is the normal
procedure,'' Pelat, a retired businessman, told reporters after
meeting with investigating Magistrate Edith Boizette.
   Three men were charged with insider trading: Paris stockbrokers
Pierre-Alain Marsan and Ricardo Zavala and an officer in a Paris
investment company, Robert Reiplinger, the judicial sources said on
condition of anonymity.
   The sources said Pelat and a friend, Isabelle Pierco, were
charged with receiving the information and profiting from it. The
charge carries the same maximum penalty as insider trading: two
years in prison and a fine of up to four times the amount illicitly
gained in the deal.
   Pelat, 70, bought 10,000 shares of Triangle stock for himself,
his wife and his two sons on Nov. 16, half for $10 a share and half
for $10.75 a share.
   At that time, Pechiney's takeover offer of $56 per share had been
negotiated and submitted to senior French government officials for
approval. The bid was made public on Nov. 21, sending Triangle's
stock price soaring.
   Pelat sold his and his family's shares during the following week,
getting more than four times the price he had just paid, for a total
profit of about $350,000.
   In a televised interview Sunday, Mitterrand said he knew Pelat as
a man of courage and integrity from their years together in the
French resistance, and before that in a German prisoner of war camp
in 1940.
   ``We were a small group who remained very close. It is rare that
prisoners of war, in such circumstances of misery and solitude, show
as much strength of soul, character and friendship'' as Pelat did,
Mitterrand said.
   But he said if Pelat were found guilty of an offense, ``then in
my role as president I would not be able to maintain the same kind
of friendship I have had with him for so long.''
   On Wednesday, Pelat resigned from the board of directors of Air
France, a spokeswoman for the state-owned airline confirmed Thursday.
   Pelat has said he was tipped to buy Triangle stock by a friend,
Max Theret, a businessman with longstanding ties to the Socialist
Party. Theret, who bought 32,300 Triangle shares the day before
Pelat's purchase, said he came up with the idea from his own stock
research and denied getting inside information.
   Theret has not been charged. He has been hospitalized in recent
weeks with a heart ailment, and French law requires that an
investigating magistrate notify a suspect face-to-face of criminal
charges.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890216-0195 </DOCNO>
