<DOCNO> AP890216-0197 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-16-89 2106EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-VotingRights     02-16 0455</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Voting Rights,0466</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former City Officials Convicted In Settlement Of Voting Rights Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT LEE ZIMMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DANVILLE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five former city officials have been
convicted of illegally guaranteeing themselves jobs as part of a
settlement of a federal voting rights lawsuit, a prosecutor said
Thursday.
   Craig DeArmond, the Vermilion County state's attorney who
prosecuted the non-jury criminal case in December, announced the
decision, which Circuit Judge Paul Komada issued in writing earlier
this week.
   The charges resulted from an agreement in 1987 to do away with
city's system of electing commissioners at large, which blacks
challenged as discriminatory. While instituting a ward system of
electing aldermen, the settlement also kept the four commissioners
on the municipal payroll for three years as executives.
   The former commissioners, Wilbur Scharlau, Ernie Cox, Jerome
Brown and Raymond Randall, were convicted, along with city attorney
Wendell Wright of charges including official misconduct and conflict
of interest.
   ``You can't commit state crimes while settling a federal
voting-rights case,'' said DeArmond. ``Our quarrel was with the
guarantee of jobs to themselves. That's self-dealing ... illegal.''
   ``Generally, I'm disappointed. I think it is the intention of the
defendants to appeal,'' said defense attorney Everett Laury.
   Wright, Randall and Cox have resigned their city jobs. Scharlau
and Brown remained on the payroll.
   DeArmond said the men could face a maximum sentence of five years
in prison. A sentencing hearing is scheduled for April 7.
   When the men were indicted in July 1987, defense attorney Matt
Lydon contended they had negotiated in good faith to reach a voting
rights settlement that would assure a smooth transition in the city
government. He also noted that U.S. District Judge Harold Baker of
Danville had approved the settlement.
   ``The bottom line was regardless of their motivation ...
everything was done in a federal court case and presented to the
court to determine whether it was proper,'' Laury said Thursday.
   Baker set the indictments aside in August 1987. But the 7th U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals reinstated them last April, saying Baker
``probably did not mean to approve the manner of negotiation,'' just
the substance of the settlement.
   The Rev. Roosevelt Davis, one of the black residents who filed
the suit, has said that the plaintiffs did not want the former
commissioners guaranteed city jobs for three years. However, he said
that was necessary in order to gain the settlement.
   Before the settlement, no black had been elected to the city
council in the 60 years the mayor-commissioner system was in place.
About 16 percent of Danville's 39,000 residents are black. After the
mayor-aldermanic form of government began, 14 people, including two
blacks, were elected to the city council from seven wards.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890216-0198 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-16-89 2016EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-AirSecurity 2ndLd-Writethru a0724 02-16 0489</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Air Security, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0724,0501</SECOND>
<HEAD>ICAO Council Priority Review of Air Security</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Flight 103, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS 3 grafs at end with details. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SOLL SUSSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTREAL (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 33-nation council of the U.N. aviation agency
Thursday ordered an urgent study of whether new measures are needed
to meet the security threat posed by terrorist sabotage.
   At a meeting requested by the United States and Britain, the
International Aviation Organization council condemned ``all acts of
unlawful interference against international civil aviation,''
including the Dec. 21 bombing of Pan Am Flight 103 that killed all
259 people aboard and 11 on the ground in Scotland.
   The U.S. and British transportation secretaries told reporters
they considered the two-day meeting of the ICAO advisory body
successful and were satisfied there would be a quick review of
security requirements.
   Samual K. Skinner of the United States said: ``The international
airline traveler can be assured that additional steps are now being
taken, as a result of this meeting, to make international air travel
an even safer mode of transportation.''
   Among issues to be addressed in the review are detecting sabotage
devices, especially explosives, and screening of checked luggage,
passengers and carry-on bags.
   Security problems created by portable radios, computers and other.
   Recommendations for any changes in international standards could
be ready bu late spring or early summer for consideration by the
ICAO membership of 160 nations.
   Paul Channon, the British transportation secretary, suggested a
rule requiring passengers with electronic devices to carry them onto
the plane rather than checking them.
   ``To ban radios altogether would be a very drastic step,'' but it
might have to be considered, he said.
   Allan McArtor, head of the U.S. Federal Aviation Administration,
said new guidance was issued in Washington after Thursday's
announcement in Scotland.
   ``The guidance is more a sense of vigilance than anything else,''
he told reporters.
   Although passengers can expect electronic devices to be checked
more rigorously, an outright ban on carrying them is unlikely,
McArtor said.
   Channon said the costs of increased security might eventually be
reflected in increased ticket prices, but ``we're not talking about
large sums of money.''
   The organization's staff also will be considering whether new
steps are needed to increase the matching of passengers and their
bags, to consider the security problem of cargo, mail and courier
services using passenger aircraft and to control access to airports.
   It also will be discussing the possibility of taking security
considerations into account in the design of aircraft. Channon said,
however, that any design changes would be minor.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
