<FILEID>AP-NR-02-16-89 2112EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-S&amp;LShootings     02-16 0775</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-S&amp;L Shootings,1st Ld-Writethru, a0747,750</SECOND>
<HEAD>Officials Say They Couldn't Have Predicted Former Patient's Behavior</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: SUBS 7th graf to change release date to fall of 1986</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LISA M. HAMM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JESSUP, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Psychiatrists could not have predicted that a
former mental patient would suddenly become homicidal, the head of
Maryland's hospital for the criminally insane said Thursday.
   ``I don't think anyone had the capacity a week ago to predict his
actions,'' said Steven Siebert.
   But Wednesday afternoon, Emanuel Tsegaye, a former patient at the
Clifton T. Perkins Hospital Center walked onto the seventh floor of
the Chevy Chase Federal Savings Bank in Bethesda, Md. where he
worked, shot four co-workers and then turned the gun on himself,
according to Montgomery County police.
   Fatally wounded were Cynthia Mitchell, 28, of Landover; Tanya
Walker, 23, of Fort Washington; and Mahasty Agha-Khan, 29, of Silver
Spring. The lone survivor of the shooting spree, Edward Johnson, 22,
was listed in critical condition at Suburban Hospital in Bethesda
with a gunshot wound to the face.
   Police spokesman George Ludington said investigators were probing
reports that Tsegaye was a ``disgruntled employee,'' in the bank's
Visa credit card department but said the motive for the shooting has
not been determined.
   As recently as Feb. 6, the therapist who had been seeing Tsegaye
biweekly since he was released from the hospital more than two years
ago said the 33-year-old debt collector was functioning well in the
community.
   Nevertheless, Siebert said no mistakes were made in the decision
to release Tsegaye from Perkins in the fall of 1986.
   ``I have not found anything which would make me question the
release decision which was made two years ago,'' he said, explaining
that Tsegaye was never violent to others during his two-year stay at
the facility.
   Tsegaye was sent to Perkins in April 1984, after he approached a
policeman with a knife, pleading with the officer to kill him and a
county circuit judge ruled that Tsegaye was not criminally
responsible for his action, said Siebert.
   Tsegaye's release came after he was evaluated by a treatment
team, an outside mental health professional reviewed the decision
and the judge who originally sent him to the institution was
notified.
   Tsegaye had been seen regularly by a psychiatrist and a social
worker since his release, and had stayed in several halfway houses
before moving into an apartment in Silver Spring, according to
Siebert.
   However Tsegaye had suffered some setbacks, Siebert said.
   Tsegaye was admitted to Washington Adventist Hospital for a week
for treatment of depression last spring, hospital officials said.
   And in July, the Community Forensic Aftercare Office notified the
Montgomery County State's Attorney's Office that Tsegaye was not
keeping his clinic appointments at Hamilton House, a residential
halfway house in Baltimore where he was scheduled for counseling.
   However hospital officials said Tsegaye had resumed his
couseling, and just last week his therapist reported Tsegaye was
complying with the terms of his conditional release.
   Tsegaye had been briefly hospitalized for mental problems five
times before, Siebert said, dating back to the late 1970s when he
reported hearing voices while still in his native Ethiopia.
   Tsegaye had been diagnosed primarily with depression, but St.
Elizabeths Hospital in Washington, where he stayed for three days in
July 1983, diagnosed him as suffering schizoaffective disorder.
   At Perkins, Tsegaye was diagnosed as suffering from bipolar
syndrome or manic depression which was characterized by bouts of
extreme depression, said Siebert.
   One person in 20 suffers from some type of bilopar syndrome,
Siebert said, and 99 percent never perform a violent act, according
to Siebert.
   Siebert and Janet Klein Brown, an attorney assigned to Perkins by
the State's Attorney's office, insisted Tsegaye also had never
demonstrated violent tendencies.
   ``He was in for a suicidal gesture, not violent behavior,'' said
Siebert. During Tsegaye's two years at Perkins, he was involved in
scuffles just three times, and he was never the instigator, Siebert
said.
   ``If we have an inkling that a person is going to be a risk to a
co-worker or employer, we would never recommend that person for
release,'' Siebert said.
   ``I do not have a good explanation for the criminal behavior
yesterday,'' said Siebert, adding there also was no way to know if
Tsegaye's actions were related to his prior mental problems.
   Ms. Brown said the bank wasn't notified of Tsegaye's history
because he wasn't considered a danger and state law doesn't require
notification.
   Authorities aren't sure how Tesgaye, with a background of mental
illness, was able to obtain a gun.
   Perkins has begun an intensive review into the incident, with the
help of outside consultants, Siebert said.
</TEXT>
