<SECOND>AM-Kidnap Murder,0275</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Charged In Kidnap-Slaying Returning To New Jersey</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NR2</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEWTON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 19-year-old man facing charges here in the
fatal stabbing of a teen-age boy and the abduction of a teen-age
girl was being returned Thursday from New Mexico, where he was
arrested.
   Michael Ardila had been held since Tuesday in Santa Rosa, N.M.,
where he was captured when his car overturned during a chase by
state police.
   Ardila is charged in the death of Anthony Pompelio, 17, and the
abduction of Donna Shaban, 17, both of nearby Sparta. Pompelio was
killed early Sunday when he tried to break up an argument between
Ardila and Miss Shaban at the home of a friend.
   Ardila also is accused of stealing a Jeep Cherokee belonging to
Pompelio's father. He waived extradition during a court hearing
Wednesday. Ardila is unemployed and lives in Wantage Township.
   Authorities said Ardila was due to arrive by plane shortly after
midnight. He is scheduled for arraignment Friday at Sussex County
Courthouse in this northwestern New Jersey community.
   Miss Shaban was found Tuesday near Groom, Texas. She told police
Ardila pushed her from the Jeep Cherokee as they drove down a
highway. She returned to New Jersey early Wednesday.
   Pompelio was buried Thursday after a funeral attended by 500
people, including his classmates at Sparta High School.
   ``He was a faithful young man who died defending another,'' said
Monsignor Francis J. Bischoff during services at St. Michael's Roman
Catholic Church in nearby Netcong. ``He would never hurt anyone. He
was just in the wrong place at the wrong time.''
