<FIRST>r i AM-Peru     02-16 0366</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Peru,0377</SECOND>
<HEAD>Peru Miners Strike, Two Killed in Guerrilla Attack</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT SEAVEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Miners across Peru staged a daylong strike
Thursday to protest the slaying of labor leader Saul Cantoral and
said he was killed by a guerrilla group linked to the governemnt.
   Also Thursday, police said Maoist Shining Path guerrillas killed
one policeman and wounded two in an attack a day earlier on a police
post near Chincha, 100 miles south of Lima.
   Other Maoist rebels shot and killed a former governing party
economic development worker in Huancayo, 140 miles east of Lima,
police said.
   The National Mining Society, an organization of mine owners, said
it could not confirm how many of the nation's estimated 70,000
miners stayed off the job Thursday.
   Cantoral, secretary-general of the leftist-led miners' federation
and one of Peru's most powerful labor leaders, was shot to death
late Monday. A female companion was run down by a car and killed in
a Lima slum.
   Government officials blamed the killings on political extremists
and said an investigation was under way to determine if the
attackers were from the Shining Path, the anti-rebel group Rodrigo
Franco Command, or an ultra-right death squad not previously known.
   The miners' federation accused the Rodrigo Franco Command of
carrying out the attack, and it linked the group to the governing
center-left Aprista Party.
   The government has denied any connection with the Franco band,
which emerged a year ago vowing to kill leftist guerrillas and their
supporters.
   Cantoral, 42, became the focus of controversy last year when he
led miners in two crippling national strikes. The walkouts caused
losses of $400 million, one-third of the annual exports from Peru's
most important industry.
   The strikes failed to force mine owners to accept a federation
demand that labor contracts of mine unions be negotiated jointly
rather than on the current union-by-union basis.
   The mine owners charged repeatedly that the strikes were being
manipulated by the Shining Path, which officials said has begun to
infiltrate labor unions.
   The federation in January decided to strike again over labor
contracts. Federation spokesman Leonardo Ramirez said Thursday the
strike is tentatively set for sometime in March.
</TEXT>
