<FIRST>u p AM-Duke-Treen 1stLd-Writethru a0640 02-16 0701</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Duke-Treen, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0640,0717</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush, Reagan Pitch for Candidate Up Against Popular Ex-Klan Leader</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 7 grafs to UPDATE with quotes from Duke telecast,
CORRECT Treen's age to 63 sted 62. Picks up 5th graf: `Under Louisiana's
...; edits remainder to tighten.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NU4</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA ASHTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Republican Party rolled out its big guns
Thursday _ President Bush and former President Reagan _ to keep a
former Ku Klux Klan leader from being elected to the Legislature as
a member of the GOP.
   Letters touting Bush's endorsement of ex-Klansman David Duke's
opponent in the state House race were circulated throughout the
district, while radio commercials featuring Reagan's familiar voice
were broadcast throughout the day.
   ``I can't help but tell you of the high regard I have for one
candidate in the race for the 81st district _ John Treen,'' Reagan
said in the radio spot for the conservative house builder and
longtime Republican.
   Duke, 38, countered with a paid half-hour broadcast on a New
Orleans television in which he declared that neither Bush nor Reagan
knows anything about the issues in the local race.
   ``George Bush hasn't walked in the Irish-Italian parade as I have
down Metairie Road. George Bush hasn't eaten at the lakefront in
Bucktown,'' Duke said.
   ``I know the people of the district _ not George Bush or Ronald
Reagan. I respect both of those men but all I can respond is ...
read my lips, George Bush. No new taxes, and David Duke basically
has the same kind of program that George Bush has advanced.''
   Treen, 63, and Duke, a former grand wizard of the Ku Klux Klan,
are in a runoff Saturday to represent the nearly all-white district
in Metairie, a New Orleans suburb. Duke, who sought the 1988
Democratic presidential nomination but registered Republican in the
fall, led a field of seven candidates with 33 percent of the vote in
the Jan. 21 primary. Treen had 19 percent.
   Under Louisiana's open primary system, the top two vote-getters
in a primary, regardless of party, face each other in the runoff if
no candidate gets half the primary votes. The seat opened when
Metairie's representative was elected to a judgeship.
   The presidential-level endorsements for a state House seat may
have unprecedented.
   ``This is the first time for sure that Ronald Reagan has ever
done it to my knowledge for a state legislative race,'' said state
Republican Party Chairman William Nungesser.
   Bush and Reagan didn't mention Duke in their endorsements, but
state and national Republican officials made it clear that a Duke
victory would harm the party.
   ``It's as if Attila the Hun joined our party,'' said Nungesser.
``All of the sudden Attila the Hun is a Republican candidate. I
don't believe he's changed one bit.''
   ``He is not a Republican and should not pass himself off to be a
Republican,'' said Leslie Goodman, spokeswoman for the Republican
National Committee in Washington. ``We can tolerate a lot in this
party, but the one thing we cannot tolerate is intolerance.''
   ``It has to be political favors being called in,'' Duke said
after Treen received the presidential endorsements. ``I'm really
tired of this. The outside interference in this race is absolutely
ridiculous. It's like the establishment is closing the ranks to
prevent an independent from coming through.''
   Duke has been campaigning door to door this week as publicity
heated up in the race.
   Treen said he received the endorsement from Reagan after a mutual
friend whom he would not identify asked the former president to get
involved.
   Treen was state campaign chairman for Bush's 1980 presidential
bid. His brother, Dave, was Louisiana governor from 1980 to 1984.
   The commercials were paid for by Treen's campaign. Neither Treen
nor Nungesser would say how much they cost.
   Duke has disavowed the Klan, which he said he left in 1980 after
being accused of selling secret membership rolls. He heads a group
called the National Association for the Advancement of White People,
which he says is not racist but a group seeking human rights for
everybody.
   He is opposed to welfare and affirmative action and supports
Louisiana's $75,000 homestead tax exemption.
</TEXT>
