<FIRST>r a AM-Copper-7     02-16 0273</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Copper-7,0281</SECOND>
<HEAD>Searle Motion For New Trial Denied In $8.15 Million Copper-7 Verdict</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURA WILKINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge Thursday refused to
overturn an $8.15 million award against the G.D. Searle &amp; Co. in the
case of a woman who said her infertility was caused by a Searle
birth control device.
   Searle asked for a new trial, claiming juror misconduct, errors
of evidence and excessive punitive damages.
   A U.S. District Court jury last September ordered Searle to pay
$8.15 million to Esther Kociemba, of Elk River. The verdict
supported her claim that a Searle Copper-7 intrauterine birth
control device had triggered a pelvic infection that left her
infertile.
   ``Searle clearly believes that a new trial was warranted based on
the evidence of jury misconduct,'' the company said in a statement
after Judge Robert Renner issued his ruling.
   Searle, based in Skokie, Ill., said it would appeal Renner's
decision to the 8th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals.
   In denying Searle's motions for a new trial, Renner said the
court does not condone improper actions of the jurors. However, he
added, ``after reviewing the record and hearing the testimony of the
individual jurors, the court concludes that the defendant was not
denied a fair trial.''
   The judge said he did not find the verdict excessive.
   The jury verdict was the first award of punitive damages against
Searle for a Copper-7-related illness and it was the largest award.
   About 500 lawsuits have been filed over the Copper-7, the most
widely used IUD in the United States before it was withdrawn from
the U.S. market in January 1986.
</TEXT>
