<FIRST>r i AM-Angola-Rebels     02-16 0290</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Angola-Rebels,0299</SECOND>
<HEAD>Angola Says 108 Rebels Slain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LISBON, Portugal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Angola said Thursday that 108 rebels were
killed during six days of fighting earlier this month in southern
Angola.
   The official Angolan news agency ANGOP said one South African
soldier also died in the fighting Feb. 8-14 in southern Cuando
Cubango province, south of the town of Caiundo. The report was
monitored in Lisbon.
   Angola claims South African forces invaded Cuando Cubango Feb. 8
to support the guerrilla group known as the National Union for the
Total Independence of Angola.
   The rebels deny South African forces entered Angola and say the
fighting led to heavy government losses.
   The ANGOP report claimed the guerrillas were forced to abandon
the offensive after defeats from government forces.
   On Feb. 10, the Angolan government formally protested to South
Africa, saying the invasion broke a regional peace agreement signed
in New York in December.
   South Africa also denies it invaded the southern province and has
called for a meeting of a joint verification commission set up to
monitor the peace accord.
   Under the terms of the U.S.-brokered agreement, South Africa is
barred from aiding the guerrilla group and is to grant independence
to Angola's southern neighbor, Namibia.
   As part of the agreement, about 50,000 Cuban troops have begun
withdrawing from Angola, where they have been helping the Marxist
government fight the U.S.- and South African-backed rebels.
   The rebels, who reject the peace agreement, claimed in a
statement distributed in Lisbon on Thursday that they killed 56
government fighters in two clashes in northern Angola.
   The rebel statement said 51 government troops died during a rebel
attack in Uige province Feb. 14, and five perished in a rebel ambush
the previous day in Malange.
</TEXT>
