<HEAD>Ten Die In Ship Fire</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fire broke out in the engine room of a Indian ship
while it was in dry dock on Thursday, killing 10 Japanese dock
workers, police said.
   The fire aboard the 13,392-ton vessel was put out early Friday
and police found the 10 bodies near the ship's engine room, police
spokesman Tadao Kojima said. Firefighters battled the blaze for 12
hours.
   The blaze aboard the Jag Doot broke out near the ship's engine
room Thursday afternoon at the NKK Asano Dock Corp. in Yokohama, 18
miles south of Tokyo, said Kojima. The cause of fire is still
unknown, he said.
   An NKK official declined to comment on the accident.
   Two females were among the victims of the fire, Kojima said.
   Fire official Mitsuyuki Ishido said 27 dockworkers and some
Indian crewmen were working near the engine room when the fire broke
out. Police said five Indians suffered burns.
   The Jag Doot, owned by Great Eastern Shipping Co. of Bombay,
India, had entered the dry dock earlier Thursday for inspection and
repairs, according to officials.
