<FIRST>u i AM-Salvador 1stLd-Writethru   02-16 0527</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Salvador, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0714,0540</SECOND>
<HEAD>Guerrillas Attacks Kill 12</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with seven grafs to UPDATE with ex-guerrilla assassinated.
Pick up 3rd pvs, `About 60...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leftist guerrillas attacked six
military posts on Thursday, killing at least 12 soldiers and
wounding 14, the military said.
   The fighting between rebels and troops was the first since Jan.
24, when the Farabundo Marti National Liberation Front said it would
participate in elections if they were delayed six months. The
government said it opposed to the proposal.
   Also Thursday, a former guerrilla commander was fatally shot on a
downtown street in San Salvador, police and government sources said.
His attackers were unknown.
   Slain was Miguel Castellanos, 39, who turned against his comrades
after his capture in 1985 and then worked for the government as an
anti-guerrilla propagandist.
   In 1986, he testified before the Congress that Salvadoran
insurgents received arms shipments from Nicaragua. Castellanos, also
known as Napoleon Romero, was director of the government-affiliated
Center for Studies of the National Reality.
   Police and government sources said on condition of anonymity that
two vehicles carrying assailants intercepted the car in which
Castellanos was traveling near the downtown Flor Blanca soccer
stadium..
   They said Castellanos' car was riddled with scores of bullets
from assault rifles. He was killed instantly and driver and
bodyguard were wounded, the sources said.
   About 60 guerrillas attacked the army base at the Entre Rios
cotton cooperative outside Zacatecoluca with mortar and rifle fire,
said Col. Benjamin Canjura, commander of the Army Engineers
detachment in Zacatecoluca, 22 miles southeast of San Salvador.
   Canjura told a news conference that nine soldiers were killed and
11 wounded during the two-hour attack that began at 2 a.m.
   He said the rebels had many casualties, but he said he could not
provide figures.
   The Marxist-led insurgents also launched four bombs at the
headquarters of the 6th Army brigade in Usulutan, 68 miles east of
San Salvador, Col. Jose Tejada said by telephone.
   They also launched four bombs at the headquarters of the elite
Atonal battalion about a mile from the 6th brigade, he said.
   Three bombs cleared the wall around the headquarters, but did not
explode, he said. The one that fell outside the base exploded beside
a house, wounding two civilians, he said.
   Canjura said rebels also attacked before dawn Civil Defense posts
in Jerusalen, Ostuma and Barrio Nuevo, three small towns in his
central military region.
   He said three soldiers were killed and three wounded in those
attacks.
   Army troops guard warehouses of large coffee, cotton and sugar
cane plantations, which are El Salvador's main foreign exchange
earners. Rebels waging a 9-year-old civil war against the
U.S.-backed government try to destroy the products as part of their
strategy of economic sabotage.
   The guerrillas, in a drastic turnabout, offered last month to
participate in this year's presidential election and respect its
result if the vote were postponed from March 19 to September. The
rebels had boycotted and condemned as sham the five previous
national elections this decade.
   They sharply reduced their offensives while the proposal was
being debated.
</TEXT>
