<FIRST>r i AM-Balloonist 1stLd-Writethru   02-16 0406</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Balloonist, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0666,0416</SECOND>
<HEAD>Trans-Pacific Balloonist Drifts North Due To Jet Stream</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with latest position, balloon slowing
down. No pickup. Changes byline</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARI YAMAGUCHI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Japanese balloonist was drifting more slowly than
planned early Friday because of a shifting jet stream that could
whisk him toward Alaska instead of his planned destination of
California, a spokesman said.
   Three days after he set off to become the first solo balloonist
to cross the Pacific Ocean, Fumio Niwa floated east near Torishima
Island, about 1,250 miles southeast of Tokyo, at 9:30 a.m., said
spokesman Naoto Higashi.
   Niwa was floating in his orange-and-blue helium balloon over the
Pacific Ocean at about 35 mph at the south edge of a jet stream,
slower than he had hoped, Higashi said.
   Another spokesman, Hiroaki Tanaka, said the jet stream can carry
him at about 125 mph, but Niwa decided not to enter it fully because
it was angling toward Alaska.
   Originally, Niwa had planned to rise immediately to 26,400 feet
and enter the jet stream, which he calculated would have blown him
the 5,000-mile distance to San Diego in four days.
   Niwa rose to 23,100 feet on Friday, from 15,100 feet on Thursday
night, Tanaka said.
   Despite delays due to slight changes in the angle of the jet
stream, Higashi said Niwa still expected to reach his target by
about Feb. 20. Niwa has supplies for 10 days.
   The 38-year-old balloonist lifted off from Yokohama, southwest of
Tokyo, early Wednesday in a spherical plastic gondola six feet wide
that he had designed himself.
   The capsule is pressurized but has no navigational or heating
equipment. Niwa relies on amateur radio reports based on radio
beacon signals to pinpoint his location.
   The temperature inside the gondola Friday morning was 23 degrees,
and it was minus 13 outside, said Tanaka. Battery-powered electric
coils in Niwa's flight suit keep him warm.
   Niwa quit his job with a computer firm three months ago to
prepare for the flight. He said he planned to sleep during the day
and stay awake at night.
   In 1981, four men reached the United States from Japan by balloon
for the first time, but no one has traveled the distance alone.
   Niwa, who has 1,000 hours of ballooning experience, estimated the
flight would cost about $540,000, which he hopes to regain through a
book and lectures about his experience.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
