<SECOND>AM-Korea-US-Protests,0451</SECOND>
<HEAD>Deaths of Two Koreans Spark Anti-American Protests in Kunsan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two apparently unrelated deaths of
Korean citizens near a U.S. air base in the provincial city of Kusan
led to violent anti-American protests, police and U.S. officials
said Friday.
   Radical students demanding punishment for U.S. servicemen
involved in the deaths held rallies and clashed with riot police
this week, witnesses said.
   U.S. and South Korean authorities are investigating the two
deaths in Kunsan, a port city about 130 miles southwest of Seoul.
   U.S. officials said the incidents were apparently unrelated.
   They said all military personnel at Kunsan Air Base now were
restricted to the base.
   The first death was that of a mushroom grower identified as Chong
Pan-yong, 54, who died Saturday after an altercation in a
residential area of the city.
   Tech. Sgt. Bruce A. Harayda, 29, of Bridgeport, Conn., stationed
at Osan Air Base with the 51st Tactical Fighter Wing, was released
in that case in the custody of Kunsan Air Base authorities, U.S.
officials said. He was visiting Kunsan at the time on the incident.
   On Wednesday, a military vehicle driven by Spec. Dale J. Green of
the 501st Signal Co. struck and killed Song Yun-jae, 36. Green is
based at Kunsan.
   Pvt. Maurice A. Ferrell, also of the 501st, was a passenger in
the vehicle at the time. U.S. officials said the accident occurred
on a city street near a local university.
   U.S. military authorities are holding the two soldiers until
investigations are completed, officials said. Their hometowns were
not available.
   Student sources, reached by telephone in Kunsan, said about 500
students yelling anti-American slogans held a rally Wednesday and
clashed with police in downtown streets for almost three hours until
they were dispersed by tear gas.
   The sources said on condition of anonymity that a rally also was
held Thursday to demand South Korean police punish the U.S. soldiers
involved in the two deaths and that Washington pay compensation to
the families.
   Also Thursday, up to 300 radical students screaming ``Oppose
Bush's visit!'' attacked a U.S. cultural center in downtown Kwangju
with firebombs and steel pipes, and at least six policemen were
hurt, officials said.
   Kwangju lies 180 miles southwest of Seoul, the capital. The
cultural center is favorite target of radicals, who have attacked it
28 times since 1980.
   President Bush is to stop over in South Korea on Feb. 27 on his
way home after attending Emperor Hirohito's funeral in Japan and
visiting China.
   The U.S. Embassy in Seoul said some furniture and fixtures
suffered fire damage in the attack.
</TEXT>
