<DOCNO> AP890216-0220 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-16-89 0608EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a PM-BusinessMirror Adv16   02-16 0610</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Mirror, Adv16,0628</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv16</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release PM Thursday, Feb. 16</HEAD>
<HEAD>When Good Is Bad</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Those ubiquitous ``economic observers'' whose
views are cited so often don't know whether to cheer or worry these
days. The economy has become that confusing.
   The reason: economic growth, normally the most sought-after goal
of policy-makers, has become a cause of concern. Too much growth is
bad. You can take Alan Greenspan's word for it.
   Greenspan, chairman of the Federal Reserve Board, has stated and
restated his view that the six-year-old expansion is headed toward
inflation _ which often precede recessions _ unless growth is
harnessed.
   In a nutshell, his rationale is contained in a statement made
last summer to the Senate Banking Committee, to wit:
   ``Considering the already limited slack in available labor and
capital resources, a leveling of the unemployment and capacity
utilization rates is essential if more intense inflationary
pressures are to be avoided in the period ahead.''
   Ever since, he has been putting upward pressure on interest
rates, the better to slow growth.
   It creates a perplexing situation for ordinary folks to
understand. There are even hints from time to time that President
Bush may be among the perplexed.
   More than once the president has stated that he and Greenspan
aren't far apart in their approaches to the economy. But then the
president has stated that he isn't nearly as concerned about
inflation as Greenspan is.
   At most times, 4 percent economic growth would be reason to
cheer. So would a sharp decline in unemployment, a rise in the rate
at which the nation's factories are utilized, higher retail sales,
consumer confidence _ and more.
   To some extent, these and other factors are still described as
evidences of health, strength and vigor. But the descriptions are
barely uttered when the caveats follow. Typical: ``Of course, the
threat of inflation. ...''
   For most Americans it is difficult to believe that growth is bad,
since economic growth has been a continuing theme of the country's
history. Moreover, isn't growth needed in order for America to meet
foreign competition?
   Yes. But Greenspan and like-thinkers say a nation's capacity to
produce is limited by the manpower, money and machines at its
disposal. As they see it, we are now straining all three resources.
   When that happens the economy begins to smoke. It becomes
stressed, less productive, because it must rely on less efficient
manpower and plants. Rather than producing goods and services, the
economy manufactures higher prices.
   Not everyone agrees with the slow-growth theme, and notable among
them is Edward Yardeni, economics director at Prudential-Bache
Securities. Yardeni is so outspoken that a year from now he will be
either hero or bum.
   ``We think growth is good,'' he stated in a recent newsletter.
``We believe (Greenspan) is exaggerating the inflationary risks.''
   Moreover, Yardeni contends, much of recent economic activity has
been in the expansion of capital goods, which expand domestic
capacity and boost exports. To Yardeni, this is a critical
consideration. He explains:
   ``If Mr. Greenspan turns the screws too tight, he could snuff out
the capital spending boom we need to expand the capacity that he
fears there isn't enough of.''
   Of course, Yardeni says, it is true that tight monetary policy
can increase slack by depressing economic demand. But his approach
is the opposite: ``We prefer policies that create slack by letting
capacity grow.''
   Ah, there's the problem to which the answer is so elusive. Is
growth good or bad? Do we slow down or do we speed up? Do we cheer
or do we worry?
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Thurs., Feb. 16</NOTE>
</DOC>
