<FIRST>a e PM-TV-`PassionandParadise     02-16 0688</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-TV-`Passion and Paradise,' ADV 17,0707</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv17</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Fri PMs, Feb. 17, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>`Passion and Paradise' Lacks Both</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Well, we're all just so pleased that the cast and
crew of ABC's ``Passion and Paradise'' got to do part of the winter
filming in Jamaica.
   That seems to be the best result of this two-part movie, no doubt
named ``Passion and Paradise'' because such a title will draw more
viewers than the more apt ``Tedium and Purgatory.''
   Was it only a week ago that we were hailing the triumph of
quality in ``Lonesome Dove?'' Back to reality, folks.
   This is a mostly muddled attempt to make a suspense yarn out of
the real-life 1943 murder of Sir Harry Oakes, a fabulously wealthy
American miner who traded gold for British title and a plantation in
the Bahamas. Oakes' murder was never solved, though it likely was
linked to his opposition to legalized gambling on the islands, a
development sorely desired by organized crime.
   The movie, which airs Sunday and Tuesday, sports a rather bizarre
cast. Yes, Rod Steiger and Mariette Hartley _ together at last!
   Steiger and Hartley are actually not bad as Oakes and his wife,
saddled as they are with a lurching script that provides ample
opportunity for great fits of overacting. Steiger, playing the
doomed Sir Harry, manages to last through the first installment.
   In the second, Hartley shrieks at one point, ``Kill me! Kill me
now!'' This seems to be part of the dialogue and not a spontaneous
plea to be released from the proceedings.
   Armand Assante, looking like Napoleon in exile, seems to be
making a career out of slouching through overwrought network
miniseries. He plays Alfred De Marigny, a count-slash-chicken-farmer
who casts aside his history of fortune-hunting to woo and win Sir
Harry's winsome _ and very rich _ daughter, Nancy. She is played
with fretful consternation by Catherine Mary Stewart, whose reaction
to tragedy seems remarkably similar to observing a run in one's
stocking. When Nancy discovers that Alfred has a wife, she
complains, ``Do you know what this makes me feel like?'' A new
agent, perhaps?
   Oakes is bludgeoned and burned in what appeared to be a voodoo
ceremony _ there was an uprising among native workers at the time.
The rest of the movie is taken up with Alfred's mind-numbing murder
trial, interspersed with scenes that attempt to portray everyone
else as still a suspect. This is the writing-directing equivalent of
trying to keep several plates spinning at one time.
   But mystery turns to melodrama. The villains _ Mafia stereotypes
partnered with snooty Britons _ have all the subtly of a herd of
Snidely Whiplashes. Michael Sarrazin does, however, do an admirably
oily job of playing the gangsters' evil emissary to the islands.
   It seems the gangsters are in cahoots with the Duke and Duchess
of Windsor (Andrew Ray and Linda Griffiths), a dastardly and
enormously amusing pair.
   The duke was governor of the Bahamas during World War II. ``I
want that casino,'' the duchess pouts to the duke. ``If I can't be
queen of England, I'll make my own kingdom here.''
   ``Why can't it be like the old days between us?'' he whines.
   ``It can be,'' she purrs. ``You'll think of something, won't
you?'' and plants a wet one on him in case he doesn't get the
picture.
   Late in the movie _ if you last this long, please consult a
physician _ there's an entirely new twist when Wayne Rogers arrives
impersonating Columbo, or in this case cheerfully frumpy private eye
Raymond Schindler, whom Nancy has brought from the States to help
prove Alfred's innocence.
   Since we know the case was never solved, we know the outcome of
the trial. But that's not the end of the movie. Schindler ensconces
himself on a sofa to propound his own cockamamie theory about what
really happened to Oakes.
   In a surprise ending it turns out there was really no reason to
make a movie about the whole messy business at all.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Fri PMs, Feb. 17</NOTE>
</DOC>
