<FIRST>a i AM-China-Bush'sFriends Adv24   02-16 0759</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Bush's Friends, Adv 24,0783</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv24</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Fri AMs Feb. 24 or Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Chinese Friends of President Bush Look Forward to His Visit</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Note Bush is due in China Feb. 25.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN POMFRET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Rev. Kan Xueqing says his prayers have been
answered. One of his flock, George Bush, has been elected president
of the United States.
   ``God has his own plan,'' said Kan, as he sat smiling in an
antechamber of his church in a bustling section of Beijing. ``He
arranges things in wondrous ways.''
   Bush's former tennis coach Wang Huailong says he'd love to get a
game in with the president when he comes to China Feb. 25-27, after
the funeral of Emperor Hirohito in Tokyo, but his old tennis partner
will probably be too busy.
   ``I'd like to see whether his backhand has improved,'' said Wang,
wearing a Japanese track suit at Beijing's International Club. ``He
never beat me in singles so I'd like to give him another shot.''
   Bush and his wife Barbara lived in China from September 1974 to
October 1975 when he headed the U.S. Liaison Office set up in the
early days of U.S.-Chinese rapprochement that resulted in full
diplomatic relations in 1979. Bush became chief of the Central
Intelligence Agency in Washington after leaving China.
   China considers Bush an ``old friend,'' an important moniker in
this land where the distinction between friends and enemy is clear.
The government openly rooted for Bush to win the presidency and
Chinese leaders were pleased when he was elected.
   But when the Bushes lived here, Beijing was a forbidding place
for foreigners.
   China was still in the throes of the ultra-leftist Cultural
Revolution. Chinese were not allowed to talk to foreigners and were
often questioned by police if they did.
   To cut some of the isolation, Bush and his wife often left their
U.S. government car at home and rode ``Forever'' brand Chinese
bicycles.
   They went to Sunday church services for foreigners. Bush played
tennis daily at the International Club while Mrs. Bush dabbled in
Tai Ch'i, a Chinese breathing exercise.
   Mostly they fraternized with other foreigners because of the
conditions at the time.
   ``In 1975, hardly anyone Chinese outside of the Foreign Ministry
would speak to us,'' said a Western diplomat, who served in Beijing
in the 1970s. ``We were pariah, dangerous. So we made do with
ourselves.''
   Coach Wang was one of the few Chinese Bush saw almost every day.
   ``He'd ride down here on his bicycle. Tennis balls in one basket,
and soda pop and ice in another,'' said Wang. ``I was always glad to
play him because that meant I could share his cold drinks.''
   Wang said Bush was a pretty good player in doubles but was a
little weak in singles.
   ``I remember when he would win a point with a good shot, he'd
always fall to his knees and stick his arms in the air,'' said Wang,
laughing. ``He was a pretty jolly fellow.''
   Wang wasn't the only one impressed by the Bushes' bicycles.
   ``The moment I saw the Bushes riding toward our little church I
knew there was something special about them,'' said Kan. ``They
didn't put on snobbish, diplomatic airs.''
   Kan and his colleague, the Rev. Shi Zesheng, met the Bushes
regularly. At the request of the diplomatic community, the pair, who
had been forced to work in the countryside during the early part of
the Cultural Revolution, began Christian church services for
foreigners only.
   The services took place in the old Bible House. Kan and Shi were
not allowed to preach but Kan led hymns and Shi accompanied on the
piano.
   ``I remember one winter day very clearly,'' said Kan. ``Mr. Bush
was late. Instead of hanging up his big blue cotton coat, he rolled
it up and stuffed it under his chair. I remember thinking, `He
really is a regular guy.'''
   Another day stands out in Shi's mind _ ``the day we baptized Mr.
Bush's daughter.''
   It was Aug. 8, 1975, the 16th birthday of Dorothy Bush, now
Dorothy Bush LeBlond.
   ``He wanted to give her a special present,'' Shi said. ``So we
talked with our superiors and they agreed to let us baptize her.''
   Shi presented the family with a baptismal certificate, done in
his own calligraphy.
   Kan and Shi said they too supported Bush's presidential candidacy.
   ``I still pray for him,'' said Kan. ``I have requested God to
watch over him, this good friend of China.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Fri AMs, Feb. 24</NOTE>
