<FIRST>s w BC-Bush-Asia Adv19   02-16 0850</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Bush-Asia, Adv 19,0871</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv19</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release AMs Feb. 19 and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bush's First Overseas Journey as President High on Symbolism</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Retransmitting to CORRECT file number</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Veteran globe-trotter George Bush sets out
Wednesday on his first overseas journey as president, a fast-paced
trip to three Asian nations anxious about America's budget problems
and its military commitments abroad.
   Over 5{ days, Bush will travel to Japan, China, South Korea and
back home again. More than 36 hours of his time will be spent on Air
Force One flying from place to place.
   Playing down expectations, White House officials said the trip
offers an opportunity to demonstrate resolve and affinity with
friends and the region. ``It would be unreasonable to expect major
resolution of policy issues four weeks into the administration,''
one official said.
   ``Symbolically it's important,'' said Robert A. Scalapino,
director of the Institute of East Asian Studies at the University of
California at Berkeley. ``There's no region in the world in which we
have greater economic, political and strategic interests.
   The trip originated with Bush's decision to attend the funeral
Friday of Japanese Emperor Hirohito, which will attract scores of
world leaders. The president has defended his decision to attend the
funeral amid criticism from those who still resent Hirohito's role
in World War II.
   ``I'm doing what's right,'' the president said recently.
   Bush, a former Navy aviator whose plane was shot down by the
Japanese in the Pacific in 1944, said, ``We have a good relationship
with Japan. I want to see it even better. And this doesn't concern
me a bit. And you're talking to a person who was in combat in World
War II. I feel you look ahead, not always look back. You do what's
right.''
   Taking advantage of the occasion, Bush will hold separate talks
in Tokyo with 16 to 20 heads of state or government, including
French President Francois Mitterrand, Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak, Jordan's King Hussein and Philippine President Corazon
Aquino.
   Bush's trip comes at a time of concern in Asia that budget and
trade deficits could prompt the United States to scale down its
defense commitments or to demand that allies shoulder a bigger share
of regional security costs. In particular, there are tensions over
the big trade imbalances that Japan and South Korea have with the
United States.
   ``There is a good deal of anxiety in this region about the future
of the American economy, the degree to which our strategic
commitments might be cut back,'' said Scalapino.
   Bush will meet in Tokyo with Japanese Prime Minister Noboru
Takeshita, their second visit in three weeks following a White House
conference Feb. 2. White House officials believe Takeshita's
attention will be diverted by the funeral and his role as host for
foreign dignitaries, and that there will not be much opportunity to
tackle substantive issues.
   After two nights in Tokyo, Bush will fly to Beijing for a
nostalgic visit to a country where he served for more than a year as
the U.S. envoy. He will visit major landmarks such as the Great Hall
of the People and meet with Chinese leaders, including 84-year-old
Deng Xiaoping, Communist Party General Secretary Zhao Ziyang and
Premier Li Peng.
   Bush will spend two nights in Beijing and then take an early
morning flight to South Korea.
   With anti-Americanism on the rise from both the left and the
right, Seoul is bracing for demonstrations during Bush's stop.
   Bush will be there less than five hours, visiting President Roh
Tae Woo at the presidential palace called the Blue House and
delivering a speech at the National Assembly. Traveling by
helicopter, Bush will not be exposed to any disruptions by
demonstrators.
   Bush, who visited 74 countries in his eight years as vice
president, stopped in Japan, South Korea and China during a 1982
journey. He visited Japan again in 1984 and China again in 1985.
   Some commentators have suggested that Bush's visit to Beijing _
before any trip to Moscow _ is a snub to the Kremlin. However, Bush
denied that he was trying to play China off against the Soviet
Union, saying recently, ``There's nothing of that nature in this
visit.''
   Bush's visit to Beijing comes amid a warming in relations between
China and the Soviet Union. Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev will go
to Beijing in May for the first Sino-Soviet summit in three decades.
   Scalapino said he expects Bush will welcome improvement in
Sino-Soviet relations ``because they may make possible settlements
of some of the more thorny political issues in Asia,'' such as the
divisions between North and South Korea.
   Bush said that since he already would be in Japan, a stop in
China ``just seemed like an appropriate visit.''
   Administration officials said it would have been a slight to the
Seoul government if he didn't stop there, as well.
   ``The very fact he's giving a public speech is in itself of some
significance,'' said Scalapino. ``How many presidents have addressed
the Korean National Assembly?''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for AMs Sun Feb. 19 and thereafter</NOTE>
</DOC>
