<FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     02-16 0783</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0816</SECOND>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. industry is using more of its capacity
than at any other time in nearly a decade, the government said in a
report that showed operating rates approaching levels that could
worsen inflation.
   The stock and bond markets were not alarmed by Wednesday's
report. Bond prices rose modestly and the Dow Jones average of 30
industrials climbed 22.68 points to 2,303.93. The dollar fell
sharply but later made back most of its losses.
   The Federal Reserve Board said January's operating rate of 84.4
percent of capacity was unchanged from December, for which the
figure was revised upward from an earlier estimate of 84.2 percent.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Business inventories rose 0.9 percent in
December and sales increased at almost the same pace despite a
buildup in stockpiles of unsold autos as car purchases lagged, the
government said.
   The Commerce Department said Wednesday that inventories held on
shelves and back lots rose to a seasonally adjusted $760.6 billion
in December, while sales reached $508.2 billion.
   December's 0.9 percent increase in inventories followed a 0.4
percent increase in November. Sales, meanwhile, rose 0.8 percent in
December following a 0.4 percent increase in November.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil imports last month surged to the highest rate
since 1980 as domestic production fell and consumption rose,
reviving fears that foreign producers may soon control more than
half of U.S. oil supplies, energy analysts said.
   The American Petroleum Institute, which represents major oil
producers and refiners, said Wednesday that U.S. crude oil
production fell to 7.9 million barrels a day, a 3.4 percent drop
from January 1988.
   Alaskan oil production, which in recent years offset declines in
other parts of the United States, slipped for the second straight
month with no major new oil fields tapped. About a quarter of U.S.
oil comes from Alaska.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Consumer activist Ralph Nader called on
President Bush and Congress to force rich people, stock traders and
corporations, rather than average taxpayers, to pay for the savings
and loan crisis.
   ``If the bankers and the bureaucrats think they're going to
resolve this massive savings and loan crime on the backs of tens of
millions of ordinary U.S. taxpayers as part of their little
inner-Washington club deliberation, they're wrong,'' Nader said
Wednesday.
   Bush last week announced a proposal to spend $200 billion over
the next 30 years _ about half of it from general tax revenues _ to
sell or close 350 insolvent institutions and meet government
commitments made last year in the rescue of another 205 S&amp;Ls.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>STAMFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Union Carbide Corp. became a takeover
target after the 1984 Bhopal gas leak depressed its stock, and some
analysts said the chemical giant could face another raid with the
cloud of Bhopal lifted.
   But others said Wednesday the surge in Carbide stock incited by
the settlement that was announced Tuesday could help protect the
company from a takeover by making it more expensive to acquire.
   Carbide agreed Tuesday to a Supreme Court of India ruling that
ordered the company to pay $470 million by March 31 to settle all
claims stemming from the Bhopal gas leak, which left more than 3,300
people dead.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The militant Machinists union announced overwhelming
support for a strike against Eastern Airlines next month unless a
contract is signed, while the carrier charged that an illegal work
slowdown has backed up 19 aircraft and delayed flights.
   In another development Wednesday, the union contended that
Eastern management has brought recruitment of possible
strikebreakers to its home turf.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A ``supercomputer on a chip'' developed by Intel
Corp. and hailed as a technical marvel by engineers will be offered
as the basis for a new line of high-speed computers, a senior Intel
executive said.
   Intel's N-10 chip was introduced Wednesday at the International
Solid State Circuits Conference, the world chip industry's biggest
research meeting of the year.
   The United States continues to dominate in processor chips _ the
brains of computers _ even though Japan has taken over most of the
world market for memory chips.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>By The Associated Press</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Blue chips led the way as the stock market rallied Wednesday,
breaking out of a week-long slump. The Dow Jones average of 30
industrials climbed 22.68 points to 2,303.93.
   The dollar retreated across a broad front before recovering some
lost ground. Gold prices fell.
   A change in perceptions about the near-term prospects for
interest rates helped lift bond prices.
   Energy futures prices broke through an important price barrier
and posted significant gains; soybeans rose modestly; platinum
surged; and cattle and pork futures were down slightly.
</TEXT>
