<DOCNO> AP890216-0238 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-16-89 0252EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Low-CalorieDinner Bjt   02-16 0591</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Low-Calorie Dinner, Bjt,0610</SECOND>
<HEAD>Healthier Frozen Dinner Line Stems From Chairman's Heart Attack</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY40 of Feb. 15</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The country's healthiest line of supermarket
frozen dinners owes its existence to the heart attack of an
agribusiness giant _ Charles M. Harper, the 6-foot-6 chairman and
chief executive of ConAgra Inc.
   The idea for a lower-fat, lower-salt line of frozen dinners came
to Harper as he lay recuperating from the heart attack that struck
him on a business trip Sept. 14, 1985, he says.
   Healthy Choice was served up to the national press Wednesday on
plastic trays by maroon-jacketed waiters at New York's posh Plaza
hotel, with Harper on the dais.
   ``This isn't just for people on restricted diets. This is for
healthy people that like to be healthy,'' Harper said in an
interview.
   The low-calorie segment of the frozen dinner market is the
fastest-growing, expanding an average of 24 percent a year from 1983
to 1987, according to Business Trends Inc., a market research firm.
It estimated that 1987 sales of low-calorie meals reached $1.5
billion.
   Harper said he issued the challenge to his research and
development staff after his wife, Josie, invented some healthful but
tasty dishes at home, convincing him that ConAgra could do the same.
   ``To make it taste good _ that was the toughest thing. There's an
entertainment value to food,'' he said.
   Other low-calorie frozen dinner lines have some dishes that are
low in fat and relatively low in salt, but ConAgra's entry is more
consistently healthy, nutrition experts said.
   Healthy Choice meets the dietary recommendations of the American
Heart Association and the National Institutes of Health, although it
does not have their endorsement.
   ``A consumer can buy the Healthy Choice and know that they're
going to get lower sodium, lower fat. With the others you have to
read the label to find out,'' Evelyn Tribole, a dietitian and
spokeswoman for the American Dietetic Association, said in a
telephone interview.
   Most companies do a lot of their calorie-cutting simply by making
portions smaller, Ms. Tribole said. Healthy Choice portions are
heavier than the competition's.
   Darlene Doherty, president of the association, said the closest
products to Healthy Choice are frozen-dinner lines that Baxter
International Inc. and Diamond Crystal Specialty Foods Inc. sell to
health-care facilities for distribution to patients.
   ConAgra is second in the overall frozen-dinner market, with a 28
percent share, behind Campbell Soup Co.'s 29 percent, according to
Business Trends. ConAgra's other principal brands are Banquet,
Armour, Morton, Patio, Chun King and Sensible Chef.
   Healthy Choice is already available in about a quarter of the
country.
   ConAgra has no plans to reduce fat and salt in all its
frozen-dinner brands, even though it would make them more healthful,
Harper said. ``We will continue to make products that people want.''
   As an example of Healthy Choice's nutritional breakdown, its
chicken parmigiana dinner has 290 calories, 65 milligrams of
cholesterol and 320 milligrams of sodium. It derives 15 percent of
its calories from fat, and 6 percent of those calories from
saturated fat.
   By comparison, Campbell's Le Menu chicken parmigiana dinner has
380 calories, 890 milligrams of sodium and 43 percent of its
calories from fat. Figures on cholesterol and saturated fat are not
available.
   The Weight Watchers brand equivalent, which is an entree rather
than a full meal, has 280 calories, 85 milligrams of cholesterol,
840 milligrams of sodium, 51 percent of its calories from fat, and
19 percent of those calories from saturated fat.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890216-0239 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-16-89 0245EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-India-CarbideSpeculation Bjt   02-16 0684</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-India-Carbide Speculation, Bjt,0706</SECOND>
<HEAD>Analysts Divided On Whether Bhopal Settlement Increases Takeover
Chances</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENT LAYMON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STAMFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Union Carbide Corp. could face another
takeover attempt now that the cloud of the Bhopal gas leak has
lifted, though the rise in its stock price after the settlement was
announced could provide protection, analysts say.
   Carbide agreed Tuesday to a Supreme Court of India ruling that
ordered the company to pay $470 million by March 31 to settle all
claims stemming from the 1984 accident, which killed more than 3,300
people.
   The settlement, which is expected to have only a minor effect on
the company's earnings, ended speculation about how much the Bhopal
incident would cost Danbury-based Carbide.
   ``There are a lot of companies that would be interested in the
mix and quality of Carbide's component assets,'' said Barry Sahgal,
director of research at Ladenburg, Thalmann &amp; Co. in New York.
   ``It's just a guessing game, but what one can certainly focus on
is the undervaluation of Carbide's assets in the marketplace,'' he
said Wednesday. ``It's an upstock. It's attractive for investors.
The risk reward looks quite compelling.''
   News of the settlement sent Carbide's stock soaring by $2 a share
Tuesday in heavy trading to close at $31.125. It advanced another
$1.375 Wednesday to $32.50, its highest level over the past year.
   ``I'm in the camp that says (the settlement) does not make them a
more attractive candidate,'' said James Wilbur, a vice president
with Smith Barney, Harris Upham &amp; Co. Inc. in New York.
   ``While the settlement of the Bhopal issues does relieve that
concern about liability ... the increase in the price yesterday
makes a takeover about $270 million more expensive.''
   Even before the settlement, Wall Street was rife with speculation
that a takeover bid could emerge. One rumor Feb. 7 pushed Carbide up
$2 a share with more than 9.16 million shares traded, several times
the ordinary volume.
   There has been talk that Carbide might fetch $50 a share as the
target of a takeover fight, which would make the total value of the
company about $7 billion. Carbide has approximately 140 million
shares outstanding.
   Three names have been mentioned as possible suitors, including
investor Edmund Safra of Safra Republic Holdings, an unidentified
West German chemical Co. and Carl C. Icahn, the well-known takeover
strategist.
   Wilbur suggested that last week's surge simply reflected
investors' desire to take advantage of the 25 percent increase in
the company's quarterly dividend, from 20 to 25 cents a share.
   Carbide increased its dividend in January after slashing it from
$1.50 to 80 cents a share last summer. The move traumatized
stockholders and sent stock plummeting to about $17 a share.
   That would have been a more logical time to attempt a takeover,
Wilbur said.
   ``We have identified at least at eight other companies that would
produce returns to a takeover group that would be higher than Union
Carbide'' right now, he said.
   One stock speculator who requested anonymity said the takeover
talk is ``probably all hot air.''
   ``Right now it's just a $7 billion company that doesn't have the
overhang anymore,'' he said. ``But there are lots of company's that
don't have an overhang.''
   Carbide is vastly different from the far-flung, flourishing
conglomerate it was before the Bhopal catastrophe. It was well known
for consumer products ranging from Eveready batteries to Glad
sandwich bags.
   Its stock fell from about $50 a share to about $35 after the
disaster, leading to a hostile takeover attempt by the much-smaller
GAF Corp. in 1985.
   To fight the takeover, Carbide sold its consumer divisions and
undertook other drastic restructuring steps, including the sale and
lease-back of its headquarters building. Sales slipped to $6.4
billion in 1985 and the company's work force was halved.
   Even before Tuesday's settlement, analysts had said Carbide was
well on its way back.
   In the year ended Dec. 31, the company earned $720 million, or
$5.31 a share, on revenue of $8.32 billion. That compared with 1987
earnings of $231 million, or $1.76 a share, on revenue of $6.91
billion.
</TEXT>
