<FIRST>u f PM-Dollar-Gold     02-16 0269</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0283</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar, Gold Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar firmed in early European trading today.
Gold prices also rose.
   Traders in Milan, Italy, said the market was looking ahead to
Friday's release of the December U.S. trade result.
   ``Naturally a monthly deficit under $10 billion will guarantee a
major dollar rally,'' said one trader. The U.S. merchandise trade
deficit widened sharply to $12.5 billion in November from $10.3
billion in October.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar rose 0.43 yen to a closing 126.33. Later, in London, it
was quoted at 126.53 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Wednesday's
rate included: 1.8438 West German marks, up from 1.8315; 1.5655
Swiss francs, up from 1.5565; 6.2783 French francs, up from 6.2425;
2.0788 Dutch guilders, up from 2.0680; 1,352.75 Italian lire, up
from 1,339.50; and, 1.1825 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1800.
   In London, one British pound cost $1.7665, cheaper for buyers
than $1.7805 Wednesday.
   Gold prices rose in Europe.
   ``It's amazing,'' said one London bullion dealer. ``One day gold
falls out of bed and the next day people want to buy it.''
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $383.35 a troy ounce, up
from $382.00 bid late Wednesday. At midmorning, the city's five
major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $384.25.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $383.35, up from $381.60 bid late
Wednesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose 54 cents to close at a bid
$385.20.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $5.88 a troy ounce,
up from Wednesday's $5.79.
</TEXT>
