<FILEID>AP-NR-02-16-89 0737EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-AutoSafety     02-16 0495</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Auto Safety,0525</SECOND>
<HEAD>NHTSA Upgrades Probes of More Than 2 Million GM Cars</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM BOVEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal regulators have intensified three
separate investigations of alleged braking problems and other safety
defects involving more than 2 million General Motors Corp. cars.
   The National Highway Traffic Safety Administration said Wednesday
it had received 428 complaints of poor braking in GM's A-, J- and
N-body cars made in 1987 and 1988.
   The alleged braking problems, according to the unconfirmed
complaints, had resulted in 85 accidents and 29 injuries, NHTSA said.
   The complaints said drivers of the cars had reported brake
failure in some cases and in others an increase in braking distance
to beyond the limits of safety.
   The A-body cars are the Pontiac 6000, Buick Century, Chevrolet
Celebrity and Cutlass Ciera. The J-body cars are the Buick Skyhawk,
Chevrolet Cavalier, Pontiac Sunbird, Cadillac Cimarron and
Oldsmobile Cutlass. The N-body cars are the Buick Skylark, Cutlass
Calais and Pontiac Grand Am.
   The cars use the same brake components, NHTSA said.
   The agency also raised to an engineering analysis its
investigation of allegations that the doors of GM's 1987 and 1988
Chevrolet Beretta and Corsica sometimes fall off when opened due to
defective door-hinge pins.
   NHTSA said 540,000 vehicles were involved in the investigation.
The agency had received 277 unconfirmed reports of doors falling
off, eight of which allegedly involved injury.
   In the third GM case, NHTSA upgraded its probe of power-steering
problems on the 1987 Pontiac Firebird and Chevrolet Camaro cars.
   The agency said it had received 403 unconfirmed complaints,
including five accidents and one injury, that brackets and bolts
suddenly fractured, causing a loss of power-steering assistance.
   GM declined to give a detailed response to each case.
   ``As always, we'll cooperate with NHTSA,'' GM spokesman John
Anderson said in Washington. ``However, just because there is an
investigation, it does not mean there are any defects present.''
   Asked if the upgrading of an investigation would suggest the
presence of a defect, Anderson said the company would stand by its
statement.
   NHTSA also opened five low-level investigations into safety
allegations involving cars.
   The agency opened preliminary evaluations into allegations of:
   _Seat belt jamming in 50,000 1987-1988 Mercury Tracers made by
Ford Motor Co.
   _Rear-window stop light failure in 1.2 million 1988 GM A- and
J-body 2-door coupes and sedans.
   _Brake light failure on 2,500 Rolls Royce cars made from 1987
through 1989.
   _Sudden movement of the front seat in 150,000 1983-1986 Subarus.
   _Defective windshield wipers in 50,000 1986-1987 Yugos.
   The agency also closed six investigations with the conclusion
there was ``no defect trend.''
   The cases involved unsubstantiated complaints of:
   _Seat-belt latch failure in the 1984 Ford Mustang.
   _Engine compartment fires in the 1980-1988 Ford Crown Victoria.
   _Trunk fires in the 1987-1988 Chrysler Corp. Dodge Daytona.
   _Oil leaks in the 1984 Subaru GL.
   _Battery cable grounding problems in the 1988 Saab 900 Turbo.
   _Front seat-back failure in the 1981 Ford Escort and Mustang.
</TEXT>
