<FIRST>r f PM-Mexico-StockScandal     02-16 0489</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mexico-Stock Scandal,0506</SECOND>
<HEAD>Principal in Brokerage Firm Says He's Innocent</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALMA VARGAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The founder of Mexico's largest brokerage firm
has declared his innocence on charges of illegal trading and
criminal fraud following his arraignment at a Mexico City prison.
   ``I hope there will be justice. I'm innocent. I believe in the
Mexican laws,'' said Eduardo Legoretta, board chairman and a founder
of Operadora de Bolsa, after being arraigned Wednesday at the city's
Eastern Penitentiary.
   Legoretta and three other top stock brokerage officials were
arrested on Monday and later charged with illegal trading related to
the October 1987 Mexican stock market crash.
   National Securities Commission president Oscar Espinoza Villareal
said no officials of the former presidential administration would be
investigated in connection with the crash, the Notimex news agency
reported.
   A government investigation continues into complaints against
nearly all Mexico's brokerage houses after stockholders lost about
$7 million in the crash.
   The government has said it may seek arrests or sanctions against
another 148 stockbrokers. The fraud complaints surfaced after
Mexico's market index plummeted 74 percent in 28 trading days in
October 1987.
   Legoretta, 44, belongs to one of Mexico's wealthiest families.
His arrest at a Mexico City restaurant Monday night shook the
country'sbusiness community.
   Legoretta told reporters the charges were motivated by what he
claimed were exaggerated and false reports of his personal wealth.
   ``I'm not very rich, I'm not as rich as they're saying. I have
two houses, three cars, and own 30 percent of a yacht. And I earn as
a stockbroker 20 million pesos a month (roughly $8,700),'' he said.
   Also charged were Jaime Ceballos Cervantes, Operadora's director
of investment promotions, and Juan Carlos Fernandez Cuevo and Jose
Francisco Rodriguez Dupont of Mexicana de Valores e Inversiones,
another major brokerage house.
   Attorney General Enrique Alvarez del Castillo on Tuesday said
Operadora de Bolsa allegedly sold non-existent Treasury certificates
and falsified clients' trading records. Mexicana de Valores
allegedly traded in securities without clients' consent, he said.
   Convictions on the charges could result in jail terms of up to 12
years for criminal fraud and 10 years for securities trading
violations.
   Espinoza said the 18-month government investigation did not
unearth wrongdoing by officials of the administration of former
President Miguel de la Madrid, Notimex reported. New President
Carlos Salinas de Gortari took office in December.
   Several opposition congressmen have called for Gustavo
Petricioli, the former treasury secretary and current ambassador to
Washington, to testify about the government's role in the crash.
   Del Castillo on Tuesday did not say how much money was involved.
But Gustavo Diaz, president of a group of investors who say they
were defrauded, estimated the brokerage firms netted $43.5 million
in profits from alleged illegal trading.
   The penal court judge supervising the case had three days from
Wednesday's arraignment to determine whether the charges warrant
formal indictments or to let the four officials go free.
</TEXT>
