<FIRST>r f PM-Ames-G.C.Murphy     02-16 0253</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ames-G.C.Murphy,0264</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Groups Interested In Buying Ames' G.C. Murphy Division</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four years after it acquired G.C. Murphy Co. in
a $200 million takeover battle, Ames Department Stores Inc. is
considering offers to sell the McKeesport-based discount store chain.
   Ames' spokeswoman Catherine Leonard said the Connecticut-based
retailer is entertaining offers for the division from a G.C. Murphy
management group and McCrory Corp. of York, Pa.
   Garry Brown, general manager of G.C. Murphy's headquarters who is
leading the employee bid, said the management buyout group's bid had
been submitted to Wertheim Schroder, the New York firm that serves
as Ames' investment banker.
   ``The proposal is on their desk,'' Brown said Wednesday.
   He said the bid is for all of the division's stores, including
about 137 units operated under the Murphy variety store banner. Also
included are 25 Bargain World stores and six Office Shop Warehouse
units.
   Brown said the acquisition, if completed, would take the form of
a leveraged buyout, in which a company's own earnings or assets are
used as collateral for loans needed to purchase it.
   McCrory, operator of 1,300 McCrory's general merchandise stores,
has also expressed interest in G.C. Murphy, Leonard said. She
declined to say whether its interest encompassed the entire division.
   A spokesman for McCrory's could not confirm the interest or
whether a formal bid had been submitted.
   It also was unclear whether Ames, which also recently acquired
Zayre's 388-store discount retail chain for $775 million, solicited
offers for G.C. Murphy or merely fielded them.
</TEXT>
