<FIRST>r f BC-BritainStocks     02-16 0225</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Britain Stocks,0232</SECOND>
<HEAD>London Shares Near Low At Midday</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices were lower at midday Thursday,
pressured by continuing fears about the world interest rate outlook
and some large sell-orders organized by British brokerage firms.
   Attention was fixed on Friday's release of Britain's retail price
index for January, which was expected to show that the annual
inflation rate rose above 7 percent last month, dealers said.
   The West German Bundesbank council's decision to leave its key
interest rate unchanged at 6 percent at its fortnightly meeting
Thursday didn't soothe the London market's concerns about a general
rise in world interest rates, said Kevin Gardiner, an analyst at the
London investment firm Warburg Securities.
   Most market participants believe the Bundesbank has merely
postponed an expected half percentage point rate rise, Gardiner
added.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index was off 17.1
points, or 0.8 percent, at 2,030.4 at about 1 p.m. in London, having
traded as much as 18 points lower an hour earlier. The index fell
steadily from its morning high of 0.9 point up.
   Volume was 426.4 million shares compared with 225.4 million
shares at the same time Wednesday.
   Dealers said they saw little buying interest in the market during
the morning session. Several British brokerage firms organized sell
programs that pushed the leading blue chip stocks lower, they said.
