<FIRST>r f BC-BeefPrices     02-16 0239</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Beef Prices,0247</SECOND>
<HEAD>Beef Prices Rise during January</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Average retail beef prices across the nation rose 6
cents a pound over the last month, the Denver-based National
Cattlemen's Association said.
   Reporting on its monthly 19-city survey of supermarket beef
prices Wednesday, the association said the average price of five
cuts on Feb. 9 was $2.93 per pound, up from $2.87 per pound on Jan.
12.
   There apparently was less retail featuring _ or special pricing _
of beef and more efforts to market cheaper meats, which are in large
supply, said the association, which noted beef production has
decreased recently.
   Compared with a month earlier, the February five-cut average was
up in 12 cities and down in seven.
   The price average also was affected by a long-term trend of
higher demand and higher prices for the more convenient beef steaks
and a somewhat lower demand for the less convenient cuts like chuck
roast, the association said.
   Over the last month, the national average ground beef price was
unchanged at $1.42 and chuck roast rose only slightly to $1.88.
Other averages were round steak, $2.71; sirloin steak, $3.57; and
T-bone steak, $5.08.
   The individual city averages for the five cuts ranged from $3.75
per pound in New York to $2.37 in San Francisco, with the highest
individual cut price $6.32 per pound for T-bone steak in Baltimore
and the lowest $1.11 for ground beef in Denver.
</TEXT>
