<DOCNO> AP890216-0248 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-16-89 1012EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-BritishPetroleum     02-16 0305</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-British Petroleum,0316</SECOND>
<HEAD>BP Posts 5 Percent Profit Gain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British Petroleum Co. PLC said Thursday its
after-tax profit rose 5 percent in the fourth quarter from a year
earlier, its results constrained by low crude oil prices.
   For the three months ended Dec. 31, BP said its after-tax profit
totaled 272 million pounds, or about $481 million at current
exchange rates, on an historical cost basis compared with 260
million pounds in the same period a year earlier.
   The historical cost figure includes inventory losses or gains and
is comparable to the first in first out (FIFO) accounting method.
   On a current cost basis, which values the company's oil
inventories at existing prices and is more in line with the typical
American system of last in first out (LIFO), after-tax profit fell
23 percent to 304 million pounds, or the equivalent of $538 million,
from 394 million pounds in the year ago period.
   Earnings per share came to 4.5 pence, or about 8 cents, up
slightly from 4.4 pence. Fourth-quarter sales fell 9 percent to 6.4
billion pounds from 7 billion pounds in the 1987 period.
   Oil and gas exploration and production results suffered from weak
crude prices, despite the benefits of integrating Britoil PLC, which
BP acquired late in 1987, the oil giant said.
   BP's refining and marketing businesses provided a ``partial
hedge,'' helped by good demand for products and lower costs, the
company said.
   For all of 1988, after-tax profit fell 13 percent to 1.21 billion
pounds on an historical cost basis from 1.39 billion pounds in 1987.
   Current cost after-tax profit rose 10 percent to 1.44 billion
pounds from 1.31 billion pounds.
   Per-share earnings for the year declined to 20 pence from 24.9
pence. Sales in 1988 fell 8 percent to 25.9 billion pounds from 28.3
billion pounds.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
