<FIRST>r f BC-Venezuela-Economy     02-16 0131</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Venezuela-Economy,0137</SECOND>
<HEAD>Venezuela Launching Economic Adjustment Plan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Venezuela Thursday geared up for sharp
economic adjustments, including a big devaluation of the bolivar.
   Venezuelan president Carlos Andres Peerez, who took office two
weeks ago, is scheduled to address the nation to outline a package
of adjustments Thursday evening.
   The Venezuelan economy has been badly hit in recent years with
the slide in oil prices and the service of its $33 billion debt, the
fourth largest in the hemisphere.
   The economic reforms to be announced will include a currency
devaluation between 45 and 55 percent, according to government
sources.
   Other measures will include unification of an exchange system
blamed for draining the country's reserves the past several years,
liberation of bank interest rates, and elimination of price controls.
</TEXT>
