<FIRST>r f PM-Pennwalt-Centaur     02-16 0341</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pennwalt-Centaur,0354</SECOND>
<HEAD>Centaur Presses Ahead With Meeting Plans; Pennwalt Mum</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pennwalt Corp. chairman Edwin E. Tuttle won't
discuss his position on Centaur Partners' increased offer for the
company, while Centaur today announced it has scheduled a special
shareholders' meeting on the offer.
   The New York investment firm, in a statement, said it scheduled
the meeting for March 30 at Pennwalt's headquarters in Philadelphia.
   Pennwalt spokeswoman Sue Kinard said the company had no comment.
She also said no date had been set for a Pennwalt board meeting
where, according to Tuttle, the board will consider Centaur's latest
offer.
   Centaur on Tuesday raised its offer from $100 to $110 per share
for the chemical company. Its proposals to shareholders include
removing all members of the Pennwalt board and electing new
directors nominated by Centaur.
   ``It is obviously a higher price,'' Tuttle told The Philadelphia
Inquirer on Wednesday. ``What conclusions the board will come to
will have to wait for (a special board) meeting to take place.''
   He did not disclose a date for the meeting.
   Pennwalt's stock climbed Wednesday to $114.125, up $1 in trading
on the New York Stock Exchange.
   ``I think we have to consider any offer seriously,'' Tuttle said.
``And we considered the first one seriously. After that serious
consideration, we came up with a very firm conclusion that one, it
was not a bona fide offer and was highly conditional. Two, it was
certainly inadequate. And three, the Centaur people were not very
worthy.''
   Centaur, which has sought a shareholder meeting in the absence of
a meeting with the Pennwalt board, claims the partnership gained
enough support to have a shareholder meeting called.
   Pennwalt sought an injunction to block the meeting, but a federal
judge last week affirmed Centaur's right to have it called. The
company has filed an appeal.
   ``We have the financing,'' Centaur spokesman Jerry Seeman said.
``We are not investing in Pennwalt to destroy it. ... It is for the
shareholders to decide the merits of our offer. Not Mr. Tuttle
alone.''
</TEXT>
