<HEAD>Little Early Movement In Grain, Soybean Futures</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wheat futures prices opened mixed while other
grain and soybean futures were nearly unchanged in early trading
today on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   A pickup in export demand for U.S. wheat, including a purchase by
Algeria of 125,000 metric tons at subsidized prices, gave old-crop
wheat futures a boost at the opening bell.
   But forecasts for precipitation in some U.S. winter wheat areas
kept a lid on those gains and encouraged selling of new-crop wheat
contracts, analysts said.
   Corn and soybeans were little changed in early trading, defying
expectations that soybean futures prices would extend Wednesday's
gains.
   In early trading, wheat was 1\ cents lower to 1{ cents higher
with the contract for delivery in March at $4.26} a bushel; corn was
unchanged to \ cent lower with March at $2.71 a bushel; oats were
unchanged to } cent higher with March at $2.09 a bushel; soybeans
were unchanged to { cent lower with March at $7.38{ a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mixed in early trading on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange ahead of this afternoon's Agriculture
Department monthly report on the number of cattle on feedlots in the
seven largest cattle-producing states.
   Live cattle were unchanged to .38 cent higher with April at 75.55
cents a pound; feeder cattle were .05 cent lower to .03 cent higher
with March at 81.82 cents a pound; live hogs were .17 cent lower to
.05 cent higher with April at 42 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies
were .72 cent lower to .58 cent higher with March at 37.65 cents a
pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled mostly lower on Wednesday.
