<FILEID>AP-NR-02-16-89 1155EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Braniff-Labor     02-16 0368</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Braniff-Labor,0385</SECOND>
<HEAD>Union Rejects Braniff Contract Proposal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A tentative contract proposal from Braniff Inc. has
been rejected by the Teamsters union local representing company
employees, officials said today.
   The Braniff proposal, including some provisions for 11 percent
raises in the first year, was rejected by Teamsters local no. 19 by
a vote of 1,058 to 242, union officials said.
   Tom Burnette, local president, said about 70 percent of the
estimated 2,000 union members cast ballots in the election.
   Main opposition to the contract came in the way raises would be
phased in among workers with different experience levels, he said.
   Teamsters and Braniff officials said they would return to the
bargaining table. The contract, dating from 1983, became amendable
last Dec. 1.
   Voting began in late January after Braniff and union officials
said they had reached a tentative agreement.
   Braniff's baggage handlers, ticket and reservations agents and
clerical and office workers are represented by the Teamsters.
   Either the airline or the union, under the Federal Railway Labor
Act, can request federal mediation if the contract dispute isn't
resolved.
   Braniff was acquired by investors last summer, shifted most of
its flight operations to Kansas City and began trying to attract
more business travelers by increasing its daily departure schedules.
It recently ordered more than $2 billion worth of new airplanes.
   The airline announced last week that it will move its
headquarters from Dallas to Orlando, Fla., and expand support
facilities in Orlando and in Kansas City to the tune of $40 million
and 1,400 jobs in the next year.
   Braniff's labor costs average $1.15 per available seat mile, the
lowest of any large U.S. airline, according to the Department of
Transportation. By contrast, American Airlines' labor costs average
$2.64 per available seat mile.
   Braniff's Teamsters took pay cuts of about 30 percent after the
airline emerged from bankruptcy under new ownership in 1983.
   The airline also faces contract talks with the unions
representing pilots, flight attendants and dispatchers at Braniff.
Officials said all three contracts become amendable on March 1.
   Braniff has more than 4,000 employees, including 440 pilots.
   The Philadelphia-based investor group controlling Braniff is
CoreGroup, headed by Jeffrey R. Chodorow and Arthur Cohen.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890216-0255 </DOCNO>
