<FIRST>r f PM-ColemanBuyout     02-16 0357</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Coleman Buyout,0371</SECOND>
<HEAD>Coleman Shareholders Oppose Takeover Bid</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL BATES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WICHITA, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of Coleman Co. shareholders have
filed a lawsuit seeking to block the Coleman family from acquiring
the publicly held corporation.
   In the action filed Wednesday in Sedgwick County District Court,
the stockholders held the $64 per share offer made by the family was
not enough.
   Coleman closed at $71 Wednesday, up 87{ cents, on the New York
Stock Exchange as more than 672,00 shares changed hands. In early
trading today it was down 62{ cents to $70.37{.
   Some analysts said Wednesday there was nearly a $50 million gap
between what the stock was trading for and the Coleman family's
offer.
   The suit calls the offer ``grossly inadequate.''
   Fred Anschel, an analyst who follows Coleman for Dean Witter
Reynolds Inc., said such suits are routine.
   He also said it probably would take a week for other bidders for
the company to step forward, if there are going to be any.
   No date was set for a hearing in the suit filed by Airmont Plaza
Associates, Charles Miller, William Steiner and Katherine Reilly.
The petition asks that the lawsuit be declared a class action on
behalf of all Coleman stockholders. The attorney who filed it, Roger
Sherwood of Wichita, refused comment.
   ``We believe the suits to be without merit but can comment no
further, other than to say that such suits are common following an
announcement of a potential acquoisition of this type,'' said
Sheldon C. Coleman, company board chairman and the family member
leading the leveraged buyout bid.
   Sheldon C. Coleman announced Wednesday he had received bank
funding assurances for the $332 million leveraged buyout.
   He said Wednesday he and other family members have formed Chatham
Acquisition Corp. and retained Goldman Sachs &amp; Co. as financial
adviser.
   The company said Chatham has received a commitment letter from
First National Bank of Chicago for up to $415 million.
   A special committee of Coleman's board is considering the buyout
offer. The committee is made up of outside directors _ board members
who aren't Coleman family members or company officers.
</TEXT>
