<FIRST>r f BC-ControlData     02-16 0243</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Control Data,0251</SECOND>
<HEAD>Perlman Mulls Options to Stop Control Data Losses</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BLOOMINGTON, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawrence Perlman, president and chief
operating officer of Control Data Corp., says he has ``not ruled out
any options'' for cutting the company's losses, including the sale
of part or all of the computer business.
   But Perlman said Wednesday that options under consideration also
include seeking equity partners to help turn around the computer
business, which had operating losses of about $130 million last year.
   His comments came in response to a question during an interview
about widespread rumors that Control Data is about to sell its
computer operations. Unisys Corp. has been mentioned most often as
the buyer.
   ``It's too early to tell if we have to sell portions of the
computer business,'' said Perlman, dismissing published reports that
Unisys representatives recently visited the St. Paul assembly plant
of Control Data's ETA supercomputer subsidiary.
   ``We have Unisys and every other (computer) manufacturer visiting
ETA,'' said Perlman, who was named to his current posts in December.
``We're trying to sell them on ETA as a compatible supercomputer
with their mainframes.''
   Perlman would prefer to keep the computer business more or less
intact, but he acknowledged that there's ``no question that one of
the ways to help make computers profitable is to find the right kind
of partner.
   ``We don't have to own all of ETA or the Cyber group (Control
Data's mainframe computer business) for that matter.''
</TEXT>
