<FIRST>u f BC-BritishStocks 1stLd-Writethru   02-16 0227</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-British Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru,0233</SECOND>
<HEAD>London Shares Close Lower</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES with close</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices fell Thursday amid continued concern
about the outlook for world interest rates as traders sat back to
await Friday's release of British inflation figures.
   The Financial Times 30-share index was down 10.2 points at
1,667.2 at the close. The Financial Times 500-share index fell 5.53
points to close at 1,153.57.
   Volume rose to 644.1 million shares from Wednesday's 468.5
million shares, but much of this gain was said to come from program
trades.
   Prices were hit early as several British brokerage firms
conducted large program trades, dealers said. But a mostly apathetic
market failed to reignite much movement upward from depressed levels.
   ``The (program trades) took the fire out of the market,'' one
dealer said.
   There wasn't any noticeable relief after the West German
Bundesbank failed to raise interest rates at a meeting Thursday, as
many players had expected. Instead, it merely perpetuated the
market's uncertainty about whether worldwide rates were headed
higher, dealers said.
   ``The feeling is that the U.S. will increase their rates
anyway,'' said one equity salesman.
   Players eagerly awaited Friday's release of Britain's retail
price index, which could bear on the outlook for British rates. The
annual inflation rate is expected to have risen to 7.3 percent in
January from 6.8 percent in December.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
