<FILEID>AP-NR-02-16-89 1332EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-BritishAerospace     02-16 0214</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-British Aerospace,0221</SECOND>
<HEAD>British Aerospace Subsidiary to Cut 2,500 Jobs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British Aerospace (Dynamics) Ltd., a guided weapons
manufacturing subsidiary of British Aerospace PLC, will cut 2,500
jobs by the end of the 1990s and close two of its six major sites,
the company said Thursday.
   British Aerospace said an internal review had concluded that the
cuts in its workforce of 13,500 and the shutting down of some sites
were necessary to improve efficiency.
   ``We currently have a wasteful duplication of facilities and
resources which, when consolidated and rationalized, will improve
utilization and efficiency,'' the company said in a statement.
   ``The measures we are taking are designed solely to protect our
(guided weapons) business over the next decade and beyond,'' said
British Aerospace Chairman Richard Evans in a brief separate
statement.
   A union representing workers at the London-based company, the
Manufacturing, Science and Finance Union, described the planned job
cuts as an ``outrage.''
   The British Aerospace statement said the company would ``consult
and discuss with employees and their representatives the various
methods'' of implementing the reductions.
   The company said it would close manufacturing sites at Bracknell,
northwest of London and Bolton in central England, as well as
closing a small guided weapons plant in Hatfield, on the northern
outskirts of London.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
