<DOCNO> AP890216-0264 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-16-89 1336EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-IBMChip     02-16 0195</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-IBM Chip,0202</SECOND>
<HEAD>IBM Reveals Fastest Memory Chip</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   International Business Machines Corp. on Thursday
unveiled what it called the world's fastest memory chip, one capable
of sending and receiving more than 6 billion bits of data per second.
   IBM said the static random access memory (SRAM) chip was for fast
machines such as mainframes and supercomputers that need to store
information in memory banks and retrieve it at high speeds.
   The chip was discussed in New York at the International Solid
State Circuits Conference, the world chip industry's biggest annual
research meeting. A day earlier, Intel Corp. unveiled what it called
the world's fastest microprocessor, the central control chip in a
computer.
   IBM said its chip can store 128,000 bits of information and has
features as small as half a micron across. One micron is
one-hundredth the width of a human hair.
   On Wednesday at the conference, Texas Instruments Inc. announced
an SRAM chip that is slightly slower but holds eight times as much
information.
   SRAM chips are faster but more expensive and have less capacity
than the more common memory chips known as dynamic random access
memories, or DRAMs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
