<FIRST>u f BC-Dollar-Gold     02-16 0388</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Dollar-Gold,0413</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Ends Higher in Europe, Gold Rises</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: AMs version expected by 5:30 p.m. EST.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar ended higher against major foreign
currencies Thursday but below its best levels in dull European
trading.
   Gold prices rose slightly.
   Foreign exchange dealers said the dollar climbed to around 1.8500
West German marks after the Bundesbank announced it would not be
raising its key interest rates amid expectations a rate hike would
be announced.
   But the market lacked the energy to push the dollar through the
1.8500-mark level, and the U.S. currency drifted back to its late
levels.
   ``People have chased the dollar higher and lower a few times this
week and are obviously tired of it,'' said one dealer, who said the
market was awaiting the release of U.S. trade figures Friday.
   Dealers said trade figures released over the past few months
haven't had the same impact on the market as last year.
   But the dollar's inability to respond to any good news this week,
together with the fact that the long-awaited hike in the U.S.
discount rate has failed to materialize, may mean the trade figures
will have an exaggerated impact on the dollar.
   Economists are expecting a U.S. December deficit of $11.7
billion, narrower than November's $12.5 billion gap.
   In London, the dollar gained against the British pound. It cost
$1.7712 to buy one pound, cheaper than $1.7805 Wednesday.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Wednesday:
   _1.8425 West German marks, up from 1.8315
   _1.5643 Swiss francs, up from 1.5565
   _6.2725 French francs, up from 6.2425
   _2.0790 Dutch guilders, up from 2.0680
   _1,348.50 Italian lire, up from 1,339.50
   _1.1859 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1800
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar rose 0.43 yen to a closing 126.33 yen. Later, in London,
it was quoted at 126.33 yen.
   Gold rose in London to a late bid price of $382.25 a troy ounce,
compared with $382.00 bid late Wednesday.
   In Zurich, gold was higher, closing at a bid $382.50 compared
with $381.60 bid late Wednesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose 54 cents to close at a bid
$385.20.
   Silver bullion prices rose on the London market where the metal
was trading at a late bid price of $5.84 a troy ounce, compared with
Wednesday's $5.79.
</TEXT>
