<FIRST>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   02-16 0239</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0250</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wheat, Soybeans Plunge In Late Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wheat and soybean futures prices closed sharply
lower Thursday on the Chicago Board of Trade amid a flurry of late
sell orders linked to bearish supply-and-demand factors.
   Corn and oat futures also retreated.
   Wheat market led the decline, with much of the selling sparked by
news that a sale of 1.5 million metric tons of French wheat to the
Soviet Union was expected to proceed smoothly.
   The report disappointed market bulls who had recently bid up
wheat prices on indications that some European grain producers were
running into logistical problems in meeting their sale commitments
to the Soviets.
   ``This latest announcement about the French ... puts an end to
that speculation,'' said Ted Mao, an analyst in New York with
Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
   New studies showing less cold-weather damage to the U.S. winter
wheat crop than many had expected also weighed on the wheat market.
   Reports of improved soybean-growing conditions in South America
contributed to the soybean market's decline.
   At the close, wheat was 2\ cents to 9 cents lower with the
contract for delivery in March at $4.23 a bushel; corn was } cent to
2} cents lower with March at $2.68{ a bushel; oats were 3\ cents to
4\ cents lower with March at $2.04\ a bushel; soybeans were 3{ cents
to 10{ cents lower with March at $7.28 a bushel.
</TEXT>
