<FILEID>AP-NR-02-16-89 1640EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Posner-Homeless     02-16 0414</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Posner-Homeless,0429</SECOND>
<HEAD>Convicted Industrialist Announces Fund-Raiser</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TRACY FIELDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Millionaire industrialist Victor Posner,
sentenced to help the homeless instead of going to jail for tax
evasion, on Thursday announced a program by one of his companies to
raise money for the homeless.
   Posner refused to say whether the Royal Crown Cola Co. drive is
related to his tax case, in which he was ordered to give $3 million
to aid the homeless in Florida. An RC executive said the two were
not connected.
   ``We all know this problem exists and discussing it further won't
help to alleviate the sorrow and waste connected with this national
blight, nor will it create shelter or provide food,'' Posner said,
reading from a prepared statement at a news conference.
   Posner, 69, pleaded no contest last year to evading $1.2 million
in federal income taxes by fraudulently inflating the value of land
he donated to a college in the 1970s.
   A federal judge fined Posner $4 million in fines and ordered him
to give $3 million to help Florida's homeless, with the stipulation
that the money not be tax-deductible. The judge appointed a
committee of civic leaders to determine how the money would be spent
for the homeless in Florida.
   ``This is an RC campaign and has nothing to do with Mr. Posner,''
said Carey Keane, vice president of marketing for the cola company,
of which Posner is chairman.
   Keane said the company hopes to raise $1 million, and other
corporations have been invited to join the effort.
   RC said it will donate a portion of the proceeds from sales of
its soft drinks to help the homeless through local organizations.
The money will come from sales in 14 markets around the country.
   Buyers of Royal Crown products in other markets will not be
contributing to the campaign, which ends April 30.
   The cities involved are Miami, New York, Chicago, Philadelphia,
Tucson and Phoenix, Ariz., St. Paul-Minneapolis, Washington, D.C.,
Nashville, Tenn., Los Angeles, Pittsburgh, Boston, Detroit and San
Diego.
   Posner, who controls a 40-company empire valued at $4 billion,
last September was named in a Securities and Exchange Commission
civil complaint against the investment firm Drexel Burnham Lambert
Inc., which has agreed to pay a record $650 million to settle
criminal charges of securities fraud.
   Posner and his son, Stephen, were accused of shady dealings with
now-jailed Wall Street speculator Ivan Boesky in a takeover deal.
The complaint is pending.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890216-0271 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-16-89 1649EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Earns-Retail     02-16 0330</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Earns-Retail,0345</SECOND>
<HEAD>J.C. Penney's Income Up 55 Percent in Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   J.C. Penney Co. Thursday reported a 55 percent
profit boost for the fourth quarter, aided by a gain from the sale
of the company's former headquarters building and better margins.
   A reduction in promotional activity and declining interest
expense also benefited the big retailer's balance sheet.
   For the 13 weeks ended Jan. 28, after-tax income came to $435
million, or $3.28 per share, compared with $280 million, or $1.93 a
share, for the corresponding quarter a year earlier.
   The earnings included a $139 million gain, after taxes, from the
sale of the company's former headquarters building in New York City.
   Total revenue, including store sales and revenue from its
insurance and realty operations, was $4.95 billionin the company's
fourth quarter, up from $5.05 billion
   Profit for all of 1988 rose 32.7 percent to $807 million, or
$6.02 per share, compared with $608 million, or $4.11 per share, for
the previous year. Revenue for the year amounted to $15.30 billion,
a 2.9 percent dip from 1987's $15.75 billion.
   As of Jan. 28, the company had purchased 8 million shares of
common stock at a cost of $418 million as part of a stock buyback
program of up to 15 million shares authorized this year.
   ``The company is well positioned to respond to consumer buying
patterns in J.C. Penney stores and (the) catalog,'' said company
chairman William R. Howell.
   ``The expansion of women's apparel offerings and the continued
strengthening of men's and children's apparel and home@leisure
merchandise will result in significant opportunities for J.C.
Penney,'' he said.
   In February, the company announced discussions were under way
with several major insurance companies for the sale of personal
lines operations of J.C. Penney Casualty Insurance Co.
   Penney will not have any significant gain or loss in exiting the
casualty insurance business. The company will continue to operate
the J.C. Penney Life Insurance Co., offering life, health and credit
insurance coverage.
</TEXT>
