<FILEID>AP-NR-02-16-89 1738EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-DefenseContractReports     02-16 0253</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Defense Contract Reports,0262</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pentagon to Raise Dollar Standard for Reporting Contracts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Defense Department, citing the effects of
inflation over the past decade, said Thursday it would soon raise
its dollar standard for reporting contracts to the public and
Congress.
   Effective March 1, the Pentagon said its daily listing of
contract awards would be restricted to contracts worth $5 million or
more.
   The current contract-reporting level is $3 million and was
established in 1978.
   ``The inflation-based adjustment, up from the current $3 million
announcement threshold, is the first to be made in almost 11
years,'' the Pentagon said.
   ``Consequently, the number of contract actions requiring
notification has increased significantly. As a result of inflation
over the intervening years, a contract valued at $3 million in 1978
is now equivalent to a $5.6 million contract today.''
   The Pentagon said the change would have no effect on the manner
in which contracts are awarded or on the number of contracts
awarded. The new standard will keep manageable the contract lists
printed every day for distribution to the media, public and
Congress, the Pentagon said.
   As is the case now, any contract awarded by a defense agency or
service that falls below the threshhold will be publicly announced,
but not on the day of award as happens with the larger contracts.
   Smaller contracts are normally disclosed after a lag of a week or
so in the government publication Commerce Business Daily.
   The Defense Department awards roughly 15 million contracts every
year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890216-0275 </DOCNO>
