<FILEID>AP-NR-02-16-89 1935EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-WrongS&amp;L     02-16 0492</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wrong S&amp;L,0514</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wrong TV Picture Prompts Flood of Calls to Healthy S&amp;L</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARIO FOX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A television news story about troubled savings and
loan associations used film footage of a healthy local S&amp;L,
prompting a flurry of calls from worried depositors, officials said
Thursday.
   ``We got a flood of phone calls, at least two dozen,'' said Jack
Lloyd, a vice president of Savings of America.
   CBS-owned WBBM-TV mentioned debt-ridden First Savings of America
in Orland Park in a report on the Channel 2 News at 5 p.m. Wednesday.
   But the videotape footage showed Savings of America, which is on
the same street in the southwest suburb.
   ``We told the right story and showed the wrong picture. We made a
mistake and we regret it,'' Colleen Dudgeon, WBBM-TV news director
said Thursday.
   ``We ran a correction last night at 10 o'clock and will again at
5 today,'' she said.
   Not only is Savings of America financially healthy, its parent
company, Irwindale, Calif.-based Home Savings of America, has assets
of more than $40 billion, said Lloyd.
   Savings of America received ``a lot of curious calls,'' said
Lloyd. ``The report was at 5 o'clock and we were open another two
hours.''
   Worried callers were told there had been a mistake.
   ``Some heard the other name and were confused because the names
are very close. We tried to allay fears, and those that needed more
convincing were given appointments,'' Lloyd said.
   The S&amp;L chain then braced for a period of reassurances.
   ``We had to mobilize overnight. The executives of the 17 branches
in the Chicago area got together by phone,'' he said. ``We wanted to
address the financial information right away.''
   Anxious depositors coming in Thursday were shown a video of
WBBM's retraction.
   They also were given the S&amp;L's financial reports and copies of
favorable newspaper articles _ including one in USA Today that
quoted a stock analyst as saying Home Savings was the best-managed
thift in the nation, Lloyd said.
   Ms. Dudgeon would not elaborate on how WBBM's error occurred, but
said no disciplinary action was planned.
   Lloyd characterized the television report as ``totally
irresponsible,'' but said that ``at this point, I think no legal
action is going to be necessary.''
   The mix-up could even be a plus for Savings of America, he said.
   ``It will let us show pople how big and how strong we are,''
Lloyd said.
   Five Chicago-area savings and loan associations are on a national
list of financially ailing institutions ripe for takeover by the
Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. under President Bush's plan to
resolve the crisis in the S&amp;L industry.
   Besides First Savings, insolvent thrifts in the Chicago area are:
Concordia Federal Bank for Savings, Lansing; Libertyville Federal
Savings; American Security Federal Savings, Chicago; and Home
Federal Savings, Joliet.
   All depositors at these S&amp;Ls will continue to be insured up to
$100,000 and have normal access to their accounts, FDIC officials
say.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
