<FIRST>u f AM-WallStreet 1stLd-Writethru   02-16 0478</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wall Street, 1st Ld-Writethru,0498</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates with closing prices throughout.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices nudged ahead Thursday as traders
awaited the monthly report Friday on the nation's international
trade position.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 7.50 to 2,311.43, on
top of a 22.68-point gain Wednesday.
   Advancing issues outnumbered declines by more than 4 to 3 in
nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with
816 up, 591 down and 553 unchanged.
   Volume on the floor of the Big Board came to 177.45 million
shares, up from 154.22 million in the previous session. Nationwide,
consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including trades in those
stocks on regional exchanges and in the over-the-counter market,
totaled 207.84 million shares.
   The dollar rose against leading overseas currencies in early
foreign-exchange trading.
   That helped prompt a slight increase in bond prices, and decline
in interest rates, in the domestic credit markets.
   But buying interest in the dollar, bonds and stocks waned a bit
as the session passed, apparently because of worries about the
monthly trade report due out Friday.
   Wall Street economists generally expect the figures to show about
a $12 billion trade deficit for December, compared with the $12.5
billion gap between imports and exports previously reported for
November.
   Church's Fried Chicken climbed 1\ to 10\ in active trading. The
company agreed to be acquired by A. Copeland Enterprises for $11 a
share in cash and securities.
   Merck rose 1 to 64} following word that researchers at the
company have found what they describe as a promising approach toward
combating the virus that causes AIDS.
   Other gainers among the blue chips included Philip Morris, up 2\
at 110}; DuPont, up [ at 97~; Procter &amp; Gamble, up { at 91[; Eastman
Kodak, up \ at 47|, and Coca-Cola, up ] at 48.
   Coca-Cola raised its quarterly dividend from 30 cents a share to
34 cents a share.
   Bank of New York rose | to 42, hitting a 52-week high. The
company said it expects annual earnings growth of 15 percent to 20
percent through 1991, somewhat more than its historical targets.
   Navistar International held steady at 6[. The company posted
profits for its fiscal first quarter ended Dec. 31 of 12 cents a
share, against 15 cents a share in the comparable period a year
earlier.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the market increased $6.29 billion, or 0.22
percent, in value.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks gained
.30 to 165.51.
   Standard &amp; Poor's industrial index rose .61 to 340.45, and S&amp;P's
500-stock composite index was up .57 at 294.81.
   The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market picked
up 1.53 to 405.70. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index closed at 325.15, up .13.
