<FILEID>AP-NR-02-16-89 2001EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-HughesLawsuit     02-16 0521</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hughes Lawsuit,0540</SECOND>
<HEAD>Legal Mistake Hampers Patent Claim Against Government</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An apparent oversight in drafting a legal
settlement could cost Hughes Aircraft Co. $270 million in potential
damage payments from the federal government in a long-running patent
infringement suit, a published report said Thursday.
   The error was identified in a ruling by U.S. Claims Court Judge
William Turner, who said Hughes' lawyers made a mistake in a 1987
out-of-court settlement in a related patent case.
   The ruling, issued Sept. 29, was published recently in U.S.
Patent Quarterly. It was first reported in the general news media
Thursday in the Los Angeles Times.
   The case involves an 18-year-long patent infringement case
pursued by Hughes, now a subsidiary of General Motors Corp.,
involving a device used to control orbiting satellites. Hughes
maintains the device made the modern communications satellite
network possible and claims the government used the device on 108
satellites without paying royalties.
   In the case, which presently is in the penalty-setting phase,
Hughes seeks $3.16 billion in damages, based on 15 percent royalties
plus compensation for delay in payment.
   Turner's ruling released the government from liability connected
with 13 government satellites built by Ford Aerospace, a unit of
Ford Motor Co. which Hughes sued for infringement of the same patent.
   The ruling was based on wording of a September 1987 settlement of
the Hughes suit against Ford that absolves Ford customers from
further liability, the Times said. The government was a Ford
customer.
   Turner said Hughes could have prevented the exclusion of the 13
satellites from the total by adding ``except the United States''
after the wording releasing Ford customers from liability.
   Ford agreed to pay Hughes $75 million in the 1987 settlement, the
Times said, quoting unidentified sources.
   John Walker, managing partner at Latham &amp; Watkins, the law firm
representing Hughes in the case, denied the Los Angeles firm erred
in drafting the settlement.
   ``Everything I know is that we didn't make a mistake at all in
the case,'' Walker told the Times.
   Hughes officials refused to comment because the matter concerned
litigation, according to Mike Murphy, a spokesman at the company's
corporate headquarters, said Thursday.
   The company has asked the judge to reconsider the ruling.
   Hughes values its royalties and penalties on the 13 satellites in
the disputed ruling at $270 million, but the government puts the
potential payment to the company at $50 million, the Times reported,
citing secret court filings.
   The patented device was invented in the early 1960s by Donald
Williams, a Hughes engineer.
   The device allows a single small rocket motor to control the
orbit of a spinning satellite by employing gyroscopic principles.
Hughes claims the invention made possible the creation of practical
communicatins satellites, today a multibillion-dollar industry.
   The government contends Hughes has overblown its claims and that
it doesn't possess a valid patent.
   In two previous stages of the case, federal courts have held the
Los Angeles-based aerospace company has a valid claim to a patent on
the device and that the government infringed on that patent. The
present phase is to set the penalty against the government.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
