<FIRST>r f AM-YugoBankruptcy     02-16 0301</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Yugo Bankruptcy,0312</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bankruptcy Court Judge Reserves Decision In Yugo Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL J. WAKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bankruptcy court judge Thursday delayed a
decision on whether to allow an Ohio liquidator to sell 4,700 of
Yugo America Inc.'s unsold cars, nearly a third of the stock of the
bankrupt Yugoslav carmaker.
   Impex Car Corp., the American agent for Yugo, and the liquidator,
Norauto Ltd of Columbus, Ohio, battled this week over control of the
autos.
   Yugo and Impex argue that a deal last fall with Norauto
represented a financing arrangement to bail out the financially
ailing company. Norauto insists it bought the cars outright and
should be allowed to sell them.
   Company officials claim that unloading the autos at
below-wholesale prices without warranties would destroy the market
for Yugos.
   Yugo, based in Upper Saddle River, on Jan. 30 filed for
protection under Chapter 11 of federal bankruptcy laws.
   U.S. Bankruptcy Court Judge Vincent J. Commisa has temporarily
barred the sale of the cars. He said he would rule next week on
whether the ban should continue after boths sides present further
court papers.
   The prospects of reorganizing Yugo would be ``very likely
eliminated'' if the restraint was lifted, Impex attorney Robert A.
Baime said in final remarks Thursday.
   Yugo's acting chief executive, Marcel Kole, testified that
Norauto extended credit to Yugo with the cars as collateral and
granted Yugo a buyback option.
   Norauto attorney Roy E. Scheider argued the deal also was between
the liquidator and the car's manufacturer, Zavodi Crevna Zastava,
which was called the ``seller'' in the contract for the cars.
   The 4,700 autos in question are among 6,000 Yugos at American
ports. Manufacturers Hanover Trust Co. has a lien on the other cars.
Yugo's 260 dealers nationwide have about 9,500 cars.
</TEXT>
