<FIRST>u f AM-Lufthansa-Airbus     02-16 0221</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lufthansa-Airbus,0233</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lufthansa To Buy Up To 30 Planes In $3 Billion Deal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lufthansa German Airlines has agreed to buy up
to 30 commerical aircraft from Airbus Industrie, a European
consortium, in an estimated $3 billion deal, Airbus officials said
Thursday.
   The order gives another boost to the commercial jet industry.
Earlier this month, American Airlines signed a 142-plane, estimated
$7 billion deal with McDonnell Douglas Corp.
   Lufthansa plans to use the new plans to replace uts fleet of
DC10-30 aircraft, enabling the airline to offer most nonstop routes
from West Germany to the United States, South America and the Far
East, Airbus said.
   The contract, signed Wednesday, calls for Lufthansa to buy 15
Airbus A340 aircraft for delivery between September 1992 and March
1994.
   Lufthansa will receive both A4340-200s, which seat 222
passengers, and A340-300s, which have 256-seat cabins. Both versions
are powered by CFM International CFM56-5C-2 engines.
   According to the contract, Lufthansa will decide later on whether
to purchase 15 more planes.
   With the Lufthansa order, Airbus now has firm orders, options and
commitments for 110 A340 aircraft, the consortium said.
   Last year, $48.5 billion in new planes were ordered, the highest
total ever. Industry officials estimate that the demand to replace
aging aircraft could push annual sales to $450 billion by the year
2005.
</TEXT>
