<HEAD>Dollar Mixed; Gold Falls</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON-BC</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar dipped against several major
currencies but rose against the British pound and Canadian dollar on
Thursday in advance of Friday's release of U.S. trade figures.
   Most economists were expecting the merchandise trade deficit for
December to be slightly below the November figure of $12.5 billion.
   Foreign exchange dealers said the dollar climbed to around 1.85
West German marks after the West German central bank announced it
would not be raising its key interest rates, following expectations
a rate hike would be announced. The rally failed to last.
   ``People have chased the dollar higher and lower a few times this
week and are obviously tired of it,'' one dealer in Europe said.
   In London, the British pound fell to $1.7712 from $1.7805 late
Wednesday. Later in New York, sterling fell to $1.7720 from $1.7743
late Wednesday.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar rose 0.43 yen to a closing 126.33 yen. Later in London,
the dollar was quoted at 126.33 yen. In New York, the dollar edged
down to 126.11 yen from 126.13 yen late Wednesday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late
Wednesday's rates, included: 1.8388 West German marks, down from
1.8405; 1.5601 Swiss francs, down from 1.5623; 1.1867 Canadian
dollars, up from 1.1796; 6.2600 French francs, down from 6.2658; and
1,344.3 Italian lire, down from 1,349.00.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Wednesday,
included: 1.8425 West German marks, up from 1.8315; 1.5643 Swiss
francs, up from 1.5565; 6.2725 French francs, up from 6.2425; 2.0790
Dutch guilders, up from 2.0680; 1,348.50 Italian lire, up from
1,339.50; and 1.1859 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1800.
   Gold rose in London to a late bid of $382.25 a troy ounce,
compared with $382.00 bid late Wednesday. In Zurich, gold closed at
$382.50 an ounce compared with $381.60 bid late Wednesday.
   Earlier in Hong Kong, gold rose 54 cents to close at a bid of
$385.20 a troy ounce.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold bullion for current
delivery fell to $383.60 a troy ounce from $384.60. Later, Republic
National Bank of New York quoted gold at $382.75 an ounce as of 4
p.m. EST compared with $383.60 late Wednesday.
   Silver bullion prices rose on the London market to a late bid of
$5.84 a troy ounce, compared with late Wednesday's $5.79. On New
York's Comex, silver for current delivery fell to $5.883 an ounce
from $5.890.
