<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     02-16 0290</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Energy Futures Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Crude oil futures prices rose on Thursday, buoyed
by a combination of reports that included news of temporary
shutdowns of Norway's North Sea oil platforms.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the March contract for West
Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of U.S. crude, rose 8 cents
to settle at $18.33 a barrel. The contract jumped 83 cents in the
previous session. Other contract months had slightly higher gains.
   Among refined oil products, the March contract for heating oil
rose 0.91 cent to 49.65 cents a gallon. The gains were triggered by
a report that Algeria's national oil company was experiencing cargo
loading problems, said Randall Rothenberg, an oil broker with Dean
Witter Reynolds Inc.
   Unleaded gasoline for March delivery rose 0.28 cent to close at
49.05 cents a gallon.
   Crude oil prices had hovered in the $17 range for several weeks,
but surged Wednesday as investors anticipated a positive outcome
from next week's meeting of non-OPEC oil producers.
   Thursday's rally began after a report of a temporary production
disruption at two of Norway's North Sea Stratfjord oilfield
platforms. A report that Saudi Arabia had cut March contract volumes
to its Japan customers by 15 percent triggered more buying later in
the day, Rothenberg said.
   Nauman Barakat, an international energy analyst with
Prudential-Bache Securities Inc., said investors are remaining
optimistic ahead of next week's meeting of non-OPEC producers in
London.
   During a visit Thursday to Oklahoma City, Saudi oil minister
Hisham Nazer said he expects the meeting to produce an agreement
that could help to further stabilize oil prices.
   Nazer's remarks came after the close of trading but Barakat said
they could have a follow-through effect on Friday's market.
</TEXT>
