<FILEID>AP-NR-02-16-89 2027EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Norway-Economy     02-16 0422</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Norway-Economy,0436</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Bank Chief Says Norway's Oil Binge Is Over</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUG MELLGREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OSLO, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Spending is down, unemployment and
bankruptcies are up, and Norway's oil-based economy is still
recovering from the morning-after effects of a 15-year binge, the
head of the central bank said Thursday.
   Tough government measures last year made headway in limiting
wages, trimming inflation and swinging foreign trade into the black,
said Bank of Norway Director Hermod Skaanland.
   ``There are no easy solutions to the problems we are facing.
Fifteen years of speculation, oil boom and an ever-increasing
standard of living have put us where we are today,'' said Skaanland.
   Skaanland's address to the bank's steering committee coincided
with the publication of the 1988 balance sheet, which showed an
increase of 27.4 percent to 7.9 billion kronor, or about $1.18
billion. The bank transferred $1.12 billion to the state treasury.
   Skaanland said the end was near for Norway's era of petroleum
wealth, which began with the 1969 discovery of oil off its North Sea
coast. Production in 1989 is expected to average 1.44 million
barrels per day.
   ``We are already approaching the peak in our oil production,'' he
said. ``It will continue to increase for a few more years and then
begin to taper off in the late 1990s.''
   Skaanland urged the Labor government of Prime Minister Gro Harlem
Brundtland to continue the belt-tightening measures started after
oil prices collapsed in 1986.
   ``Last year, most of us began to feel the direct effect of
(Norway's) new economic reality. The feeling of job security is
lower than at any time since World War II,'' he said.
   Unemployment doubled last year to 4 percent of the work force,
the highest rate since the 1930s. During 1988, 3,494 companies filed
bankruptcy petitions, up 81 percent over 1987. Many of them were
forced out of business by high interest rates and a drop in private
consumption by 1.6 percent.
   He urged the government to continue keeping the lid on wages to
help Norway regain its international competitiveness. A wage limit
last year helped bring inflation down to 5.6 percent from 7 percent
in 1987. Foreign trade scored a 1988 surplus of $618 million.
   Norway's 1988 banking crisis cost banks more than $1.04 billion
in losses on loans, according to official estimates. Skaanland said
these losses were due to ``bad banking, bad policies and bad luck.''
   ``Even if banks show significant losses in 1989 as well, we
expect net results to show an improvement,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
