<FIRST>r f AM-ColaWars     02-16 0311</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cola Wars,0325</SECOND>
<HEAD>Coca-Cola Agrees to Make Changes in Diet Coke Ads</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soft drink giants Coca-Cola Co. and Pepsi-Cola
Co. each claimed Thursday they had been vindicated by the television
networks in their latest advertising spat.
   Coca-Cola said it agreed to make what it called ``two minor
alterations'' in its new ads that claim a ``move is on'' from
regular Pepsi to Diet Coke.
   The Atlanta-based company said the revised campaign would
continue to air on network television.
   ``Diet Coke wins again,'' the company said.
   But Pepsi-Cola, which had complained to the networks that the
Diet Coke spot was false and misleading, said the requested
alterations represented ``fundamental changes.''
   ``They called a foul against Coke ... We are overjoyed,'' said
Tod MacKenzie, a spokesman for Pepsi in Somers, N.Y.
   At the same time, Pepsi said it had voluntarily withdrawn its ad
that poked fun at how Coca-Cola came up with its claims, showing
executives poring over soft drink statistics while wearing
distorting 3D glasses.
   MacKenzie said its ad was aired only as an interim measure while
the networks reviewed its complaint abot the Diet Coke ads.
   In the original series of ads launched in late January, Coca-Cola
took the unusual step of positioning Diet Coke against the sugared
version of Pepsi.
   ``Last year, nearly two million families stopped buying Pepsi and
more of them moved to Diet Coke than any other major soft drink,''
the Diet Coke ads said.
   After a review by the networks, Coca-Cola said it agreed to
change the second part of its claim to say, ``... and about a half
million of them moved to Diet Coke.''
   Coca-Cola also agreed to indicate on the screen the name of the
research company that came up with the data supporting its claim and
note that it includes both Diet Coke and caffeine-free Diet Coke.
</TEXT>
